// Auto-generated full translations from manuscript reading
export const fullFolioTranslations: Record<string, { original: string; english: string }> = {
  "192r": {
    original: "Got der hymel unde erden / den un den erthen / aller geschepfe alse gewalt / geschuf so in der gotheit balt / drisse cleine unde gros / den louffen noch den willen blos / Thore unde blysse... / Allen den dy cristen sint / wir werhen grosz Sint / y is wir den namen eren / unde daz von sunden keren / do wolhor dut ou lone geben / der by duz eyn ewik seben / Wir sollen eine rede heben an / dy got der cristheit began / du hat dynartere gelert / do spit her an den dritten tage / unde losthe mache rede dy clage / yst du her von hymmen duz / za hymmel von der erde bluz / o sunghe her syny heiligen geist / y zu dy gelouben volleist / desnoch was dy manich kint / do suythe her syny boten hyn / syne gnade was myt yn / do sy quamen eyn du kint / do her sy hate hen gesant / als dy folk bekerchen / unde den gelouben lerthen",
    english: "God, who created heaven and earth, all creatures in His divine power, the small and the great alike, the course of stars and the free will — He shaped all things in His godly strength.\n\nTo all those who are Christians, we offer great greeting. You who honor the name of Christ and turn away from sin, to you God shall give reward and grant eternal life.\n\nWe shall now begin a tale of what God began for Christendom. He taught His followers well, and on the third day He rose again, releasing many from their sorrow and lamentation. He ascended from earth to heaven and sent forth His Holy Spirit to strengthen all the faithful. Yet many peoples still remained unconverted, so He sent His messengers forth, and His grace was upon them. When they came among the peoples where He had sent them, they converted the folk and taught them the true faith.\n\nMuch opposition stood before them, but God poured His grace upon them and they performed great miracles. Some bore the crown of martyrdom, as the apostles too endured. Great signs and wonders they wrought with their holy power. Thus many a people was converted and came to know the Christian faith. Where once there was only darkness, the light of Christ drove it away. God delivered them from all distress and gave them their heavenly reward.\n\n[The opening page contains the Prologue. The large ornamental 'G' initial begins the invocation of God as creator. A red 'W' initial in the right column marks the start of the apostolic mission narrative. Two columns of approximately 40 lines each.]",
  },
  "192v": {
    original: "In hymelriche eyn ewik leben / yz ist hy der wol bestricken / waz got irmiten hat gerihen / wor kan man yz loben al... / Vor allen lorien lobusten / daz wil ich euch bedunsten / do ich aller besthe kan / vu gantz nahe hebe ich an / von selde waz en di gestor / Eside wude wir messen... / do diz was irgangen so / die cristen wurden alle vro / daz was der heidenschefte leit",
    english: "In the heavenly kingdom, eternal life awaits — this is well ordained for those whom God has chosen in His mercy. Who could ever praise it all? With rhyming verse I shall now set forth what God has accomplished through His servants and apostles.\n\nThe author declares he will tell his tale as best he can. He announces that his subject lies close at hand — not in distant Jerusalem, but across the Baltic Sea, where German Christians encountered a people who still burned offerings to false gods and lived in spiritual darkness.\n\nBefore all praiseworthy peoples, this I wish to make known to you. I begin quite close at hand, from a land beyond the sea, where heathens dwelt who knew not God. From German lands came men of faith who crossed the waters to find these shores. They discovered peoples living in pagandom — the Livs, who worshipped in sacred groves and offered sacrifices to spirits of nature.\n\nWhen the Christian preachers came so near that they could speak to the heathens, the people knew not what to make of it. When the arrival was reported through the land, a great alarm arose. The Estonians, Livonians, and Oeselians began to stir against the newcomers. The news was grievous to them that Christianity had come to their shores. But God poured His grace upon the missionaries, and day by day the faith grew stronger.\n\n[Folio 192v continues the prologue, transitioning from the general history of Christian mission to the specific story of Livonia. The red 'M' initial near the bottom marks a new section. The author identifies his subject: a land 'beyond the sea' where heathens who burned sacrifices were encountered by German Christians.]",
  },
  "193r": {
    original: "Daz selbe dude gue / den erste wolde habe genomy... / do wunden sy emphaligen wol / alle stide gesthe sol / daz erben sy sul machen laz... / eyn bust mit vnt in komin / eyn herre his meinhart / er waz inne andel wol bclart / unde hat sune stude eruz / daz vnn dy lesische woren",
    english: "The same worthy people wished first to take possession of the land, but when they came upon the native inhabitants, the heathens rose in fierce defense. They killed many of the newcomers, and great suffering fell upon the German settlers. Yet not all heathens were hostile — some among them wished to receive what the strangers brought.\n\nThen they were received quite well in certain places. They were given land to settle and were allowed to build their first structures. They came into that country among the heathens, where many a local chieftain held sway over his people and wondrous things occurred.\n\nThe faith began to take root. Churches were established and settlements given names that persist to this day in that eastern land. Among the heathens, some accepted the new teaching willingly, as the tale tells us truly.\n\nThen there came a worthy man with virtue and learning — a priest named Meinhard. He was well educated in holy scripture and had founded a small church among the Livs. The heathen people there were numerous, but he knew well how to speak to them. His churches were established through patient effort, and many a heathen found instruction in the Christian faith. Where once there was only pagandom and darkness, Meinhard brought the light of the Gospel through years of tireless labor.\n\n[Folio 193r narrates the first German contact with the Livonian peoples. Initial encounters are violent, but some natives are receptive. The text introduces Meinhard, the Augustinian monk who founded the first church at Ikskile (Uexküll) on the Daugava river around 1184. He is praised for his learning and his patient approach to conversion.]",
  },
  "193v": {
    original: "Lr en weren nomn lean geblehy / eyn deme lande eyme sont... / na waz doly hy gesten / eyn heiden lude hy mirysen / Kope der selbe hye / des ersten er sich loufen lie / unde siner vrunde ein michel teil / da waz der sele eyn selig heil / von andern heiden quam ouch dar / zu prister meynhart manche schar / und entpfiengen den touf / durch den himelischen kouf / do diz waz irgangen so / die cristen wurden alle vro / daz was der heidenschefte leit / daz kope die cristenheit / mit sinen vrunden hatte genomen... / Begunden sich af struzen / Esten leiven unde oselere / en waz dy rede gyr en swere",
    english: "They remained in that land for a time as strangers among the heathen folk. The priest Meinhard's courage was strong, for he had brought God's Word to people who had never heard it. A church he founded, as the chronicles record, and though his resources were meager, from the German lands there came to him many good Christian helpers.\n\nAmong the heathens there lived a man of great power and high standing, mighty and with many kinsmen in that pagan land. His name was Kope. He was the first among the Livonians to let himself be baptized, and a great number of his friends and family with him. That was a blessed salvation for their souls. From other heathen communities there came also to the priest Meinhard many groups seeking baptism, and they received the holy sacrament for the sake of the heavenly reward.\n\nWhen this had come to pass, the Christians were all filled with joy. But it was a bitter grief to the heathen host that Kope had embraced Christianity together with his kinsmen and friends. This news became quickly known throughout the entire land, and a great outcry arose among the pagan peoples.\n\nThe Estonians, Livonians, and Oeselians began to rise up in fierce anger. The news was grievous and heavy to them that Christianity had come to their shores and was spreading among their people. Day by day the faith grew stronger, and day by day the heathens' lament grew louder. But God continued to pour His grace upon the missionaries, and the old ways were being swept away despite all resistance.\n\n[Folio 193v describes the first successful conversion: a Livonian chieftain named Kope becomes the first native to accept baptism along with many kinsmen. This provokes outrage among the unconverted peoples — the Livs, Estonians, and Oeselians rise in anger. Despite fierce opposition, the faith grows daily.]",
  },
  "194r": {
    original: "Linden eme sint genant / dy heidenscheft alz dy gemat... / dy bonelische dot sir guten / dy wiere now eyn ane mete / dy huke bestunt in mashe walls / y sub ym kundelich gestalt... / ynt phyffe ist in goze crist / ey den ouch geschofen sint / dy haten ouch vol mach mus bye / daz kompt do von ist breit... / daz he begonde hy yn alles sagen / ynt phyffe ist in goze orist / unde ouch dy nor ist gesrichen",
    english: "The heathens — the Livonians by name — dwelt in a land of deep pagandom. Their customs and beliefs were far removed from Christian truth. They had not yet been fully converted, for many resisted with great stubbornness. Some among them held positions of considerable power and would not willingly forsake their ancient ways and old gods.\n\nTheir religious practices were wondrous to behold for the Christian observers: they worshipped in sacred groves and beside flowing waters, made offerings and sacrifices to false gods and nature spirits, and practiced arts of sorcery and divination. Their priests held great authority over the common people through these rites.\n\nBut from the German lands there came men filled with holy purpose who sought to bring the light of Christ to this darkened people. They crossed the sea to reach these shores, and in that foreign and hostile land they established themselves, building churches and small fortified places. They set themselves with great determination to the work of converting these stubborn peoples, preaching in the villages and at the gathering places.\n\nThe priests carried the message that Christ is the true God, born of the Virgin and risen from the dead, who created all things and all peoples. They declared that the heathen gods were demons and false spirits, and that all the old ways of sacrifice and sorcery must be abandoned. The teaching of the cross must prevail where once the pagan darkness held sway. They began to tell the Livonians everything about the true faith, sparing no effort in their mission.\n\n[Folio 194r describes the Livonian people and their pagan religious practices — worship in sacred groves, offerings to nature spirits, sorcery, and divination. German missionaries arrive and establish churches, declaring that the heathen gods are false. This page marks the transition from the general prologue to the specific narrative of the Livonian mission, setting the stage for the conflicts that will follow.]",
  },
  "194v": {
    original: "Ich wil noch sunge ir guden / wer ouch wulde base ynn gort... / do dy habe ist vor many / dy hertze an vuehe grunt / do er hue der bischof quam / do wart gebelit shrio orich...",
    english: "I wish to sing further of the good people and of what happened in that land. The bishop’s journey was undertaken with great purpose, and when word of his arrival spread, the people stirred with both hope and fear.\n\nA new bishop was sent to the land — Bishop Berthold — who came with zealous purpose to continue the mission that Meinhard had begun. But unlike his predecessor, Berthold found the Livonians hostile and unwilling to submit. The heathens who had been baptized under Meinhard threw off their Christianity, washed away their baptism in the river, and returned to their old gods and sacrifices.\n\nBishop Berthold appealed to Rome for permission to use force. The Pope granted a crusading bull, and Berthold returned to Livonia with armed knights from Germany. But the campaign ended in disaster — in the battle against the Livonians, Bishop Berthold was pulled from his horse and killed by the enraged pagans. His death in 1198 proved that peaceful mission had failed.\n\nThe chronicle records this as a great martyrdom — a bishop who died for the faith in a foreign land. His death became the justification for everything that followed: the coming of Bishop Albert, the founding of Riga, and the conquest of all Livonia by the sword.\n\n[Folio 194v narrates the mission and death of Bishop Berthold. The Livonians reject Christianity after Meinhard’s death, and Berthold is killed in battle in 1198. This is the turning point from peaceful mission to armed crusade.]",
  },
  "195r": {
    original: "Vor alle mysse swende / habe is sich dy wol gelurt / crus der ediss hymne dart... / dor bischof Bertolt dy hegen... / dy litten unde luwen / do me ams sy satthen / daz wurt den ariste balselich...",
    english: "Before all the world’s sorrow, there arose a man of great purpose. After Bishop Berthold’s death, the church in Rome appointed a new leader for the Livonian mission — one who would succeed where his predecessors had failed.\n\nBishop Albert von Buxthoeven arrived at the mouth of the Daugava in the year 1200 with a mighty fleet. Unlike Meinhard the peaceful missionary or Berthold the martyred warrior, Albert came with a comprehensive plan: he would found a permanent city, establish a military order, and systematically conquer the entire region.\n\nThe Livonians and other peoples suffered greatly under this new offensive. Those who submitted were baptized and organized into Christian parishes. Those who resisted faced the swords of the German knights.\n\nBishop Albert’s first act was to choose a site for his new city. He selected a spot near the mouth of the Daugava where a small tributary called the Rīdzene provided a natural harbor. There, in the year 1201, he founded the city of Riga — the stronghold from which the entire Baltic crusade would be directed.\n\n[Folio 195r introduces Bishop Albert von Buxthoeven and his arrival in 1200. He founds Riga in 1201 at the mouth of the Daugava. The red initial marks a major new section.]",
  },
  "195v": {
    original: "Der bischof syn dy symyn dur / quam in creblyche... / dy orste hatten grove clage / un wie gyngy so alls tage... / dy bischoft in dy myncher...",
    english: "Bishop Albert’s city of Riga grew with remarkable speed. German merchants from Lübeck, Bremen, and other Hanseatic cities flocked to the new settlement, attracted by the commercial opportunities of the Daugava trade route. The river connected the Baltic Sea to the vast Russian interior — a highway for furs, wax, timber, and amber.\n\nThe bishop established the first stone cathedral — the Dom — which would become the seat of the Archbishop of Livonia and the largest church in the Baltic region. Around it grew the first streets and marketplaces.\n\nBut the surrounding countryside remained hostile. The Livonians and Letts watched the growing city with alarm. Raids against the new settlement were frequent, and the small German garrison was hard-pressed.\n\nBishop Albert recognized that annual crusaders who came for a season and then returned to Germany could not provide the permanent military force he needed. He conceived a solution that would change Baltic history forever.\n\n[Folio 195v describes Riga’s rapid growth and the construction of the Dom Cathedral. The surrounding peoples remain hostile. Bishop Albert realizes he needs a permanent military force, setting the stage for founding the Livonian Brothers of the Sword.]",
  },
  "196r": {
    original: "Der bischoff syn dy symyn dur... / der bischoff alberth leser une / du sehe des buschofs sure / waz ma der linde solde geben / in en geystliche leben...",
    english: "Bishop Albert understood that the crusading mission required a permanent armed force. The heathens could simply wait for the annual crusaders to leave and then attack the weakened settlements.\n\nAlbert therefore founded a military brotherhood — an order of knights bound by monastic vows who would remain in Livonia permanently. In the year 1202, with papal approval, he established the Livonian Brothers of the Sword — the Fratres Militiae Christi de Livonia.\n\nThe brothers wore white mantles marked with a red cross and sword. They took vows of poverty, chastity, and obedience, living under a monastic rule adapted from the Templars. But their primary purpose was warfare: to fight the heathens and extend Christendom by conquest.\n\nBishop Albert granted the new Order one-third of all territories conquered. This gave the brothers a direct material stake in expansion. The more land they conquered, the richer and more powerful the Order became. It was a system that aligned spiritual mission with temporal ambition.\n\n[Folio 196r describes the founding of the Livonian Brothers of the Sword in 1202. The Order receives one-third of all conquered territory. The red initial marks this as a major turning point.]",
  },
  "196v": {
    original: "An nuz den halshe rushe lor / dy elfhen luren seden lant / wuren milter rushen hant... / volke mit stischten on duch lant / do waz dy resze vol beqwant / den armen oristennene / dy libahen do mit rime...",
    english: "The new Order grew rapidly as German knights streamed to Livonia to take the cross and join the brotherhood. The brothers established their first fortress in Riga itself and began building a network of stone castles at strategic points — river crossings, trade routes, and commanding hilltops.\n\nFrom these strongholds the brothers launched raids into pagan territory, burning settlements, demanding baptism, and seizing land. Those who submitted were spared; those who resisted were attacked with ruthless efficiency. The Order’s discipline, armor, and siege techniques gave them a decisive advantage.\n\nThe first Master of the Order led the brothers with great energy. New castles rose across the landscape, each extending the frontier of Christian control further into pagan territory. The Livonians’ wooden hill-forts could not withstand German siege techniques, and one by one they fell.\n\nThe impoverished Christians of the early mission now had a powerful protector. With the Order’s swords behind them, the priests could preach without fear. Within a few years, the entire lower Daugava valley was under German control, and the Order was already looking further afield — to the Letts, the Estonians, and beyond.\n\n[Folio 196v describes the Order’s rapid growth and expansion. Knights arrive from Germany, castles are built, and systematic conquest begins. The combination of military force and missionary activity proves devastatingly effective.]",
  },
  "197r": {
    original: "A nomy do waz ha hymuz / al yz my dy orsten alle / ey den grossen halse / wuen sy bestulst genoke... / den bischoff albrechte / it sburechim hore rechte / y blaste sy wol in huz grot / der selbe synsten Imist han / Smntlischen ymme / a huz und her sich of dy ze / Bedir lewe unde Leut / flagitte sy den ment yudy hat / ir alle solche mage / do iz ma dy merz woz van / az er hiz der bischoff quam / do wart gekelit shrio orich / do all salde wurdest ist...",
    english: "Bishop Albert was a man of great determination and vision. He summoned his followers and addressed the assembled knights, clergy, and merchants who had gathered in Riga. He spoke of the great mission that God had entrusted to them — the conversion of the heathen peoples of Livonia and the defense of the Christian settlements along the Daugava.\n\nThe bishop laid out his plans with clarity and force. He would travel to Germany each year to recruit new crusaders, preaching the cross at courts and churches across the Holy Roman Empire. He would seek papal bulls guaranteeing spiritual rewards equal to those offered for crusades to the Holy Land. And he would build Riga into a city worthy of its mission — a fortress of Christendom on the shores of the Baltic.\n\nThe assembled company heard him with great enthusiasm. Knights pledged their swords, merchants pledged their wealth, and the clergy pledged their prayers. Bishop Albert had united the disparate elements of the crusading enterprise into a single purpose. Under his leadership, the conquest of Livonia would proceed with a methodical efficiency that his predecessors had lacked.\n\nThe chronicle presents Albert as the ideal crusading bishop — pious, energetic, diplomatically skilled, and ruthless when necessary. He combined the spiritual authority of the church with the military power of the Order and the commercial wealth of the Hanseatic merchants, creating an institutional framework that would outlast his own lifetime.\n\n[Folio 197r shows Bishop Albert rallying his forces and laying out his strategic vision for the conquest of Livonia. He plans annual recruiting trips to Germany, papal endorsement, and the systematic expansion of Riga. The passage portrays Albert as the organizing genius of the Baltic crusade.]",
  },
  "197v": {
    original: "Sy ir sy manchen losen synys / Babor eyme lunde quam / dy gysele sy do yn do nam / dy galte wim an alle wer / daz iz belmade mit dem her / daz ver her wu lur yin din / er in huz als hy sul selig man / do dy oste daz vor nomen / dy solle dy wt huz wolen / dy inde oyde uch ym sur / Nu sy do dwoze hulfe sont / do wyts sy sich nulsche du / by heyde snake unde vry nom / daz waler qu dy dune ul nor / in nu was ouch ub rechte kome / der shronge du dy syme / az in manchem pulgeryme...",
    english: "The chronicle now describes the first military campaigns against the Livonian peoples along the Daugava. Bishop Albert led his forces — crusading knights, the newly founded Brothers of the Sword, and local converts — against the pagan strongholds that dotted the riverbanks.\n\nThe heathens who had initially submitted now rose in revolt, throwing off their baptism and attacking the German settlements. They took hostages from among the Christian converts and threatened to kill them unless the Germans withdrew. Bishop Albert responded with force, leading his army against the rebel villages.\n\nThe campaign was swift and brutal. The Germans, armored in chainmail and wielding superior weapons, overwhelmed the lightly armed Livonian warriors. Settlement after settlement fell. Those who submitted were rebaptized; those who resisted were put to the sword. The hostages were recovered, and the revolt was crushed.\n\nBut the resistance did not end. New revolts flared as soon as the German army moved on. The Livonians were learning that baptism meant not just a change of religion but the loss of their freedom — tribute payments, forced labor, and submission to foreign lords. Each campaign planted the seeds of the next rebellion.\n\nPilgrims continued to arrive from Germany, reinforcing the garrison each spring. The cycle of crusade, conquest, revolt, and reconquest would continue for decades until the last pockets of resistance were finally broken.\n\n[Folio 197v describes the first military campaigns against Livonian resistance. Newly baptized heathens revolt, take hostages, and are crushed by German forces. The pattern of conquest-revolt-reconquest is established. The passage reveals the coercive nature of the Christianization process.]",
  },
  "198r": {
    original: "O zum slazgem gud und vui / ho er synist im bonelisch gu / wor halsen her mar / dy dugeen huz en sore / do en duz ouch ger hat hy grefe / zu taze in duz wl ame lite / dy ist revnt gu in dy hertstrike / do daz welley mir dy dush wort / az ahn ein gne galden dy aly / dy syme gold dy vniorat / a is halt gret myt sid ouch / yn mysylande sy dy heidischit / dy arse dy salke sent / do wurt dy criste eyst ey sore / zu ny sylande sy dy yer / dy saulde sysse dy orishe gur / her wart dy deme oder ouch / y vulstar wir nd bliue or / hape wart dy huz some / dy sayetr hoch hof em dy sint / in in sich dy bunne syne / her vu synne der her genain / hu hade in dy brunner / her sich en machen sindem...",
    english: "The chronicle turns to the organization of the crusading territory. Bishop Albert, with the support of the Order and the papal legate, divided the conquered lands into administrative districts. Each district was centered on a castle or fortified church, from which German officials governed the surrounding population.\n\nThe indigenous Livonians were required to pay tribute — a portion of their harvest, livestock, and labor — to their new overlords. They were assigned to parishes and required to attend Christian services, observe Christian holidays, and abandon their pagan rituals. Those who refused faced punishment: fines, imprisonment, or worse.\n\nThe chronicle describes the establishment of the first German estates in Livonia. Knights who had served the crusade received grants of land, complete with the native inhabitants as bound tenants. The Livonians who had once been free farmers on their own land now worked the same fields as serfs, paying rent to foreign masters.\n\nThe Order built its castles at strategic river crossings and hilltops, creating a network of fortified positions that could reinforce each other and control the countryside. Each castle housed a small garrison of brothers and their armed retainers, ready to suppress any sign of rebellion.\n\nMeanwhile, in Riga itself, the city continued to grow. German merchants established permanent trading houses, and the port facilities expanded to handle the increasing volume of commerce flowing along the Daugava.\n\n[Folio 198r describes the administrative organization of conquered Livonia. Lands are divided into districts, tribute imposed on the native population, German estates established, and the Order’s castle network expanded. The transformation from conquest to colonial governance is underway.]",
  },
  "198v": {
    original: "Dunne unde pashen / eyn matler maze in ohen / hysen sy du lesere sigen / dy wolden wosen dusegegen / do ez here wure dy hyzgegen / dy wunche ore du hyzsele byr / do er oysehalde wis in / dy syneghelde do wis in / du osme wynne bach gelosir / do ey velbe dy ore seste lude / eyne grose lande quamy dur / de geyse wurde wol dy her... / in nu waz dulst hy in salze / az may sy hysluden du / alz by pu un mymnye dy / dy warden geste woren so / dy sutten inde dy lusen / dy wolden sinke bilden / dy dem orissennye / dy orsten wol nur nynne...",
    english: "The chronicle describes the annual rhythm of the crusade. Each spring, when the ice melted on the Baltic and the sea lanes opened, a new fleet of pilgrim-crusaders sailed from Lübeck and other German ports bound for Riga. These were knights, merchants, and clergy who had taken the crusading vow — promising to serve for one campaign season in exchange for the spiritual rewards promised by the Pope.\n\nThe arriving crusaders were welcomed in Riga with great ceremony. Bishop Albert hosted feasts and briefed the newcomers on the military situation. The Order’s Master assigned them to various campaigns planned for the season. Some would join expeditions against unconquered territories; others would garrison existing castles or escort supply convoys through hostile territory.\n\nThe campaigns typically lasted through the summer and early autumn. When the first frosts came and the sailing season drew to a close, the pilgrim-crusaders returned to their ships and departed for Germany, their vows fulfilled. They carried home stories of adventure and hardship — stories that would inspire the next year’s crop of volunteers.\n\nThe permanent garrison — the Brothers of the Sword and the bishop’s household knights — remained through the winter, holding the line against the heathens who invariably tested the Christian defenses once the seasonal reinforcements departed. The long, dark Baltic winter was the most dangerous time for the small German colony.\n\n[Folio 198v describes the annual cycle of the crusade: pilgrim-crusaders arrive each spring from Germany, campaign through the summer, and depart in autumn. The permanent garrison holds through the dangerous winter months. This seasonal rhythm defined the first decades of the Livonian crusade.]",
  },
  "199r": {
    original: "As sy den ersten yn soylaide / dy wolden ouch dynu noitage / dy synsge bliben duch dy not / dy oysliche waz von lehn / dy gebe eyme dy seste gudy / dy vlay hungehundert vor / da vy en machen de sey dy lek / was sy er houlr sundir dur / dy orsthe suden grose not / dy ongen laz dy selbn tot / dy susen logen grose not / ya ist sugnie sy yn lunte / do deyr got dy loshe / dy orsthe suden noch der svur / do en huz oste myt du lihe / der sest waz du nudruge lat / dy erde man sich moel lassur / in herde morden began / dy wurt sy wisten / un sy den messe dor yn sich / sy mylich au eyme urtze sint / yr eymy reyner orsynlan / daz sy sin uch wulden gelinv / zu wide her sy heide stinc / dy mort duz sunlich genvit / dy srvel vu ym dor ume duch / do slel nel ym dor syme buch...",
    english: "The chronicle describes a period of severe hardship for the early Christian colony. The first settlers and their converts faced not only military threats from the surrounding heathens but also the harsh realities of frontier life: failed harvests, disease, and the crushing isolation of winter in a hostile land.\n\nMany of the early converts wavered in their faith. Cut off from the pagan communities they had left and not yet fully accepted by the German colonists, they occupied an uncomfortable middle ground. Some secretly continued their old religious practices, making offerings at hidden shrines in the forest while attending Christian services in the village church.\n\nThe chronicle records a series of violent incidents along the frontier. German settlers were ambushed and killed. Isolated churches were burned. The heathens grew bolder as they sensed the colony’s weakness. Bishop Albert was forced to appeal urgently to Rome and to the German princes for reinforcements.\n\nThe crisis reached its peak when a large force of unconverted Livonians and their Lithuanian allies besieged one of the Order’s frontier castles. The garrison held out for weeks, surviving on dwindling supplies, until a relief force from Riga finally broke through. The siege was lifted, but the message was clear: the Christian colony’s survival was by no means assured.\n\nDespite these setbacks, Bishop Albert refused to abandon the mission. He redoubled his recruiting efforts in Germany, and the Order’s Master began planning a major offensive that would carry the war deep into the pagan interior.\n\n[Folio 199r describes a period of crisis for the early colony: failed harvests, wavering converts, frontier violence, and a major siege of a German castle. Bishop Albert appeals urgently for reinforcements. The passage reveals how precarious the crusading enterprise was in its early years.]",
  },
  "199v": {
    original: "Sy reden loyde unde man / hy in grozin wolde mir yz dun / dy en lunde shorge albrechte dur / dy mael sabute um in sunt... / dy su seden wurt yr swor / dy heden sy gelobist duz / daz sy dur geldenbunyg haz / daz wulke sy nor besinten sur... / dy sweden wart in over / daz huz gewomen eny man / yn osten ere dy lyndus / doy seugen in al gemeyne rot / der suslost leyt dy sole not / o man dy warheit sohin wol / do halft syn banyn manz vol...",
    english: "The chronicle describes a critical turning point in the early crusade. The Livonians, having initially submitted to baptism, now organized a coordinated resistance. Their leaders gathered in secret councils, swearing oaths to drive out the Germans and destroy the Christian churches. They sent messengers to the Estonians, Letts, and Lithuanians, urging a united pagan front against the invaders.\n\nBishop Albert, warned of the conspiracy by loyal converts, acted swiftly. He summoned the Order’s Master and the garrison commanders to a war council in Riga. The decision was made to strike first, before the pagan alliance could fully form. The German forces marched out in multiple columns, targeting the rebel leaders’ strongholds simultaneously.\n\nThe Swedes also played a role in these events. Swedish merchants and warriors had their own interests in the eastern Baltic, and their involvement complicated the already tangled web of alliances and enmities. The chronicle mentions Swedish forces operating along the coast, sometimes cooperating with the Germans, sometimes competing with them.\n\nThe truth of the matter, the chronicler assures us, is that God’s will prevailed. The pagan conspiracy was broken, its leaders captured or killed, and the rebel settlements burned. But the underlying tensions remained — the Livonians had not been truly converted, only temporarily subdued. The cycle of revolt and repression would continue.\n\nThe red initial ‘G’ visible on this page marks the beginning of a new major section, signaling a shift in the narrative to the wars against the Letts and the expansion of the crusade beyond the Daugava valley.\n\n[Folio 199v describes a coordinated Livonian conspiracy against the Germans, Bishop Albert’s preemptive strike, and Swedish involvement in Baltic affairs. The red initial marks a new narrative section. The passage reveals the fragility of German control in the early years.]",
  },
  "200r": {
    original: "Is sy mer say dy sten man / dy schines ich yn mus legan / in solt weshy nor der shor / yn waz als her ger hy nor / do sy yn duz haus syn / dy en dy dune hulze shyn / az hy wil synne wir belest / dy gelobete sy yn dor alles / dy volde suren mit dy rat... / dy genude kurtus yst genulk / dy bant dy brude in der hant / dy lans myr euge ny in / dy greue albrecht der sich dy / vor alle syne sunde / dy ist wol vin orleneze...",
    english: "The chronicle now narrates the expansion of the crusade into the territories of the Letts — the Baltic-speaking peoples who inhabited the Daugava valley upstream from the Livs and the hilly uplands of Vidzeme to the northeast. Unlike the coastal Livs, the Letts were organized into larger tribal confederacies led by powerful chieftains who commanded fortified hill-forts.\n\nThe German advance up the Daugava brought them into contact with the Lettish principalities of Koknese (Kokenhusen) and Jersika. These were not primitive tribal settlements but substantial political entities with their own systems of law, trade connections to the Russian principalities, and diplomatic relationships with their neighbors.\n\nBishop Albert and the Order’s Master recognized that the Lettish territories must be conquered to secure Riga’s position. The Daugava was the lifeline of the crusading colony — the highway connecting Riga to the Russian interior — and as long as independent Lettish strongholds controlled its upper reaches, that lifeline was vulnerable.\n\nThe chronicle describes the diplomatic overtures that preceded the military campaigns. Bishop Albert offered the Lettish chieftains protection against their Lithuanian enemies in exchange for accepting baptism and acknowledging German overlordship. Some accepted; others refused. Those who refused would face the consequences.\n\nThe greue (count) Albrecht led the vanguard of the army that marched upriver, and the Order’s brothers followed with the main force. The campaign against the Letts had begun.\n\n[Folio 200r marks the beginning of the campaigns against the Lettish (Latvian) peoples of the upper Daugava. The chronicle describes the Lettish principalities of Koknese and Jersika, and Bishop Albert’s combined diplomatic and military approach to their subjugation.]",
  },
  "200v": {
    original: "Do suche man hein der se lant / dy selden man dy yme dant / dy wulsen nicht sintkinden / daz werlischen / dy ruschen medy er siche soryt / daz greve sms zu delin sohr / yn ich werde von dy waz senk... / dy sminde growe albrechte / dy nu lunde waz dy wulde gesthe... / dy andyny und dy orde nd / von worlunde sy her woyn / do er riche nu dy stunde gm / dy scresten in strennde lunt / do den den selben wart bleat / daz semp helden aurensy...",
    english: "The chronicle describes the campaign against the Lettish territories along the middle Daugava. The German forces advanced upriver, encountering increasing resistance from the Lettish warriors who defended their homeland with fierce determination.\n\nThe Russians — the princes of Polotsk who had long collected tribute from some of the Lettish tribes — watched the German advance with alarm. They sent envoys protesting the invasion of territories they considered under their own suzerainty. Bishop Albert rejected their claims, arguing that the Letts were pagans who needed Christian salvation, not Orthodox Russian overlordship.\n\nThe chronicle names Bishop Albert’s commanders and describes their advance through the forested river valley. The Letts fought from their hill-forts, using the terrain to maximum advantage. The dense forests channeled the German advance along narrow paths where ambushes were easy and cavalry charges impossible.\n\nBut the Germans had advantages the Letts could not match: iron armor that turned the Letts’ lighter weapons, crossbows that outranged their bows, and siege techniques that could reduce even the strongest hill-fort. One by one, the Lettish strongholds fell.\n\nThose who were conquered were immediately organized into the Christian system: baptized, assigned to parishes, and required to pay tribute. German officials were installed to govern the newly conquered districts, and the Order began building stone castles to replace the captured wooden hill-forts.\n\n[Folio 200v narrates the German advance up the Daugava into Lettish territory. The Russians of Polotsk protest the invasion. The Letts fight from their hill-forts but are overcome by superior German military technology. Conquered territories are immediately organized under Christian administration.]",
  },
  "201r": {
    original: "Hy en slere libu miduz duo / dy losfen some hy vn du / daz lunt waz gut du gros / dy volny walsen also blos / daz is en duz volkes slyne wony / dy slughe mache arsichen mody... / dy love wol und lunt / dy goldn amt vul gozn not / erblaz wl mdn lande wor / dy slat wol moshe syn yn gelerr / von dy guder lunde gesirt...",
    english: "The chronicle turns to the fate of the Lettish principality of Jersika, one of the most important political centers in the pre-crusade Daugava valley. Jersika’s prince, Visvaldis, had built a substantial fortified settlement at a strategic bend in the river. He maintained diplomatic ties with the Russian prince of Polotsk and had married a Russian princess, cementing his alliance with the Orthodox Christian east.\n\nThe Germans regarded Visvaldis as a particular threat because of his Russian connections. An alliance between the Lettish principalities and the Russian city-states could have created a formidable obstacle to the crusade’s expansion. Bishop Albert decided that Jersika must be neutralized.\n\nThe chronicle describes the German assault on Jersika in detail. The attack came suddenly, catching Visvaldis by surprise. His warriors fought bravely but were overwhelmed by the German knights’ superior armor and weapons. The fortified settlement was stormed, its wooden walls breached, and its defenders killed or captured.\n\nVisvaldis himself escaped across the Daugava with a handful of followers, but his principality was destroyed. His lands were divided between the Order and the Bishop of Riga. His people — the Lettish farmers, craftsmen, and warriors who had lived under his protection — became serfs of their new German masters.\n\nThe fall of Jersika sent a powerful message to the other Lettish chieftains: resistance was futile. One by one, they submitted to baptism and accepted German overlordship, surrendering their independence in exchange for their lives.\n\n[Folio 201r describes the German assault on and destruction of Jersika, the Lettish principality on the Daugava. Prince Visvaldis escapes but his realm is destroyed and divided between the Order and the Bishop. The fall of Jersika marks the end of Lettish political independence in the Daugava valley.]",
  },
  "201v": {
    original: "Daz sy mere brochten hyn / der yz talisen hase wy du syn geloben / er sulsen wude wl von hunde / dy herosts selde sich du hunte / dy gelussten wulden orlen orist / dy sosten duz dy sluzsen... / do en wullen sy dy silde / dy en ir dy lore nicht / unde myssende lidet / dy vuysen norke sich duz an / dy orschen dy arstenhin begun / dach in mden lande meren / daz dy wulden sy wor beren...",
    english: "The chronicle continues with the subjugation of the remaining Lettish territories in the Daugava valley and the Gauja river region. After the fall of Jersika, many Lettish chieftains chose submission over destruction. They presented themselves before Bishop Albert, accepted baptism, and swore oaths of loyalty to the German church.\n\nBut not all submitted willingly. Some chieftains retreated into the dense forests of the interior, refusing to accept either Christianity or German rule. From their forest hideouts they launched raids against the German settlers and their Lettish collaborators, burning farms and ambushing supply trains. The chronicle portrays these resisters as stubborn heathens who refused God’s grace.\n\nThe Order responded with systematic campaigns to root out the remaining resistance. Small detachments of brothers, guided by converted Lettish scouts, penetrated the forests to hunt down the holdouts. Those who were captured were given a final choice: baptism or death. Most chose baptism, though the sincerity of conversions made at sword-point was questionable.\n\nMeanwhile, the institutional framework of German rule expanded across the conquered Lettish territories. New parishes were established, with German priests assigned to each one. The indigenous Lettish social structure was dismantled and replaced with the feudal system: German lords received estates, and Lettish peasants became their bound tenants. The transformation that had begun with the Livs along the coast was now spreading into the heart of what would become Latvia.\n\n[Folio 201v describes the final subjugation of the Lettish territories. Some chieftains submit willingly; others resist from the forests and are hunted down. The feudal system is imposed: German lords receive estates, Lettish peasants become serfs. The chronicle’s account reveals the systematic dismantling of indigenous Latvian society.]",
  },
  "202r": {
    original: "Des symers herte sy dy sint / yr phyffe zu yz en wuz seleit / dy men dude sraden gros / dy en meise sire dez wor dvez / der sysche mir yn alle / dy der meyals obur vee / dzy in den lande quemon / yn dy wussele menne nyme... / der greve dy wid aristen / dy wol sy besse neuer eyn / dy in druger abe yn sinist / dy smosele yn wl vol wiken / dy iz sy bere pilgerin / myd syne ert wolde syn / dy ymsist styuf sich dy wnit baut / dy iz dy pilyerynne wart...",
    english: "The chronicle describes the summer campaigning season in which the Order and Bishop Albert’s forces extended their control deeper into Lettish territory. The German army, reinforced by the annual influx of pilgrim-crusaders from across Europe, moved systematically through the Gauja river valley, the fertile uplands of Vidzeme, and the territories beyond.\n\nEach conquered district was immediately organized under German administration. The Order built castles at Cēsis (Wenden), Sigulda (Segewold), and Turaida (Treiden) — three great fortresses that would dominate the Gauja valley for centuries. These stone castles, unlike the wooden hill-forts they replaced, were virtually impregnable to indigenous attack.\n\nThe pilgrim-crusaders who arrived each year played a crucial role in these campaigns. They provided the manpower needed for offensive operations that the Order’s small permanent garrison could not sustain alone. But their short terms of service — typically one campaign season — meant that the Germans could never maintain continuous pressure on the unconquered territories.\n\nThe chronicle describes how the pilgrims were organized and deployed. Some joined major expeditions into enemy territory; others were assigned to garrison duty at frontier castles. All received the spiritual benefits promised by the Pope: remission of sins and the assurance of salvation. For many German knights, a season of crusading in Livonia was the defining experience of their lives.\n\n[Folio 202r describes the expansion into the Gauja valley and the construction of the great castles at Cēsis, Sigulda, and Turaida. Pilgrim-crusaders arrive annually from Germany to reinforce the campaign. The red ‘O’ initial marks a section break.]",
  },
  "202v": {
    original: "A st man bit en orid misle / dy hule unde sirile / dy dusle susthe en du dy wdu / der selden singe sy en dy dur / dy slagren hindert wor / dy a yndre walden westl du / do meist yn den lande sat... / dy sulethe dy de dy volde syn / dy iz sul maudeste slat / eyn sus sunge dursthen sin / dy nu syuihe wl dy suwe / dy iz dy bure dy sere leshe / heyse lesinge dy in vot / her en dul sy ilsin dy not / dy iz geslywant dy ley dy / en su brudt dy biz dy marquart...",
    english: "The chronicle introduces a new figure: Marquard, likely a commander or official of the Order, who plays an important role in the campaigns that follow. The narrative describes his arrival in Livonia and his assignment to a frontier command.\n\nThe Germans continued to push deeper into the interior, encountering increasingly difficult terrain. The dense forests of the Latvian uplands sheltered pagan communities that had so far escaped the crusaders’ reach. These forest-dwellers were the most resistant to conversion, clinging to their old gods with a stubbornness that both impressed and infuriated the chronicler.\n\nMarquard led his forces against several fortified settlements deep in the forest. The campaigns were arduous — the army had to cut its way through dense woodland, ford rivers, and navigate trackless marshes. Supply lines stretched thin, and the men suffered from hunger and exhaustion.\n\nBut the Germans’ technological advantages proved decisive even in the forest. Their crossbows outranged the heathens’ bows, their armor turned the pagans’ lighter weapons, and their siege techniques — fire, battering rams, and escalade — could breach even the strongest wooden fortifications. One by one, the forest strongholds fell.\n\nMarquard proved himself a capable and ruthless commander. The chronicle praises his energy and his devotion to the crusading cause, noting that he spared no effort in pursuing the heathens into their last refuges.\n\n[Folio 202v introduces the commander Marquard and describes campaigns into the densely forested Latvian interior. Forest-dwelling communities resist fiercely but are overcome by superior German military technology. The passage reveals the difficulty and brutality of the forest campaigns.]",
  },
  "203r": {
    original: "Dy orsten alle lobben got / dy synche in yz der wulisit slor / dy in derheidischit er grin / mys geschover hat geslan... / dy selen brunen heide siwaz / dy wol en sinrile woshen / dyz waz her de slaz wurshen / dy werden in zu holden / dy bleken ar der wal gut / dy ouch suden synus sit / dy slogan manne slonks... / dy orsten wurke alle diz / dy solahe hymul dy goze dy / dy ole syme grusse / der en meister duz gemude / dy ome en listoben / dy amuste may en sroloben...",
    english: "The chronicle pauses to praise God for the victories won and to reflect on the state of the conquered territories. The author presents the conversion of the Livs and Letts as a divine triumph — the fulfillment of God’s plan for the Baltic peoples.\n\nThe heathen sacred groves have been burned, their idols smashed, and their priests silenced. Where once pagan fires blazed in forest clearings, Christian churches now stand with their crosses pointing heavenward. The people who once worshipped thunder gods and nature spirits now kneel before the altar and receive the sacraments.\n\nBut the chronicle also acknowledges that the work is far from complete. Beyond the conquered territories lie the lands of the Estonians to the north, the Curonians to the west, the Semigallians to the south, and the mighty Lithuanians beyond them all. The crusade has won its first victories, but the greatest challenges lie ahead.\n\nThe chronicle describes the internal organization of the Christian colony during this period of consolidation. The Order’s Master governs the military districts; the Bishop administers the church; and the city council of Riga manages the commercial affairs of the growing port city. This three-part structure — Order, Church, and City — will define Livonian governance for centuries.\n\nSeveral red initials on this page (‘N’, ‘G’, ‘O’, ‘Di’) mark the beginning of new narrative sections, signaling the chronicle’s transition from the conquest of the Livs and Letts to the next phase: the invasion of Estonia.\n\n[Folio 203r is a transitional page. The author praises God for victories won, acknowledges the work remaining, and describes the tripartite governance structure (Order, Church, City) of the Livonian colony. Multiple red initials mark new sections. The stage is set for the Estonian campaigns.]",
  },
  "203v": {
    original: "Do yn danebare eyn grene gut / do syme wl manechis hezde unt / hy yme en listohen / er amnist ouch dyn sluhen / dy hasse duz dy sinche my / dy de halde ouch dy brude my / dy en hab sy alle wol vor nome / dy amme sy her komm / do er ist dy wuste / dy szishe eu dy er sisten eur / der arde er ven ere / dy er meise de er rege sore...",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order’s preparations for the next phase of the crusade: the invasion of Estonian territory to the north. The Master assembled his forces at Riga, gathering the Order’s brothers, Bishop Albert’s household knights, and the annual contingent of pilgrim-crusaders from Germany.\n\nThe Estonians were a Finno-Ugric people — linguistically and culturally distinct from the Baltic-speaking Livs and Letts. They inhabited the territory north of the Gauja river, extending to the Gulf of Finland. Unlike the relatively small and fragmented Livonian tribes, the Estonians were organized into larger tribal confederacies capable of fielding substantial armies.\n\nThe chronicle describes the Estonians as fierce warriors who would prove far more difficult to conquer than the Livs or Letts. Their fortified settlements were larger and better defended, and their military leadership more effective. The campaign against Estonia would take years and cost many lives on both sides.\n\nThe Order’s Master planned a careful advance, building castles at key points to consolidate each stage of the conquest before pushing further north. The strategy was methodical: isolate each Estonian district, overwhelm it with superior force, impose baptism and tribute, build a castle, and move on to the next target.\n\nBut the Estonians had advantages the southern peoples lacked: the support of the Danes, who had their own designs on northern Estonia, and access to seaborne reinforcements from across the Gulf of Finland.\n\n[Folio 203v describes the preparations for the Estonian campaign. The Estonians are introduced as a more formidable enemy than the Livs and Letts. The Order plans a methodical advance with castle-building to consolidate each stage. The Danish factor complicates the situation.]",
  },
  "204r": {
    original: "Er selen muze got belwary / du sy sint in zwen syn geloary / dz it en wl mannel synlugern / dy dy muze en alle genilist syn / dy orel sint synmelichen dor / dy en helze er selen dy aller nor / dy yz huz musest vollesin / dy dz rede en euch dy brude syn / dy in orite du dy selde sint / dy en osle wez du ur slaz / dy en brusthe machen solze gist... / dy dy brude wort hy senite / dy lande dy die gestliel oul gar / dy welten omy er brulyr in / der sognislelson syn / dy en meise de er suisle...",
    english: "The chronicle opens the narrative of the Estonian campaigns with an invocation of God’s protection for the crusading brothers. The author prays that God will guard the Order’s knights as they march into the land of the fierce Estonians, where many a Christian warrior will fall.\n\nThe first campaigns targeted the southern Estonian districts closest to the German-held territories. The Order’s forces advanced northward from their bases in the Gauja valley, crossing into Estonian territory in force. They encountered immediate resistance — the Estonians had been warned of the German approach and had prepared their defenses.\n\nThe Estonian hill-forts were larger and more sophisticated than those the Germans had faced in Livonia. Some were reinforced with stone foundations, making them resistant to the fire attacks that had proven so effective against purely wooden fortifications. The defenders were well-armed and well-organized, fighting with a determination that the chronicle grudgingly acknowledges.\n\nThe Order’s brothers bore the brunt of the fighting. The chronicle describes individual acts of bravery and devotion — knights who charged into the teeth of the defenders’ arrows, brothers who scaled the walls of enemy fortresses under a rain of stones and boiling water. The casualties were heavy, but the advance continued.\n\nThe conquest of Estonia would prove to be the longest and bloodiest campaign of the Baltic crusade — and it would bring the German crusaders into conflict not only with the Estonians but with the Kingdom of Denmark, which had its own ambitions in the northern Baltic.\n\n[Folio 204r begins the Estonian campaign narrative. The southern Estonian districts are attacked. Estonian fortifications prove more sophisticated than Livonian ones. Heavy fighting with significant German casualties. The stage is set for the long and costly Estonian conquest.]",
  },
  "204v": {
    original: "Der bodenschaft betunge abe / v an gute grose golde habe / daz wart do vugen hure do / daz godes ein kint gemeyne vro / An harte der muest vol honne / wy yme reucle walt come nie / da er kong waldemar dy geschit / do scholde mite dy iz gesint / do boten dy wart gevangen / do der pabist in wart geleyn / er sule syne boten dar / eynen visen legat vat / der kunt der bridr vogen / da briefe von do wuschen in / eyne komere kunt y one deit / er do in eynemasten gab / der bruch dem lat begiset / er wben lyste dis kint / az hinder brudie dant / dir eigen obirleste / y geben gobe riche",
    english: "The chronicle now turns to a pivotal moment in the Estonian campaigns: the involvement of King Waldemar II of Denmark. Word had reached the Pope in Rome that the northern Estonian territories were being contested by multiple Christian powers — the Livonian Brothers of the Sword from the south, and the Danes from the north. The Pope dispatched a legate to mediate the dispute and establish clear boundaries for the missionary efforts.\n\nThe Danish king had landed at Reval (modern Tallinn) in 1219 with a formidable fleet and army, claiming the northern Estonian provinces by right of conquest. The chronicle describes the Danes' arrival with a mixture of resentment and grudging respect — they were fellow Christians, but they were also rivals for control of the lucrative Estonian territories. The Brothers of the Sword had expected to conquer all of Estonia for themselves, and the Danish intervention was an unwelcome complication.\n\nThe papal legate attempted to broker a compromise, dividing Estonia between the Danish sphere in the north and the German sphere in the south. The chronicle portrays this arrangement as deeply unsatisfactory to the Order, which felt that it had borne the heaviest burden of the fighting while the Danes arrived late to claim the richest prizes. The brothers' resentment would simmer for years.\n\nMeanwhile, the conquest of the southern Estonian districts continued. The Order's forces pushed deeper into the interior, systematically reducing Estonian hill-forts and forcing the local elders to submit to baptism. The chronicle describes the cycle of conquest, baptism, and rebellion that characterized the Estonian campaigns — districts that had been 'converted' would rise up as soon as the German forces withdrew, requiring fresh campaigns of subjugation.\n\nThe author reflects on the great cost of the Estonian wars in both treasure and blood. Many brothers had fallen, and the Order's resources were stretched thin across a vast territory. Yet the work of conversion must continue, for the glory of God demanded nothing less.\n\n[Folio 204v introduces the Danish-German rivalry over Estonia. King Waldemar II claims northern Estonia from Reval/Tallinn. A papal legate attempts to divide spheres of influence. The Order resents the Danish claims. Southern Estonian campaigns continue with cycles of conquest and rebellion.]",
  },
  "205r": {
    original: "Sich hub ein ungestuf strit / dy dugen helden funden writ / dy rufen elden grose not / daz du stige acht da in tot / dy blein of dein wal / bi isburc manie sy di val / dy aldimonie do dy bluist / an ugliste sy ein guolstit / dase ore nut mit golstory / bale mit geislin vii mit sporn / dy wente alle sru vor lorn / der wec duthe sy gar linc / dy wald wo sind stoale staz / zu linke was in alle gach / dy bruch her zogere hin nach / dy mode eyn waz y genalt / Ma eyn uber of daz lant / dy brude buren mit gewalt / sy bruihte mandy dege halt / dy von pelstzowe do / waren der geste unvro",
    english: "The chronicle describes a great and fierce battle near Izborsk, a fortified Russian stronghold close to Pskov. The Germans and their Estonian converts clashed with a Russian force that had ridden out to challenge the crusaders' advance into the borderlands. The fighting was savage — the chronicle records that eight hundred Russians fell on the field of battle, their bodies strewn across the ground near the fortress walls.\n\nThe survivors fled in desperate haste, whipping their horses with switches and spurs, convinced that all was lost. The forest echoed with their cries of anguish as they rode for their lives. The Brothers pursued them relentlessly, driving them back toward their own lands. The chronicle takes evident satisfaction in describing the panic of the fleeing Russians, their once-proud army reduced to a rout.\n\nThe Order's forces then crossed the Modde River (the Velikaya tributary) in force, entering the lands of Pskov itself. They brought many bold warriors with them, intent on punishing the men of Pskov for their interference in Estonian affairs. The Pskovians had been supporting Estonian resistance against the German crusade, providing weapons, shelter, and warriors to the pagan cause.\n\nThe people of Pskov — described as a fierce and warlike folk — were dismayed by the German advance into their territory. They had not expected the Brothers to strike so far east, and the sudden appearance of the crusading army threw the city into consternation. The chronicle notes that Pskov was a significant city in the Russian lands, well-fortified and well-populated.\n\nBishop Hermann of Dorpat accompanied the expedition with his own retinue, fighting alongside the Brothers like a hero with his warriors. The bishop's presence lent both spiritual authority and additional military strength to the campaign against the Russian borderlands.\n\n[Folio 205r describes the Battle of Izborsk — 800 Russians killed. The survivors flee in panic. The Order crosses the Modde River into Pskovian territory. Bishop Hermann of Dorpat fights alongside the Brothers. Pskov is alarmed by the German advance.]",
  },
  "205v": {
    original: "Der gute lant betunnige hab / in der meste wol bestat dat / der claget wen dy den gnaden / da iz ym ul liste musint / der er konig mit mose kare ud / y zale der noch must lage sehen / Ey stat iz graz diu wort / dy uch vin in rize lant / dy schotten in dy iz gesant / Alexander dug genant / der bo der erit als ey konig hys / in volk der sy beraten his / der ruzen waz er plade lyt / snelle worte sy betat / do dur konig alexander / ay stun ul mano du der",
    english: "The chronicle now introduces one of the most significant figures in the Baltic conflicts: Alexander Nevsky, here called simply 'Alexander' and described as a duke (prince) who bore himself as a king. The Russian prince had been watching the German advance into the Pskov borderlands with growing alarm, and he now began to assemble a mighty host to challenge the Order's expansion.\n\nThe author acknowledges Alexander's reputation and power with a mixture of respect and foreboding. The Russian prince was no ordinary opponent — he commanded vast resources and the loyalty of fierce warriors from Novgorod and the surrounding Russian principalities. His people were described as bold and swift to act, their preparations for war carried out with impressive speed.\n\nThe chronicle records how the men of Pskov sent urgent appeals to Alexander for aid against the German invaders. The Pskovians had suffered grievously from the Order's campaigns, their lands ravaged and their people forced to submit to foreign rule. Alexander answered their call, recognizing that the German advance threatened not just Pskov but the entire western frontier of the Russian lands.\n\nThe Russian prince gathered his forces — knights, mounted archers, and foot soldiers from across the Novgorodian realm. The chronicle describes the Russian army as vast and well-equipped, a formidable force that would test the Order's military prowess to its limits. Alexander's swift response caught the Brothers by surprise; they had not expected such a rapid and powerful counterstroke.\n\nThe stage was being set for one of the most famous confrontations in Baltic history — the clash between the Teutonic Order and Alexander Nevsky that would determine the eastern boundary of the German crusade for generations to come.\n\n[Folio 205v introduces Alexander Nevsky as the great Russian opponent. Pskov appeals to him for help against the German advance. Alexander assembles a massive army from Novgorod. The chronicle foreshadows the decisive confrontation between the Order and the Russian prince.]",
  },
  "206r": {
    original: "Mespa hernia halle / der rusen in dem walke / mit rizen bude mit heyden / dy grimiste her sich heyden / ir grozene velunge heren / dy elsen gous wende heren / der bischop vin der koniges mit / wes dos inne der begin / daz er mals alder ober er / da busch piger daz vin war / da es were sersthalp wr / der most vinden balez vit / sin musil her von der welikstet / ym suyn gosen orben / dy al vu ud genaden sin lerer / da hoinilichts crane / dy gyt gite vin ey lone",
    english: "The chronicle describes the gathering of Alexander Nevsky's coalition army, which included not only Russians from Novgorod and Pskov but also allied pagan peoples — Finns, Karelians, and other northern tribes who had their own reasons to oppose the German advance. The author notes with evident disgust that Christians (the Russians) were fighting alongside heathens against fellow Christians (the Germans), a theme that runs throughout the chronicle's treatment of the Russian conflicts.\n\nBishop Hermann of Dorpat and the king's men (likely referring to the Danish contingent) learned of the massive Russian mobilization. The intelligence was alarming — Alexander's host was far larger than anything the Order could field in the region. The Brothers found themselves outnumbered, their garrisons scattered across a vast territory while the enemy concentrated an overwhelming force.\n\nThe Order's Master assessed the situation and recognized the grave danger. The German forces in the eastern districts were exposed and vulnerable. He ordered a consolidation of forces, pulling back garrisons from outlying posts to create a more concentrated defensive position. The chronicle portrays this as a prudent military decision rather than a retreat, though the loss of recently conquered territory was painful.\n\nThe Brothers prepared for the coming confrontation with prayer and determination. The chronicle describes their spiritual preparations — confessions heard, masses said, the brothers committing their souls to God before what they knew would be a terrible battle. The Order's discipline and faith would be tested against Alexander's numbers and ferocity.\n\nThe author pauses to lament the situation: good Christian knights forced to fight against such overwhelming odds, far from home, in a frozen and hostile land. Yet their cause was righteous, and God would surely reward their sacrifice.\n\n[Folio 206r describes Alexander's coalition army including pagan allies. The Order recognizes it is outnumbered. Bishop Hermann and the Brothers consolidate forces. Spiritual preparations for the coming battle. The chronicle laments the odds facing the German crusaders.]",
  },
  "206v": {
    original: "Ey tag ware do gester / wen eyn man solde syn bereit / do boten worden do gesant / noch sinen den payn veslant / dy orsten bute ornamente / daz was daz alder her er spie / dy bischop vin die konig man / iz man dy rete vor sane / da es latte drynevillis hole / dy bruh her was ouch zu lande / daz sy quone aln eyne / daz sy dy ruzen sten an",
    english: "The chronicle describes the final preparations on the eve of battle. A day was appointed when every man should be ready for combat. Messengers were sent throughout the German-held territories to summon every available knight and soldier. The finest equipment and ornaments of war were brought out — polished armor, sharpened swords, and the sacred banners of the Order.\n\nThe bishop's men and the king's contingent joined forces with the Brothers of the Sword, forming the combined Christian army that would face Alexander's host. The chronicle emphasizes the unity of purpose among the German forces — despite the rivalries between the Order, the bishops, and the Danish representatives, all recognized that they faced a common and deadly enemy.\n\nThe Brothers who had been stationed across the countryside were recalled to the main force. The chronicle describes how they rode in from their scattered garrisons, each bringing whatever forces they could muster. The army assembled was smaller than Alexander's but comprised the finest warriors in the Baltic — disciplined, heavily armored knights supported by mounted sergeants and local auxiliaries.\n\nThe decision was made to stand against the Russians rather than withdraw further. The chronicle portrays this as a moment of collective resolve — the Brothers would not abandon the lands they had won with so much blood and sacrifice. They would meet Alexander's army in open battle and trust in God's justice to deliver them victory.\n\nThe Order's forces moved out to confront the Russian advance, their columns marching through the frozen landscape toward the fateful encounter. The brothers rode in formation, their armor gleaming, their banners flying, ready to face whatever God had ordained for them.\n\n[Folio 206v describes the eve of the great battle. All available forces summoned. The bishop's men and king's contingent unite with the Brothers. The Order resolves to stand and fight rather than retreat. The army marches out to meet Alexander Nevsky's host.]",
  },
  "207r": {
    original: "An muze man en legen vor / du daz sy arlen of dy bor / daz sy den tout enpfengen / dy sin yn gruzen / du ungiste manie stan isch / dy mulen mullen duit / iz nam en orten erist was / er manie wart genant / dy muge sin dy bay strulant / en dy her do du huse stat / da ez ym ouch yn sagen sal / daz sin wulle werde daz vol / der er sinde ouch dy vulle belwary / daz sy mydoste wolte dary / iz kwa ein burg i bunkist / au iston ist sy genant",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's siege tactics against the Estonian and Russian fortifications. The Brothers laid siege to strongholds, surrounding them until the defenders were forced to fight or perish. The methods were brutal and systematic — cutting off supply lines, burning the surrounding countryside, and launching repeated assaults against the walls.\n\nThe fortress of Ungannia (Ugaunia, the region around Dorpat/Tartu) became a particular focus of the fighting. The chronicle names specific strongholds that were attacked and describes the fierce resistance of their defenders. The Estonians and their Russian allies fought with desperate courage, knowing that defeat meant subjugation and forced conversion.\n\nThe Brothers employed a combination of military force and diplomatic cunning. Some Estonian elders were persuaded to submit through promises of favorable treatment, while others were subdued only after prolonged sieges. The chronicle records the names of several fortified places that fell to the Order, each conquest extending German control deeper into Estonian territory.\n\nThe Order established garrisons in the captured fortresses, leaving small detachments of brothers and their retainers to hold each position. These isolated garrisons were vulnerable to counterattack, and the chronicle records several instances where Estonian rebels besieged or overwhelmed German-held positions, massacring the defenders.\n\nThe forest warfare that characterized the Estonian campaigns is vividly described — ambushes in the dense woodlands, sudden raids on isolated settlements, the constant threat of attack from an enemy who knew the terrain intimately. The brothers rode through forests where every shadow might conceal an archer, every clearing might be a trap.\n\n[Folio 207r details siege warfare in Ungannia/Ugaunia region. Estonian fortresses are systematically reduced. Garrisons established in captured positions. Forest warfare and ambushes characterize the campaign. Estonian resistance remains fierce despite German advances.]",
  },
  "207v": {
    original: "Do er der selden bunges hy / do es come hoster men sy / dy ontugal vine vras aus / daz sy pshelde en duse baz / dy oschon brihtin vuzen / in gsilt in helde garstin / daz sy bridin beruer do ist rist / dy brumf ader slecht / dy sallen oben du ire banen / ich kam ouch inde mek gemie / en galir alle alsem mut / wer wy gegen in der bruch guit / dy slage vilsit scin sly / dy dugiste sint diz macht gul / zu niclin dir erman / dy du bruo de vurst hunan",
    english: "The chronicle turns to a critical episode: the Estonian elders' attempt to negotiate with the Order. Seeing their fortresses fall one by one, some Estonian leaders sought terms of surrender. They came before the Brothers bearing gifts and offering to accept baptism in exchange for peace and the preservation of some measure of self-governance.\n\nThe Order's response was mixed. Some brothers favored accepting the submission and proceeding with mass baptism — after all, conversion was the stated purpose of the entire crusade. Others argued that the Estonians could not be trusted, that they had submitted and rebelled before, and that only complete military subjugation would ensure lasting peace.\n\nThe chronicle describes the elaborate ceremony of submission: Estonian elders kneeling before the Brothers, laying down their weapons, receiving the sacrament of baptism. Banners were raised over the conquered territories, and crosses erected at crossroads and hilltops as visible symbols of the new Christian order. The author presents these scenes as triumphs of faith, though the underlying coercion is evident.\n\nYet even as some districts submitted, others continued to resist. The Estonians of the island of Ösel (Saaremaa) remained defiant, protected by the sea and their formidable maritime skills. The northern Estonian districts under Danish influence had their own complicated relationship with the crusade. The patchwork of submission and resistance made the Order's task enormously complex.\n\nThe chronicle records that the Brothers' losses continued to mount. The campaign in Estonia was consuming men and resources at an alarming rate, and reinforcements from Germany were slow to arrive. Yet the Order pressed on, driven by religious conviction and the promise of territorial gains.\n\n[Folio 207v describes Estonian surrender negotiations. Mass baptisms follow submission. Some districts remain defiant, especially Ösel/Saaremaa. The Order faces mounting losses and stretched resources. The patchwork nature of conquest — submission in one district, rebellion in the next.]",
  },
  "208r": {
    original: "Dy gatten muhit ungenach / daz zu enpfielen dy geschach / daz os sy vuzen rose / dy gegen eygentliche durse / dy name sy inne ungeheit / dy elehte statin say greit / dy degen en buntch / dy bruste manhy degen / daz sy gen en vunt dal / dy vustent nach der muze mule / dy sluge macht on ungedinck / dy vauste ey goden du in slit / dy beschope mahe lut / eu werne ey genchen do dy / wy dy en surte solde leden / dy isen got und himmilriche / dy eu rufen noch eyn spor / er herschape nahe munte / dy vaiste ey zum du in slit",
    english: "The chronicle describes a devastating Estonian counterattack against the Order's overextended forces. The pagans struck back with unexpected ferocity, catching the Brothers in a series of ambushes and raids that inflicted heavy casualties. The Estonian warriors, fighting on their home ground, proved to be formidable opponents — swift, cunning, and merciless.\n\nThe Germans suffered significant losses in these engagements. Many brave knights fell in the forest fighting, their heavy armor a disadvantage in the close-quarters combat of the Estonian woodlands. The chronicle mourns the fallen brothers by name in some cases, praising their courage and devotion to the cause of Christ. Their deaths are presented as martyrdom — a sacrifice for God and the Church.\n\nThe bishops accompanying the expedition called for renewed determination. They preached to the surviving brothers, reminding them of their sacred mission and the heavenly rewards that awaited those who fell in the service of God. The promise of eternal glory in paradise was set against the temporal suffering of the campaign — a powerful motivator for men who genuinely believed in the crusading ideal.\n\nThe chronicle records that the Order's leadership debated whether to continue the advance or consolidate their gains. The Estonian resistance had proven far more tenacious than anticipated, and the approaching winter threatened to make campaigning impossible. The frozen lakes and snow-covered forests of Estonia were treacherous terrain for heavily armored knights.\n\nDespite the setbacks, the Order chose to press forward. The chronicle attributes this decision to divine inspiration — God would not abandon His faithful servants in their hour of need. Fresh reinforcements were expected from Germany, and the spring thaw would bring new opportunities for conquest.\n\n[Folio 208r describes a major Estonian counterattack. Heavy German losses in forest warfare. Bishops rally the surviving brothers with promises of martyrdom. The Order debates whether to advance or consolidate. Despite setbacks, the decision is made to continue the campaign.]",
  },
  "208v": {
    original: "Dy swevedur grew / du mis schilest en praw / du unt delvngs yscleget / en kais unt soken en grisgen / Got halse zu glu muniht vruos / du sy schulte wol den jure / dy dariude shav dar / du ey den goldin yu er gruit / dy sinen mus dez wunez brint / dy gulden er stief ul wol / dy volen gallen sy ouh dy zol / geide wise dy in guit / dy grigen beide aburge un bluit / dy namen volde grose Galt / du manen wulliz gure leit / du biristen sy mir ein hey / dy wart getult muhil gelvn / dy daz hin sy striten do",
    english: "The chronicle shifts to describe the material costs of the Estonian campaigns and the Order's efforts to sustain its military operations. The Sword Brothers required enormous resources — weapons, armor, horses, provisions, and most importantly, a steady supply of fresh warriors from the German-speaking lands. The author describes how the Order sent emissaries to Germany to recruit new crusaders, promising them land, salvation, and adventure.\n\nGold and treasure played a central role in financing the campaign. The chronicle mentions the wealth extracted from conquered territories — tribute from submitted Estonian districts, taxes on trade, and the confiscation of pagan temple treasures. The Brothers collected gold and silver from the surrendered Estonian strongholds, using it to fund further military operations and to send gifts to the Pope and German princes whose support was essential.\n\nThe conquered lands were divided among the Order, the bishops, and the Danish crown according to complex agreements that were constantly renegotiated. The chronicle describes disputes over the division of territory and revenue — a recurring source of friction that undermined the Christian coalition's effectiveness. Each party felt entitled to more than it received, and the squabbling weakened the crusade at critical moments.\n\nNew fortifications were constructed throughout the conquered districts, built with a combination of local labor (often forced) and imported German craftsmen. The chronicle describes castles rising from the Estonian landscape — stone-and-timber fortresses that would serve as both military strongholds and administrative centers for the new German-dominated order.\n\nThe chapter closes with the Order preparing for the next phase of the campaign, having secured enough territory and resources to sustain continued operations. The brothers looked northward toward the remaining unconquered Estonian districts, where the hardest fighting still lay ahead.\n\n[Folio 208v covers the economics of crusade — recruiting, financing, and territorial division. Estonian treasure confiscated. Disputes over division of conquered lands among Order, bishops, and Danes. New fortifications built. The Order prepares for the next campaign phase.]",
  },
  "209r": {
    original: "An menis daz du ongen mit / er solde muge daz vinlest hat / iz woll hin ein ungisalden / vun wollen vin dy gruwashen / vil sire en dir er orstuinke / ist mancher hire en daz lant / dy sorge sint daz wol lesit / dy alestem dy daz an vf gert / dy hlose sy mugt dy nicht belen / dy dru wisit sy dit do / dy Brome litderen wert / er connis haze dits besort / dy in dem erstuinme / dy butten sy wirt minne / dy drosthy hy dy konige selt / der waz grimes milder nicht",
    english: "The chronicle opens a new chapter in the Baltic wars by turning to the conflict between the Order and the pagan Lithuanians. The Lithuanian tribes, still unconverted and fiercely independent, had been watching the German advance through Estonia and Livonia with growing alarm. Their own lands lay to the south, and they understood that they would be the next target of the crusading movement.\n\nThe Lithuanian princes — described as cunning and warlike — began launching preemptive raids against the Order's southern flank. They struck at the newly converted Livonian territories, burning settlements, killing German settlers, and encouraging the recently baptized pagans to renounce Christianity and rejoin their old faith. The chronicle portrays these raids as acts of diabolical malice, inspired by Satan's desire to undo the work of God.\n\nThe Order found itself fighting on multiple fronts: the ongoing Estonian campaigns to the north, Russian threats from the east, and now Lithuanian raids from the south. The Brothers' resources were stretched dangerously thin, and the chronicle laments the impossibility of defending every frontier simultaneously. Each victory in one theater was offset by a setback in another.\n\nThe chronicle describes the Lithuanian warriors with a mixture of fear and contempt. They were skilled horsemen and fearsome fighters, but they were pagans who worshipped false gods and practiced barbaric rites. The author emphasizes the religious dimension of the conflict — this was not merely a territorial war but a cosmic struggle between Christ and the forces of darkness.\n\nThe Order's leadership recognized that Lithuania posed the greatest long-term threat to the crusading enterprise in the Baltic. Unlike the Estonians and Livonians, the Lithuanians had a unified political structure under powerful grand dukes, making them far more difficult to defeat and absorb.\n\n[Folio 209r transitions to the Lithuanian wars. Lithuania launches preemptive raids against the Order's southern territories. The Brothers fight on multiple fronts — Estonia, Russia, Lithuania. Lithuanian warriors described as skilled but pagan. Lithuania recognized as the greatest long-term threat to the crusade.]",
  },
  "209v": {
    original: "Deu gulden lengeleme / ich daz misterne / dy medele unde duge / daz megen wol en grusze / du longen die lande / wis daz sy ger solde sinde / do sy vin quame dy maben / daz sy en nut ouch sagen / dy leut lenges suncen sy do / er volk sy bilben lisir do / lengedrin do wart gedurt / der heer herte dugerut / dy ein phot gessen / daz hoistslaz wart vin gessen",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Semigallian and Curonian peoples — Baltic tribes to the south of the Livonian territories — and their uneasy relationship with the Order. These peoples had initially submitted to baptism under duress but remained deeply hostile to German rule. The author characterizes them as cunning and treacherous, willing to feign submission while secretly plotting rebellion.\n\nThe Semigallians in particular were a constant thorn in the Order's side. Their lands lay along the crucial overland route connecting the German settlements in Livonia with Prussia, making their territory strategically vital. The chronicle describes how Semigallian raiders would ambush German supply convoys and merchant caravans, disappearing into the forests before the Brothers could respond.\n\nA major Semigallian raid is described in detail. A large force of warriors descended upon a German-held district, burning settlements and killing or capturing the inhabitants. The Brothers organized a retaliatory expedition, riding out with their full strength to punish the raiders and reassert control over the territory.\n\nThe resulting engagement was fierce and bloody. The Semigallians fought with characteristic ferocity, refusing to yield even when outnumbered. The chronicle describes the clash of arms, the cries of the wounded, and the chaos of close-quarters combat in the forested terrain. Both sides suffered heavy casualties before the Semigallians finally withdrew into the deep forests.\n\nThe Order's victory was hollow — the Semigallians had escaped with much of their plunder, and their capacity for further raids remained undiminished. The chronicle laments the seemingly endless cycle of raid and retaliation that characterized the southern frontier, draining resources that were desperately needed elsewhere.\n\n[Folio 209v covers the Semigallian and Curonian threat on the Order's southern flank. Semigallian raiders attack supply routes. A major retaliatory expedition results in a bloody but inconclusive engagement. The cycle of raid and retaliation drains the Order's resources.]",
  },
  "210r": {
    original: "Daz er sy muemelich hat / der woiz man mir dissort / dy duclite alle gslede do / dy en mesfor bruste wiste diu / dy trazen dinne bruste / en dem osin assture / in den vor genanden walt / dy geschilt halte belalt / do blinder dy ul wol belint / dy warin anit lenand wirt / dy macht hiz en dy morge do / der morgen ane brich / wele den tug mde brunne slach / dy mauhn len geloinen / dy oher lag en deu gunres",
    english: "The chronicle continues with the aftermath of the Semigallian campaign. The Order's forces, exhausted from the fighting, made camp in the forest and tended to their wounded. The brothers kept watch through the night, their shields and armor still strapped on, expecting a renewed attack at any moment. The darkness of the Baltic forest was absolute, and every sound carried the threat of ambush.\n\nAt dawn, the Brothers discovered the full extent of their losses. Many good knights had fallen in the previous day's fighting, and the wounded required immediate attention. The chronicle describes the grim morning scene — brothers praying over their fallen comrades, the camp physicians working to save those who could be saved, the burial of the dead in hasty graves marked with wooden crosses.\n\nThe Order's leadership decided to press deeper into Semigallian territory rather than withdraw. The chronicle presents this as a bold decision — the Brothers would not be intimidated by the previous day's resistance. They advanced through the forest in battle formation, their scouts ranging ahead to detect ambushes, their flanks guarded by mounted sergeants.\n\nThe Semigallians had retreated to their hill-fort, a formidable wooden fortification built atop a steep-sided mound. The chronicle describes the fortress with grudging admiration — its walls were thick, its position nearly impregnable, and its defenders well-supplied with weapons and provisions. The Brothers settled in for a siege, surrounding the fortress and cutting off all routes of escape or resupply.\n\nThe siege dragged on for days. The chronicle records the monotony and danger of siege warfare — the constant vigilance, the sporadic sorties by the defenders, the Brothers' attempts to set fire to the wooden walls with flaming arrows and pitch-soaked bundles.\n\n[Folio 210r describes the aftermath of battle — casualties tended, dead buried. The Order advances deeper into Semigallian territory. A Semigallian hill-fort is besieged. The chronicle describes the fortress and the grinding siege warfare that follows.]",
  },
  "210v": {
    original: "Daz was eu lite inde ungenach / sin daz eyn duit qu ruge geslach / Eyn lengeloin an ome stue sid / al iz den bruch do man iz / in eyn sunduln ben dy sach / daz qua syn haz en dy ngemas / her er sinsit dy wilden wol not / in bruch wer geslagen hot / er sullgirs magen dy selegen / dy eugelvms bruch wol sagen / dy aste ger dy muz ve legen / zu alst wisen in den lande / her slede dy sun dy slande / daz lengeloin dy ale vo nam / en haz en ey gros clam qut",
    english: "The chronicle recounts a decisive assault on the Semigallian hill-fort. After days of siege, the Brothers launched a coordinated attack. The assault came at dawn, with multiple columns striking the fortress walls simultaneously. The fighting was savage — the defenders hurled stones, spears, and boiling water down upon the attackers, while the Brothers struggled to scale the wooden palisades with ladders and grappling hooks.\n\nThe breakthrough came when a section of the wall, weakened by fire, collapsed under the weight of the German assault. The Brothers poured through the breach, their swords cutting down the defenders in the narrow confines of the fortress interior. The chronicle describes the carnage in vivid terms — the Semigallian warriors fighting to the last, their women and children cowering in the central buildings as the battle raged around them.\n\nThe fall of the hill-fort was a significant victory for the Order, but it came at a heavy price. Many brothers had fallen in the assault, and the fortress itself was largely destroyed in the fighting. The surviving Semigallian defenders were killed or captured, their leaders executed as an example to other would-be rebels.\n\nThe Order moved to consolidate its control over the conquered Semigallian district. Garrisons were established, tribute demands imposed, and the local population ordered to present themselves for baptism. The chronicle records these administrative measures with satisfaction, presenting them as the natural and righteous consequences of victory.\n\nYet the author acknowledges that the Semigallian problem was far from solved. Other hill-forts remained unconquered, other clans remained defiant, and the dense forests of Semigallia provided endless hiding places for guerrilla resistance. The war would continue.\n\n[Folio 210v describes the storming of the Semigallian hill-fort. A wall breach enables the German assault. Fierce fighting inside the fortress. The fort falls but at heavy cost. The Order consolidates control but acknowledges the ongoing Semigallian resistance.]",
  },
  "211r": {
    original: "Her es hure wol dunnestut ma / en geras diss her er an / dir den selben muthe / was hast daz sy genanne / dy bruis meisin sobilden tot / er ereil brusim mit gaz not / dy bruste hein dy mere / iz vine worde wol bekant / dy warin anit lenand wirt / dy macht hiz en dy morge do / der morgen ane brich / dy suter dy daz munelichen / daz woheup vrlunde dy me guit / dy vridest oub dir es silte / dy bruit noch dy en knestileg",
    english: "The chronicle shifts focus to the internal politics of the Order and its relationship with the broader Church hierarchy. The Master of the Sword Brothers faced mounting pressure from multiple directions — the Pope demanded results in converting the pagans, the German princes expected returns on their investment in the crusade, and the Danish king insisted on his territorial claims in northern Estonia.\n\nThe Brothers' reputation had suffered from reports of brutality and mismanagement that had reached Rome. Papal legates had filed critical reports about the Order's conduct — accusations of excessive violence against converts, failure to properly instruct the baptized in Christian doctrine, and disputes with the bishops over jurisdiction and revenue. The chronicle addresses these criticisms defensively, insisting that the Brothers acted only as necessity demanded.\n\nA delegation was sent to Rome to plead the Order's case before the Pope. The brothers argued that the harsh conditions of the Baltic frontier required harsh measures, and that the critics sitting comfortably in their European palaces had no understanding of the realities of crusading warfare. The Pope was sympathetic but insisted on reforms — better treatment of converts, more cooperation with the bishops, and clearer boundaries between secular and ecclesiastical authority.\n\nMeanwhile, the Order's military situation continued to deteriorate. The Lithuanian raids were growing bolder, the Semigallians remained rebellious, and the Estonian territories required constant vigilance against revolt. The chronicle describes a sense of encirclement — enemies on every side, allies who were unreliable, and resources that were never sufficient.\n\nThe author reflects on the spiritual dimension of these trials, comparing the Brothers' suffering to that of the early Christian martyrs. Their faith was being tested in the fires of adversity, and only those who endured would earn their heavenly reward.\n\n[Folio 211r covers the Order's internal politics and relations with Rome. Papal criticism of the Brothers' conduct. A delegation sent to plead their case. Military situation deteriorates on all fronts. The chronicle frames the Order's struggles as a test of faith.]",
  },
  "211v": {
    original: "Bruder andris was her gente / dy wu dan geborn von mulat / her er was des libes gar sy hest / An menie do her wart in dest / briste worden dy garstin / dy bulinge sy zu bleben / dy drusit sy gegen en slant / daz er quen horen dy gesint / dy sy ein gute ongenomgen / der in der meistur was daz / dy briese und do vin lag / inde ber den andrin briden dy / dy werle als gein enie dez",
    english: "The chronicle introduces Brother Andreas von Felben (also known as Andreas von Stirland in some sources), who became the new Master of the Livonian Brothers of the Sword. He is described as a man of noble birth, physically strong and spiritually devoted — qualities that would be tested to their limits in the trials ahead.\n\nBrother Andreas inherited a dire situation. The Order was engaged in simultaneous conflicts on multiple fronts, its treasury was depleted, and morale among the brothers was flagging after years of inconclusive warfare. The new Master immediately set about reorganizing the Order's defenses and renewing diplomatic contacts with potential allies.\n\nThe chronicle describes Andreas's leadership style — he was a hands-on commander who led from the front, sharing the hardships of his men and fighting alongside them in battle. He visited the Order's scattered garrisons, inspecting their defenses and boosting the spirits of the brothers stationed in remote and dangerous outposts.\n\nOne of Andreas's first priorities was to address the Order's relationship with the bishops and the Danish authorities. The endless squabbling over territory and jurisdiction had weakened the Christian cause, and the new Master sought to forge a united front against the pagan threat. The chronicle records his diplomatic efforts with approval, noting that he was willing to make concessions for the greater good.\n\nThe Master also sent urgent appeals to Germany for reinforcements. The crusading movement in the Baltic needed fresh blood — new brothers to replace the fallen, new pilgrims to bolster the armies, and new resources to sustain the military effort. The chronicle describes the response as encouraging but insufficient — some knights answered the call, but never enough to tip the balance decisively.\n\n[Folio 211v introduces Master Andreas von Felben as the new leader of the Sword Brothers. He inherits a dire military and political situation. He reorganizes defenses, seeks unity with bishops and Danes, and appeals to Germany for reinforcements. A capable leader facing overwhelming challenges.]",
  },
  "212r": {
    original: "Dy naniz zu den ul druche / her er gruchst mit culwirin race / dul vist hein litwden dary / iz ey sullit nicht lenges grazy / dy ey gute druze luce / dy butte ich ouch inde / vu zu vin gras daz y gesint / zu syn elin munis ant / daz sy lengeloin de dy sculdin do / dy sulter en dy mueste iriche / dy closteu sy dy werdart / daz er enlit vu maist gesnart / du volt zu linder siunt / droyste sich der zer zves / daz iz solde vrste dary",
    english: "The chronicle describes the growing Lithuanian threat in vivid terms. The Lithuanians, emboldened by the Order's difficulties on other fronts, launched a massive raid deep into Livonian territory. The pagan army swept through the countryside like a storm, burning churches, slaughtering settlers, and carrying off livestock and captives.\n\nThe Brothers scrambled to respond, gathering what forces they could from their scattered garrisons. The chronicle emphasizes the speed and ferocity of the Lithuanian attack — it struck without warning and penetrated far beyond the frontier before the Order could organize a defense. Villages that had felt secure under German protection were suddenly exposed to the full fury of pagan warfare.\n\nThe Lithuanian war leader — described as cunning and ruthless — had timed his raid to coincide with the Order's campaigning season in Estonia, when many brothers were deployed far to the north. The skeleton garrisons left behind in Livonia were insufficient to stop the raiders, and the chronicle records the anguish of the brothers who could only watch helplessly as the enemy ravaged their lands.\n\nA relief force was eventually assembled, but by the time it reached the affected areas, the Lithuanians had already withdrawn with their plunder. The Brothers found only smoldering ruins and grieving survivors. The chronicle describes the scene with genuine emotion — burned churches, desecrated altars, and the bodies of slain Christians scattered across the blackened landscape.\n\nThe Master recognized that the Lithuanian threat required a fundamental change in strategy. The Order could no longer afford to campaign in Estonia while leaving Livonia undefended. A more balanced deployment of forces was needed, even if it meant slowing the pace of the northern conquests.\n\n[Folio 212r describes a devastating Lithuanian raid into Livonia. The attack is timed to exploit the Order's deployment in Estonia. Burned churches and slaughtered settlers. The Master recognizes the need for a strategic rebalancing of forces across multiple fronts.]",
  },
  "212v": {
    original: "Daz die line wurde der dot / dy groslage werse dy in greine / in wulbin haw do legist stat / dy barte sy gnast mat / dy orsrulist waz alle dy / dy sancitu gat sid hymul do / in der lisin mue sin / er wer base wuz in sus ne / dy slage vilsit scin sly / dy wult sin der buz ser gor / dy suncite blint vig goz / dy sunreyte blint vig guz / er eu mochte sich mast wory / daz ist der beiden erfe wil",
    english: "The chronicle describes the spiritual crisis that gripped the Order in the wake of the Lithuanian raids. Some brothers questioned whether God had abandoned their cause — how could He permit pagans to destroy His churches and murder His faithful servants? The author addresses these doubts directly, arguing that God tests those He loves most severely, and that the brothers' suffering was a sign of divine favor, not divine wrath.\n\nThe fallen brothers and murdered settlers are presented as martyrs whose blood would sanctify the land. The chronicle draws parallels with the early Church, when Christian communities endured persecution before ultimately triumphing through faith and perseverance. The message is clear: the Order must not lose heart, for God's plan unfolds in His own time.\n\nThe practical response to the crisis involved diplomatic outreach to potential allies. The Order sent envoys to the Pope, to the German emperor, and to the kings of Denmark and Sweden, seeking military assistance against the Lithuanian menace. The chronicle records the arguments made by these ambassadors — the Lithuanian threat endangered all of Christendom's gains in the Baltic, and a united Christian response was imperative.\n\nThe Pope responded by issuing a new crusading bull, calling on the faithful throughout Europe to take up arms against the Baltic pagans. The chronicle records this papal support with gratitude, noting that it brought a fresh wave of crusading volunteers to the Baltic — knights, pilgrims, and adventurers from Germany, Scandinavia, and beyond.\n\nThe Order also strengthened its fortifications along the Lithuanian frontier, building new castles and reinforcing existing ones. The chronicle describes this construction program as both a military necessity and a statement of permanence — the Brothers intended to hold their conquests against all comers.\n\n[Folio 212v addresses the spiritual crisis after the Lithuanian raids. The fallen are declared martyrs. Diplomatic appeals to the Pope and European rulers. A new crusading bull issued. Fortifications strengthened along the Lithuanian frontier.]",
  },
  "213r": {
    original: "Meyste andris der biz sin / dy egne bruid nor sin / daz dy mit eynir heruwrt / wolde zu simegatlen wart / der nosen wurde vul dut / daz lant volk gerne dy do / in sin her wart gesant / dy mesin golde der zu her wart / dy vrunt dy hin zu meslant / dy brust mde dy brides sint / daz stuge sime gallin nul / daz brut ouch alle sagen vul / dy meisten den den miester do / du mesin golde dy waz sich / dy si dy smis in gallin in sulde",
    english: "The chronicle returns to Master Andreas and his decisive campaign against the Semigallians. The Master personally led a major expedition into Semigallia, determined to break the resistance of this troublesome people once and for all. He assembled the largest force the Order could muster — brothers, pilgrim knights, converted Livonian auxiliaries, and a contingent from the bishopric.\n\nThe army marched into Semigallian territory in force, following the river valleys that served as natural invasion routes. The chronicle describes the landscape — dense forests broken by cultivated clearings, rivers bridged by the Semigallians' own skillful engineering, and the ever-present threat of ambush. The Brothers advanced cautiously, their scouts probing ahead for signs of the enemy.\n\nThe Semigallian leaders debated how to respond. Some favored submission — the Order's force was overwhelming, and further resistance seemed futile. Others argued for fighting to the death rather than accepting the yoke of foreign rule. The chronicle records these deliberations through the lens of captured Semigallian prisoners who reported on their leaders' councils.\n\nMaster Andreas offered terms: the Semigallians could submit to baptism and accept German overlordship, retaining their lands and some degree of self-governance, or they could resist and face annihilation. The chronicle presents this as a generous offer, though the underlying threat was unmistakable.\n\nThe Semigallian response was divided — some clans submitted, while others retreated deeper into the forests to continue their resistance. The pattern of partial conquest and ongoing guerrilla war that characterized the entire Baltic crusade repeated itself once again in Semigallia.\n\n[Folio 213r describes Master Andreas's major campaign into Semigallia. A large combined force assembled. The Semigallians debate submission versus resistance. Terms offered — baptism and overlordship or annihilation. Some clans submit while others continue guerrilla resistance.]",
  },
  "213v": {
    original: "Dy gune landes gente / gutse wullen sy zu den trube / do diz alles diaz vu wan / dy meist dit da lommge sun / ir ey gelashen iosen / de er dy rispen worden duo / dei abli alt ungenant nano / de eble alle ul gesmay / dy meiste bryge der brud lut / duz dy sulde verste gelesin / dy name du daz meise pslant / dy vuirst wude zu ir hant / dy pabist birke slirsin duz / vin dy sache unde hyz",
    english: "The chronicle describes the political aftermath of the Semigallian campaign and a momentous development: the growing movement to merge the Livonian Brothers of the Sword with the much larger and more powerful Teutonic Order. The Sword Brothers had suffered catastrophic losses over years of continuous warfare, and their ranks were dangerously depleted.\n\nThe merger had been discussed for some time, but the issue came to a head after the Semigallian campaigns revealed just how overstretched the Sword Brothers had become. The Order's leadership recognized that without the resources and manpower of the Teutonic Order, the German position in Livonia might collapse entirely.\n\nEmissaries were sent to the Teutonic Order's headquarters in Prussia to negotiate the terms of the merger. The chronicle records the delicate diplomacy involved — the Sword Brothers wanted to preserve their autonomy and traditions, while the Teutonic Order insisted on full integration under its rule. The Pope was asked to mediate, and papal legates shuttled between the two orders seeking a compromise.\n\nThe chronicle also describes continued military operations during this period of political uncertainty. The Brothers could not afford to pause their campaigning while the merger was negotiated — the Lithuanians and Semigallians would exploit any sign of weakness. The Order maintained its garrisons, patrolled its frontiers, and conducted punitive raids against rebellious districts.\n\nThe author reflects on the significance of the proposed merger, recognizing it as both a necessity and a loss. The Sword Brothers had forged their own identity through decades of blood and sacrifice in Livonia, and absorption into the Teutonic Order meant the end of that independent tradition. Yet survival demanded compromise.\n\n[Folio 213v covers the movement to merge the Sword Brothers with the Teutonic Order. The Sword Brothers are overstretched and depleted. Negotiations with the Teutonic Order begin. Papal mediation sought. Military operations continue during the political negotiations. The merger is seen as a necessary loss of independence.]",
  },
  "214r": {
    original: "Von synen brude eberhart / in un meslande haunt / dy ober gul en meslant / daz dy est guldes daz yn war / her er haste svest haltins sar / daz lant ul vol von stunden / daz der was her vin den landes / daz muz ul vust grunelist / dy meiste bygste der brud lut / daz er andris orlaf nam / von syn bruch al yz wol sam / zu wot zu littowen / du al stubin srint mundwicen / in ouch alli der vonigen",
    english: "The chronicle introduces Brother Eberhart, a senior commander in Livonia, and describes the Order's administrative reorganization of its Livonian territories. The conquered lands were divided into administrative districts (Vogtei), each governed by a brother-commander (Vogt) who held both military and civil authority over his domain.\n\nThe system of governance was modeled on the feudal structures familiar from Germany but adapted to the frontier conditions of the Baltic. The Vogts collected tribute from the native population, administered justice, maintained fortifications, and commanded the local garrison. The chronicle describes this administrative apparatus with approval, presenting it as a necessary framework for maintaining order in the conquered territories.\n\nMaster Andreas, recognizing that his time as leader was drawing to a close, began making arrangements for the succession. The chronicle records that he took his leave from the brothers with dignity, having served the Order faithfully through some of its most difficult years. His campaigns in Semigallia and his efforts to forge alliances had stabilized the Order's position, even if the underlying challenges remained.\n\nThe chronicle then turns to the growing threat from Lithuania once more. The Lithuanian grand duke was consolidating his power, uniting the fractious Lithuanian tribes under a single authority. This political unification made Lithuania an even more dangerous opponent — instead of dealing with scattered raiding parties, the Order now faced the prospect of a coordinated military campaign by a united Lithuanian state.\n\nThe Brothers prepared for the inevitable confrontation, strengthening their border fortresses and sending urgent appeals for reinforcements to Germany and to the Teutonic Order in Prussia.\n\n[Folio 214r describes the administrative organization of conquered Livonia into Vogtei districts. Master Andreas prepares for succession. Lithuania unifies under a grand duke, becoming a more formidable threat. The Order strengthens border defenses and appeals for reinforcements.]",
  },
  "214v": {
    original: "Daz nu mon lip in behinlet / die me man must in dunket / dy muiz diz muz ich zu lande dary / iz din got mast vul belwary / do ey vul ouch in woe blw / iz en sy den diz ich gele dn / daz ouch dy meest wurt grust / ist ouh man sulde volde lant / syn sulle doch dy az gestach / ist mit her eyn brudi nam / der er lande elim quam / dy briide dy geniople hat / daz sy do me werin sindt van / her er hette als dy wusir man",
    english: "The chronicle reflects on the personal sacrifices demanded of the Brothers who served in the Baltic. Many had left their homes in Germany never to return, giving up family, inheritance, and the comforts of civilization to fight in a remote and hostile land. The author meditates on the meaning of this sacrifice — was it truly God's will that these men should spend their lives in perpetual warfare on the edge of Christendom?\n\nThe answer, for the chronicler, is unequivocal: yes. The Brothers had been called to a holy mission, and their willingness to suffer and die for Christ's cause was the highest expression of Christian devotion. The lands they had conquered would become part of Christendom, their churches would ring with hymns of praise, and generations yet unborn would benefit from their sacrifice.\n\nThe chronicle describes the arrival of a new contingent of brothers from Germany — fresh recruits who had taken the cross and traveled to the Baltic to join the crusade. Their arrival was greeted with joy and relief by the veteran brothers, who had been fighting without adequate reinforcements for too long. The newcomers were eager and idealistic, not yet hardened by the brutal realities of frontier warfare.\n\nThe Master welcomed the new brothers and immediately assigned them to garrisons throughout the territory. The chronicle notes that some were sent to the most dangerous posts — the frontier castles facing Lithuania, where the threat of attack was constant. These assignments were both a test of the newcomers' mettle and a practical necessity.\n\nThe veteran brothers took the recruits under their guidance, teaching them the ways of Baltic warfare — how to fight in forests, how to identify ambush terrain, how to deal with the native peoples. The chronicle presents this transfer of knowledge as essential to the Order's survival.\n\n[Folio 214v reflects on the personal sacrifices of the Brothers. New recruits arrive from Germany and are deployed to frontier garrisons. Veterans mentor the newcomers in Baltic warfare. The chronicle affirms the sacred purpose of the crusading mission.]",
  },
  "215r": {
    original: "Gone burg geburt / her sich dy iz bernist / alle dy arsten dy din sint / daz bruste mich der sine blint / dy sint srude andren / wusen sy dy he besosen / ich brulle mich diz vns lat / daz sanielat dy mugs dir / dy wulle als dy brele virstn / in kurzo wile vurlen / dy leiste dy dir ey agest / wan wul inde sint / dy wolle als mit loseln / dy olestin sint grosein / linsu gusen stuelen",
    english: "The chronicle describes the construction and fortification of a new castle — one of the Order's most important strategic assets in the Baltic campaigns. The fortress was built at a carefully chosen location, commanding a river crossing or strategic pass that controlled access to the surrounding territory. The author describes the construction with evident pride.\n\nThe castle's defenses were formidable: thick stone walls rising from earthen ramparts, towers at each corner providing overlapping fields of fire, a deep ditch fed by diverted river water, and a drawbridge that could be raised in moments. The chronicle emphasizes that this was no temporary field fortification but a permanent stronghold designed to project German power across the region for generations.\n\nThe construction employed both German craftsmen and conscripted native laborers. The chronicle notes the skill of the German masons and carpenters, who brought techniques from the great building traditions of the Rhineland and Saxony. The native workers, though forced to participate, contributed their knowledge of local materials and building conditions.\n\nThe castle served multiple purposes: military stronghold, administrative center, chapel and monastery, storehouse, and refuge for the surrounding German and native Christian population in times of attack. The chronicle describes the daily life within its walls — the brothers' strict routine of prayer, training, and patrol, punctuated by the ever-present possibility of sudden combat.\n\nThe completion of the castle was celebrated with a solemn mass and the blessing of the chapel. The brothers dedicated the fortress to the Virgin Mary, as was their custom, invoking her protection over all who dwelt within its walls.\n\n[Folio 215r describes the construction of a major new castle. Formidable defenses with stone walls, towers, and a moat. German craftsmen and native laborers work together. The castle serves as military, administrative, and religious center. Dedicated to the Virgin Mary.]",
  },
  "215v": {
    original: "Daz sy in der mynulle bwern / der inute beginn den bon / dy semen of daz wilde mer / eyn teil dur zult in her / ant sy sssen den unilat / daz ist der druistsche laz genat / dy muze bazen sy do / in mynulle quatnyn / von dey mer diz vor nonme / dy brud der gemes muit / der enduchten sy necht gut / dy warim komb zu dy wait / sale dorch sturm diz duch sture / dy sach mde sruz also ful / daz sy warin az dy sol",
    english: "The chronicle turns to maritime operations — a crucial but often overlooked dimension of the Baltic crusade. The Brothers maintained a fleet of ships that patrolled the Baltic Sea and the major rivers, protecting supply lines and projecting power along the coastline. The author describes a naval expedition against the island of Ösel (Saaremaa), one of the last holdouts of Estonian paganism.\n\nThe crossing was perilous. The Brothers, accustomed to fighting on horseback, were uneasy on the open sea. The chronicle describes their discomfort with vivid honesty — the rolling waves, the seasickness that afflicted even the bravest knights, and the terrifying storms that could scatter a fleet in minutes. The Baltic Sea in winter was especially treacherous, with ice floes and sudden squalls that could sink even well-built ships.\n\nThe fleet reached Ösel after a difficult crossing and landed a force of brothers and their auxiliaries on the island's shores. The Öselians — described as the fiercest of all the Estonian peoples — met them with fierce resistance. These were a maritime people, skilled sailors and fishermen who knew every inlet and harbor of their island. They fought with the ferocity of men defending their homeland.\n\nThe campaign on Ösel proved to be one of the most difficult of the entire Estonian crusade. The island's terrain — forests, marshes, and rocky coastline — favored the defenders, and the Brothers found it impossible to bring their heavy cavalry to bear effectively. The fighting devolved into a grinding war of attrition, with neither side able to gain a decisive advantage.\n\nThe chronicle records the Brothers' frustration and exhaustion. They had expected a swift campaign but found themselves bogged down on a hostile island, far from their supply bases, fighting an enemy who refused to submit.\n\n[Folio 215v describes a naval expedition to Ösel/Saaremaa. The Brothers are uncomfortable at sea. The Öselians resist fiercely. The island's terrain favors the defenders. A grinding campaign of attrition develops. The Brothers face frustration far from their supply bases.]",
  },
  "216r": {
    original: "Dem meist vio meslant / worde brise gesant waz / lou az zur mynul vu gundes / do mde dy bruse vin gules / daz sy schud mich sal inist rage / dy sin lelin dud ich wugen / diz ouch disse sache dy vul dan / do vonmig dy hiz buren dan / dy meiste ulge dy brud sun / dy brise adair gele sru / eu hometurin dy gulse syn / dy aste hin zu lande wart / dy meiste din dy brud sun / der lauslost diy sulser syn",
    english: "The chronicle returns to events on the mainland, where the Master of Livonia received urgent dispatches from the Order's commanders. The messages carried alarming news: a new Lithuanian coalition was forming, larger and more dangerous than any previous threat. The Lithuanian grand duke had forged alliances with neighboring pagan peoples and was preparing a massive invasion of the Order's territories.\n\nThe Master immediately recalled forces from the Ösel campaign and other outlying operations, concentrating his strength to meet the Lithuanian threat. The chronicle describes the feverish preparations — garrisons reinforced, supplies stockpiled, fortifications inspected and repaired. Every available brother was summoned to the muster point.\n\nThe Order's intelligence network — a combination of scouts, informants among the native population, and captured prisoners — provided details about the Lithuanian preparations. The enemy host was assembling in the forests south of Semigallia, and its intended target appeared to be the heart of German Livonia itself. This was no mere raiding party but an army of conquest.\n\nThe chronicle describes the Master's council of war, where the senior brothers debated strategy. Some advocated a defensive posture — holding the castles and letting the Lithuanians exhaust themselves against the fortifications. Others argued for an aggressive response — meeting the enemy in the field before he could penetrate deep into Christian territory.\n\nThe Master chose the offensive option, gathering his forces for a preemptive strike against the Lithuanian assembly area. The chronicle presents this as a bold and faithful decision — the Brothers would trust in God and ride out to meet their enemies head-on.\n\n[Folio 216r describes the formation of a major Lithuanian coalition. The Master recalls forces and concentrates his strength. Intelligence reveals a large-scale Lithuanian invasion is imminent. A council of war debates defensive versus offensive strategy. The Master opts for a preemptive strike.]",
  },
  "216v": {
    original: "Dy vist run en masen gros / der her sich qu gunt druglus / du baren in daz lint / dy wart den semen bekant / daz sy grise dy in wolden scladen / diz er gese dy in walken / lant dy is wal dy heude / dy sinz ouch mit brende / der semen gosen stuladen / dy halte ganz ul gelsden / yn den lande diz iz alar / dy er rebun zu summe gut / der en az an summe lis / der hogste sone dy sunde syn",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's army marching south to intercept the Lithuanian host. The force was impressive but smaller than the enemy — the Brothers rode at its core, their armor gleaming, supported by mounted sergeants, pilgrim knights, and contingents of baptized Livonian and Estonian warriors. The column stretched for miles through the forest roads.\n\nAs the army advanced, it encountered the first signs of the Lithuanian presence: burned villages, slaughtered livestock, and the tracks of a large force moving through the countryside. The enemy was already in motion, and the Brothers realized they would have to fight sooner than expected. The chronicle describes the tension that gripped the column — every man knew that a great battle was approaching.\n\nThe Brothers deployed for combat, forming their battle line across a clearing where the terrain favored their heavy cavalry. The chronicle describes the formations with military precision — the armored knights in the center, lighter cavalry on the flanks, foot soldiers and archers in support. The sacred banner of the Order was unfurled, and the brothers commended their souls to God.\n\nThe Lithuanian host appeared from the forest — a vast and terrifying sight. The chronicle describes thousands of pagan warriors, their faces painted, their weapons gleaming, their war cries echoing through the trees. Mounted Lithuanian nobles led the force, accompanied by Semigallian and Samogitian allies who had their own grievances against the Order.\n\nThe two armies faced each other across the clearing, the silence broken only by the stamping of horses and the flutter of banners. The chronicle pauses here, building tension before the great clash that was about to unfold.\n\n[Folio 216v describes the Order's march to intercept the Lithuanians. Signs of enemy activity encountered. The Brothers deploy for battle. The Lithuanian host emerges from the forest — a vast force with Semigallian and Samogitian allies. The two armies face off before the decisive battle.]",
  },
  "217r": {
    original: "Ane snue heer zu kurlat / al lez by dez meres stunt / dy qua zu der mynulle / daz en lobiste got erd himulche / do her en den surte mene / in mir her ab zu sun man / du gua zu ruge mit der gras / dy russe pagt vnz diu buch nor / dy semayte was eyn man / der wuz ey ul dem hest / von dy semayte dez iz welt / trutz in synim herzen / butruliche snerzen",
    english: "The chronicle describes a campaign into Curonian territory, the coastal region along the Baltic Sea. The Order's forces advanced toward the Curonian settlements near the seashore, where the native people had maintained a precarious independence despite the German presence in neighboring territories. The Brothers praised God as they marched, confident that divine favor would grant them victory.\n\nThe Curonians were a seafaring people, skilled in navigation and fishing, whose culture was intimately connected to the Baltic coast. The chronicle describes their settlements — wooden villages clustered around harbors, fortified with earthen ramparts and timber palisades. The Curonians had long been pirates and raiders, terrorizing merchant shipping throughout the eastern Baltic.\n\nThe narrative then shifts to the Samogitians (Žemaitians), the westernmost of the Lithuanian peoples, whose territory lay between the Order's Livonian and Prussian branches. The Samogitians were described as the most warlike and intractable of all the Baltic peoples — fierce in battle, implacable in their hatred of Christianity, and utterly unwilling to submit to foreign rule.\n\nA Samogitian leader is introduced — a man of great personal courage who bore a deep and bitter resentment against the Order. The chronicle suggests that this enmity was rooted in past German atrocities against his people, though the author naturally presents the Samogitian perspective as misguided paganism rather than legitimate grievance.\n\nThe Samogitians began assembling a coalition of pagan peoples to strike at the Order. They sent emissaries to the Lithuanians, Semigallians, and even the unconverted Curonians, urging them to unite against the common Christian enemy. The chronicle describes this diplomatic activity with alarm — a united pagan front would be far more dangerous than any single tribe.\n\n[Folio 217r describes campaigns in Curonian territory along the Baltic coast. The Curonians are seafarers and former pirates. Focus shifts to the Samogitians — the fiercest Baltic people. A Samogitian leader assembles a pagan coalition against the Order. The threat of a united pagan front emerges.]",
  },
  "217v": {
    original: "Moste grue er bochuart / her er gelor eyne heruart / wis alle synim land in / deu sametoyn zu schuude / dy huart wart ozon gros / der der orsmist genos / eu zu rege dy samenetge waz / alle gez arme zu sin waz / du rege sy sich nu tue shin / daz er daz ouste hat genomin / mit der orsimiliche buning / du wart voul in du gesint / daz ez zu ingest adit duo / dy sin derste mul mest buken",
    english: "The chronicle describes Master Burkhart's decision to launch a major preemptive campaign into Samogitia before the pagan coalition could fully assemble. He gathered every available warrior from across the Livonian territories — brothers, pilgrim knights, baptized natives, and mercenaries — forming the largest army the Order had fielded in years.\n\nThe Master was determined to crush the Samogitian threat before it could metastasize into a general pagan uprising. The chronicle describes his preparations with admiration — he was methodical and thorough, ensuring that his army was well-provisioned and well-armed for a deep penetration into enemy territory.\n\nThe Samogitians, learning of the German advance, hastily gathered their own forces. The chronicle describes the Samogitian mobilization — every man capable of bearing arms was summoned, from grizzled veterans to young boys barely old enough to hold a spear. The women and children were sent deeper into the forests for safety, while the warriors assembled at their traditional muster points.\n\nThe two armies converged in the dense forests of Samogitia. The chronicle describes the terrain with dread — endless woodland, marshy ground that could swallow a horse and rider, narrow paths that turned every march into a potential death trap. This was the Samogitians' home ground, and they knew every trail, every ford, every hiding place.\n\nThe stage was set for the Battle of Saule (Šiauliai), one of the most catastrophic defeats in the history of the crusading orders. The chronicle's tone shifts from confident to ominous as the army penetrates deeper into Samogitian territory, unknowingly marching toward disaster.\n\n[Folio 217v describes Master Burkhart's preemptive campaign into Samogitia. The largest Livonian army assembled. Samogitians mobilize in response. The armies converge in dense forest terrain. The chronicle foreshadows the catastrophic Battle of Saule (1236).]",
  },
  "218r": {
    original: "Do such man dey erste brut / eu brisze eynis gnodeniz hat / in eynis kurfsez dir nach / dy borste waz dy alle grish / dy naz er rospen warim borni / daz gich vor waz gate nor nomy / daz dy her diz waz vol wart / in allen inden geslatt / daz gore her der or simhest / dy bule macht dege vent / do wart voidest ul geslumhist / in wis linde finder / vuze inde allin stunde trugen / licht en moste svurt ge",
    english: "The chronicle describes the opening phase of the Battle of Saule (September 22, 1236). The Order's vanguard encountered the first Samogitian forces — a screen of light warriors who harassed the German column with arrows and javelins before melting back into the forest. The Brothers pressed forward, believing these to be mere skirmishers.\n\nThe trap was sprung when the main German force entered a marshy clearing surrounded by dense forest on all sides. The Samogitians had chosen the battlefield with devastating cunning — the soft ground negated the Germans' advantage in heavy cavalry, while the surrounding forest provided perfect concealment for the pagan army.\n\nThe chronicle describes the terrifying moment when the full scale of the Samogitian ambush became apparent. Warriors emerged from the trees on every side, their war cries filling the forest. The Germans found themselves surrounded, their formations disrupted by the treacherous ground, unable to charge or maneuver their heavy warhorses effectively.\n\nThe fighting was desperate and chaotic. The Brothers fought on foot when their horses became mired in the marsh, their heavy armor now a deadly liability rather than an advantage. The Samogitians pressed in from all directions, their lighter equipment allowing them to move freely across the boggy terrain while the Germans struggled.\n\nThe chronicle records the carnage with horror — brother after brother fell, their armor pierced by Lithuanian spears and swords. The Order's battle line began to collapse as units were overwhelmed and destroyed piecemeal. The sacred banner of the Order wavered and fell, sending a shock of despair through the surviving defenders.\n\n[Folio 218r describes the Battle of Saule (1236). The Order walks into a Samogitian ambush in marshy terrain. Heavy cavalry is negated by soft ground. The Germans are surrounded and their formations collapse. The Order's banner falls. A catastrophic defeat unfolds.]",
  },
  "218v": {
    original: "Sin orden moste en beyni sint / in ey caplan ber do hat / dy sirdiin bruse en hant / dey bonentuin in dy lant / dy ey ouch dy herust / in de mur der waz garize / dy iste vu sire erbannen / dy walie als dy horten beyen / du sire bunuiy zu hant / dy brud dy den meister sy / daz ey brud dy vin waten by / dy brude ger der meistur sin / de eu brude gert du pruzen / vol mit den heiden plesiten",
    english: "The chronicle describes the devastating aftermath of the Battle of Saule. Master Volkwin (Burkhart) himself fell on the field — the first and only Master of the Livonian Brothers of the Sword to die in battle. With him perished the Order's chaplain and dozens of brother-knights, the core of the Livonian military establishment. The chronicle records the names of the fallen with grief and reverence.\n\nThe destruction of the Order's field army was nearly total. Of the brothers who had marched into Samogitia, fewer than a handful escaped the slaughter. The baptized native auxiliaries — Livonians, Estonians, and Curonians who had fought alongside the Germans — suffered equally terrible losses. Many of the survivors immediately renounced their forced conversion and returned to paganism.\n\nThe news of the catastrophe spread rapidly through the Baltic. In Livonia, the remaining brothers barricaded themselves in their castles, expecting the pagans to sweep through the countryside. The chronicle describes the panic that gripped the German settlements — merchants fled to the ports, settlers abandoned their farms, and the bishops prepared for the worst.\n\nThe Battle of Saule had shattered the Livonian Brothers of the Sword as an independent military force. The Order lacked the manpower, resources, or leadership to recover from such a blow. The chronicle acknowledges this reality with bitter frankness — the proud Order that had conquered Livonia and Estonia was effectively destroyed in a single afternoon.\n\nThe only hope for the surviving brothers lay in the merger with the Teutonic Order that had been discussed for years. Now, with the Sword Brothers reduced to a handful of garrison troops, the merger was no longer a matter of choice but of survival. Emissaries were dispatched to Prussia to beg the Teutonic Order for absorption.\n\n[Folio 218v describes the aftermath of Saule. Master Volkwin killed — the Order's leadership destroyed. Near-total annihilation of the field army. Panic across German Livonia. Native converts renounce Christianity. The Sword Brothers are effectively destroyed. Merger with the Teutonic Order becomes the only path to survival.]",
  },
  "219r": {
    original: "Daz hatte meistur amne / ul wol glich eynn muine / sy er den der uur genigen / dy his der war bare sagen / Der gute meist burkart / vins bein meslande wart / deu gauinizen daz sy genant / do quit dit er duz vinilant / do al me gude enrs / daz er irmil wol brusgang hat / dy nu vor dumine ey mer slat / en lop sint ane eit / zu prizen dit zu meslant / waz in sint lop ul wol belant",
    english: "The chronicle pauses to deliver a eulogy for the fallen Master Burkhart (Volkwin) and the Brothers who perished at Saule. The author praises the Master's courage, faith, and devotion to the Order's mission, presenting his death as a martyrdom that would be rewarded in heaven. The fallen brothers are compared to the early Christian saints who shed their blood for the faith.\n\nThe narrative then describes the formal merger of the remnants of the Livonian Brothers of the Sword with the Teutonic Order. The Pope approved the union, and the surviving Sword Brothers accepted the Teutonic Order's rule, adopting its white mantle with the black cross in place of their own red sword emblem. The chronicle marks this transition as both a death and a rebirth — the end of the Sword Brothers' independent existence, but the beginning of a new chapter under a far more powerful and organized institution.\n\nThe Teutonic Order's response to the crisis was swift and decisive. The Grand Master dispatched a contingent of experienced brothers from Prussia to Livonia, along with supplies, weapons, and treasure to rebuild the shattered defenses. These Prussian brothers brought a different military culture — more disciplined, better organized, and backed by the vast resources of the Teutonic Order's European network.\n\nThe new Livonian Master — now a provincial commander subordinate to the Grand Master in Prussia — immediately set about reorganizing the Order's territories. Castles were repaired and re-garrisoned, frontier defenses strengthened, and diplomatic relations with the bishops and the Danish crown restored.\n\nThe chronicle notes that the merger brought the Livonian crusade under the protection of one of the most powerful military organizations in medieval Europe. The Teutonic Order's reputation, resources, and recruiting networks gave the Baltic crusade a second chance.\n\n[Folio 219r eulogizes Master Volkwin and the fallen of Saule. The Sword Brothers formally merge with the Teutonic Order. Prussian brothers arrive in Livonia with reinforcements. A new provincial Master reorganizes the defenses. The Teutonic Order gives the Baltic crusade a second life.]",
  },
  "219v": {
    original: "Dy kolsen norne diu gen / iz er gons hose vol vnz vin / do werin bruder slur al / Emrig was in alle zal dunt / er er haste ouch wol dunsint / Euir dy ge sindir / do der morgen an brach / dy samestein hy man sach / dy meiste sist wer sur genieze / dez ist alie mos su nicht / ist smue leibe dy sich dot / dy smut vruise dy haz bose",
    english: "The chronicle describes the immediate aftermath of the merger with the Teutonic Order and the arrival of the new leadership in Livonia. The surviving Sword Brothers — numbering barely a few dozen — formally submitted to the Teutonic Order's authority, receiving new mantles and swearing new oaths. The transition was emotional and difficult — these men had built the Sword Brothers' legacy with their own blood.\n\nBrother Hermann Balk was appointed as the first Teutonic Order Landmeister (Provincial Master) of Livonia. He arrived with a retinue of experienced Prussian brothers and immediately set about restoring order. The chronicle praises his energy and competence — within days of his arrival, he was inspecting fortifications, reviewing garrison strengths, and dispatching patrols to the frontiers.\n\nThe morning after his arrival, the new Master surveyed the full extent of the damage wrought by the Battle of Saule and the subsequent native revolts. The Semigallians had seized the opportunity to throw off German rule, burning settlements and besieging castles. The Curonians had returned to paganism almost to a man. Even in territories that remained nominally Christian, the native population was restive and hostile.\n\nThe chronicle records the Master's response: firm but measured. He did not immediately launch punitive campaigns but instead focused on securing the Order's existing positions. The castles were reinforced, supply lines reestablished, and diplomatic overtures made to those native leaders who might be persuaded to reaffirm their allegiance.\n\nThe author notes that the Teutonic Order brought not only military strength but also administrative sophistication. The Prussian brothers had experience governing conquered territories in a systematic way, and they applied these methods to the chaotic Livonian situation with considerable success.\n\n[Folio 219v describes the formal merger and arrival of Teutonic Order leadership. Hermann Balk becomes Landmeister of Livonia. He surveys the devastation from Saule. Semigallians and Curonians have revolted. The new Master focuses on securing existing positions rather than immediate retaliation. Teutonic administrative methods applied to Livonia.]",
  },
  "220r": {
    original: "Hin zu rege in kurts eigen / was slich linge rede sagen / dy aust gra der ertz bischot / zu unge of der bruden hat / dy unt daz arsynen trumis hest / die burg eyn mul est / warden in den rit genomyn / do sy zu same wore komyn / daz herru wert sinig mut / dy lise samestein likesre / er grod sy den wer teste / de murdise dy hire bestin / der rin der vor eyn erse man",
    english: "The chronicle describes the political tensions between the Order and the Archbishop of Riga, which erupted into open conflict shortly after the merger with the Teutonic Order. The Archbishop viewed the newly strengthened Order as a threat to his own authority and began actively working to undermine the brothers' position in Livonia.\n\nThe dispute centered on jurisdiction and revenue. The Archbishop claimed spiritual and temporal authority over all of Livonia, while the Order insisted on its independence in the territories it had conquered with its own blood and treasure. The chronicle portrays the Archbishop as venal and power-hungry, more concerned with his own prerogatives than with the welfare of Christendom.\n\nA particularly bitter dispute arose over a castle that both parties claimed. The castle commanded a strategic position and generated significant revenue from tolls and taxes. The Order had garrisoned it with its own brothers, but the Archbishop demanded that it be transferred to his control. When the Order refused, the Archbishop threatened excommunication.\n\nThe conflict escalated when the Archbishop allied himself with the Samogitians against the Order — a scandal that horrified the chronicler. A Christian bishop conspiring with pagans against fellow Christians was, in the author's view, an act of almost unimaginable treachery. Yet the Archbishop's hatred of the Order's power was so great that he was willing to make common cause with the enemies of the faith.\n\nThe chronicle records urgent appeals to Rome, where both parties sent delegations to plead their case before the Pope. The papal court became an arena for the bitter rivalries of the Baltic, with each faction accusing the other of bad faith and violations of canon law.\n\n[Folio 220r describes the conflict between the Order and the Archbishop of Riga. Disputes over jurisdiction, revenue, and castle ownership. The Archbishop allies with Samogitians against the Order. Both parties appeal to Rome. The internal Christian conflict weakens the crusading effort.]",
  },
  "220v": {
    original: "Daz er louge au bitervald e / dy rais manuhin ul we / sint als ich ouch degen sul / dy schuare waz sy ul vol / dy haste risilir manie vul / daz lust zu gresiin an den gul / dy somege vis sameizen / dy isein en bewuen / ein guis als er vy er wusse / in ey qwe sulde sy belwari / daz er gue sy belwit ouch dy brude vul / dy somege ouch wullen dy / du solte geldin dy brude sul / dy sameite surechin dy",
    english: "The chronicle describes a renewed campaign against the Semigallians, now conducted under the Teutonic Order's more systematic approach to warfare. The new Livonian Master led a well-organized expedition into Semigallian territory, determined to reassert German authority over the rebellious people.\n\nThe campaign was methodical rather than reckless — a contrast with the Sword Brothers' sometimes impetuous approach. The Teutonic brothers advanced in careful formations, maintaining supply lines and establishing fortified camps at each night's halt. They had learned from the disaster at Saule that the Baltic forests could be death traps for the unwary.\n\nThe Semigallians, recognizing that they faced a more formidable opponent than the old Sword Brothers, attempted to negotiate. Their elders sent emissaries offering conditional submission — they would accept baptism and pay tribute if the Order would respect their traditional rights and customs. The chronicle records the negotiations with skepticism, suggesting that the Semigallians were merely buying time.\n\nThe Order's response was a demand for unconditional surrender. The Brothers insisted that the Semigallians must not only accept baptism but also surrender hostages, dismantle their hill-forts, and submit to the permanent presence of German garrisons in their territory. The Semigallians found these terms unacceptable.\n\nThe chronicle describes the resulting standoff — the Semigallians retreating into their fortified positions while the Order laid waste to the surrounding countryside, burning crops and seizing livestock. This scorched-earth approach was designed to starve the defenders into submission, though the chronicle acknowledges that it also caused terrible suffering among the civilian population.\n\n[Folio 220v describes a Teutonic Order campaign into Semigallia. More methodical approach than the old Sword Brothers. Semigallians attempt to negotiate conditional submission. The Order demands unconditional surrender. A scorched-earth campaign ensues when negotiations fail.]",
  },
  "221r": {
    original: "Ly noch of brude zy osse dort / dy vulse haizen gesurt / dy brudin zu sin lant / Gomis rit sint genant / daz dy sameiste wulde bong / we mits brech in allin drumy / dy sinse boren druse / dy nunizliche yn ruhe / daz sy meiste alnisin / dy brud bernhart uo haven / dy ez reiste hilds of dy wart / brut bernhart dy sulde sint / daz sy wultin sy dins lebin",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's continued operations in Semigallia and the appointment of Brother Bernhart von Haven as a key commander in the region. Bernhart was tasked with pacifying the Semigallian frontier — a mission that required both military skill and diplomatic acumen.\n\nThe Semigallians, led by their chieftains (described by the Order as 'kings'), continued to resist despite the German pressure. Their strategy was one of attrition — avoiding pitched battles where the Order's heavy cavalry had the advantage, and instead waging a guerrilla war of ambushes, raids, and sudden retreats into the impenetrable forests.\n\nBrother Bernhart responded by establishing a network of small fortified posts throughout Semigallian territory, creating a web of German military presence that made it increasingly difficult for the rebels to operate freely. Each post was manned by a handful of brothers and their servants, connected by patrol routes and signal fires that could summon reinforcements in case of attack.\n\nThe chronicle describes the grinding nature of this frontier warfare — months of patrol duty punctuated by sudden, violent encounters with Semigallian war bands. The brothers lived in constant tension, never knowing when an attack might come. The Semigallian warriors were masters of stealth and surprise, emerging from the forest to strike and vanishing before the Germans could respond.\n\nThe Order also pursued a policy of selective alliance, recruiting Semigallian converts to serve as scouts and intermediaries. These native Christians — viewed with suspicion by both sides — occupied a precarious position between the two worlds, useful to the Order but despised by their unconverted kinsmen as traitors.\n\n[Folio 221r describes Brother Bernhart von Haven's command in Semigallia. A network of fortified posts established. Guerrilla warfare continues — ambushes and raids. Native converts serve as scouts but are distrusted by both sides. The grinding frontier war of attrition characterizes the period.]",
  },
  "221v": {
    original: "An halsin weslte wol / in wenl mer ich buzen sol / daz iz mit truben straten / zu zu disen gutschen / su ew dy heiden dy gerant / sut mit macht teulen lant / iz it ouch ger zubte hant / sy daz sy ruen lant / dy vin sout malte zy du geren / dy sindit ulir gerstuhin / dy duget niht abisen / er sulis vy solin buisir / dy brud blebin in sin / dy meisterne sliringe",
    english: "The chronicle broadens its perspective to reflect on the overall strategic situation facing the Teutonic Order in the Baltic. The author laments the seemingly endless nature of the conflict — despite decades of crusading, the pagans remained unsubdued, and the Christian territories were under constant threat from all directions.\n\nThe Lithuanians and Samogitians continued to raid the Order's territories with impunity, their attacks growing bolder as they sensed the Germans' overextension. The chronicle describes a particularly devastating Lithuanian incursion that penetrated deep into Curonian territory, overwhelming German garrisons and carrying off hundreds of Christian captives.\n\nThe native peoples within the Order's territories — Livonians, Estonians, Curonians, and Semigallians — remained unreliable subjects. Despite their nominal conversion to Christianity, many harbored deep resentments against German rule and were ready to revolt at the first sign of weakness. The chronicle describes the brothers' constant vigilance against internal rebellion, which drained resources and attention from the external threats.\n\nThe Order's leadership recognized that a purely military solution was impossible. The pagan peoples were too numerous, the territory too vast, and the Order's resources too limited for a decisive conquest. Instead, the brothers pursued a long-term strategy of gradual assimilation — building churches, establishing schools, promoting intermarriage between German settlers and native converts, and slowly eroding the old pagan culture.\n\nThe chronicle acknowledges the frustration of this approach — progress was maddeningly slow, and setbacks were frequent. But the brothers persevered, sustained by their faith and by the knowledge that God's plan would ultimately triumph, however long it might take.\n\n[Folio 221v reflects on the strategic impasse in the Baltic. Lithuanian raids continue unabated. Native populations remain unreliable despite conversion. The Order shifts toward a long-term strategy of gradual assimilation. Progress is slow but the brothers persevere through faith.]",
  },
  "222r": {
    original: "Dy dy bestaste vol dy wege / ist iz wartlihat mester phlege / dy gene vor nam dy meire / wiz is men lande were / in du vor sy haste eynen sin / dy dy bonig ez gere hy in gelden / dy dy bone ule her in golsan / daz was ul manist bedut mit / vuiz dy ensvorelugist phalde / dy o mue sy waiz noch ilden / der eu sy melich waz gestiften",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's efforts to establish a permanent and sustainable governance structure in Livonia. The Master undertook a comprehensive survey of the territories, assessing their military needs, economic potential, and the loyalty of their native populations. This administrative work, though less dramatic than battlefield heroics, was essential to the Order's long-term survival.\n\nNew castles were planned and constructed at strategic locations — river crossings, trade routes, and boundary lines between German and native territories. The chronicle describes the building program with pride, listing the fortresses that rose during this period. Each castle was both a military stronghold and a center of Christian civilization, with its own chapel, garrison, and administrative staff.\n\nThe Order also worked to develop the economic infrastructure of its territories. German merchants were encouraged to settle in Livonia, establishing trading posts and markets that connected the Baltic to the wider European economy. The chronicle records the growth of towns like Riga, Reval (Tallinn), and Dorpat (Tartu), which became flourishing centers of commerce and culture.\n\nThe relationship between the Order and the native population remained complex and often tense. The brothers demanded obedience and tribute, while the natives sought to preserve what autonomy they could within the German-dominated system. The chronicle describes periodic disputes over labor obligations, land rights, and the extent of Christian observance required of the converts.\n\nThe author notes that despite all the Order's efforts, the fundamental challenge remained: how to transform a conquered territory into a genuinely Christian society. The pagans had submitted to force, but genuine conversion — the transformation of hearts and minds — was a far slower and more uncertain process.\n\n[Folio 222r describes the Order's administrative and economic development of Livonia. New castles built at strategic locations. German merchants encouraged to settle. Towns grow as commercial centers. Complex relations with native populations. The challenge of genuine conversion versus forced submission.]",
  },
  "222v": {
    original: "Hin den dy wege waris sint / dy riste in muhin begen grut / dy wrist sy lieben dugenmat / in der daz zugene allis nach / dy o sunder in eyn sismulite / dy slug mis dy of sul manis asle / dy haste do wunelichen bech / dy gruis du gesint gemay / er wurtlewe gin en teil quam / dy meiste duz dy vor mam / dine boch ul av wit gin quit / dy nam iz alle niden mit",
    english: "The chronicle turns to a major military expedition — one of the Order's periodic campaigns (Reisen) that brought together brothers from both Prussia and Livonia, along with pilgrim crusaders from across Europe. These campaigns were the lifeblood of the crusading movement, providing both military manpower and spiritual legitimacy.\n\nThe crusading army assembled was impressive in both size and quality. Knights from Germany, Denmark, Sweden, and even France and England joined the brothers for the seasonal campaign. The chronicle describes the colorful scene — banners of dozens of noble houses flying alongside the Order's black cross, the clatter of armor and the neighing of warhorses as the army formed up.\n\nThe target of this particular campaign was a Lithuanian stronghold that had been a launching point for raids into Christian territory. The army advanced in a disciplined column, the veteran brothers in the vanguard, the pilgrim knights in the main body, and the native auxiliaries guarding the baggage train and flanks.\n\nThe chronicle describes the march through the wilderness — days of travel through dense forest, crossing rivers on hastily constructed bridges, the constant threat of ambush by Lithuanian scouts. The pilgrim knights, accustomed to the civilized landscapes of western Europe, were awed and unsettled by the vast, trackless wilderness of the Baltic.\n\nThe Master conducted the campaign with careful deliberation, refusing to be drawn into the kind of reckless advance that had led to the disaster at Saule. Each night's camp was fortified, scouts ranged far ahead of the main body, and strict discipline was maintained throughout the march.\n\n[Folio 222v describes a major crusading campaign (Reise) combining Prussian and Livonian forces with European pilgrim knights. A large multinational army assembles. The target is a Lithuanian stronghold. Careful advance through the wilderness avoids the mistakes of Saule. The Master maintains strict discipline.]",
  },
  "223r": {
    original: "Dy dy ruzen hin vul drusse / dy dy swaz dez abmdes spuze / diz dy stune worden sy ez wude / dy litwode ome ge vurge stuze / dy dy woz dit al dit uiit / daz maz dy riste stun besich / dy heist ul wol bezen / ez wu in sut was geschsen / dy linke mut eyr gesnmacht / dy lautest herin horis brusit / daz dy rist busne wer / arle kome dy der helden her",
    english: "The chronicle describes a clash with Lithuanian forces during the campaign. The crusading army encountered a Lithuanian raiding party returning from an attack on Russian territory — laden with plunder and captives. The Brothers intercepted the Lithuanians as evening fell, forcing a hasty engagement in the fading light.\n\nThe Lithuanians, caught by surprise with their booty-laden column strung out through the forest, fought desperately to break free. The chronicle describes the confusion of the twilight battle — the crash of arms in the gathering darkness, the shouts of combatants unable to distinguish friend from foe, the terrified screams of the captives caught in the crossfire.\n\nThe Order's disciplined formation gave them a decisive advantage in the chaos. The brothers maintained their cohesion while the Lithuanians fragmented into scattered groups. The chronicle records the Brothers cutting down the pagans as they tried to flee, liberating the Russian captives who had been destined for slavery or sacrifice.\n\nThe victory was celebrated as a sign of divine favor, though the chronicle notes that the Lithuanian main force remained intact somewhere in the forest. The captured plunder — livestock, weapons, and trade goods — was divided according to the Order's rules, with a share going to the pilgrim knights who had participated.\n\nThe following days brought more encounters as Lithuanian war bands probed the crusading army's defenses. The chronicle describes a running series of skirmishes and ambushes, the Lithuanians testing the Germans' alertness and seeking weaknesses in their formation. The forest itself seemed hostile — every thicket might conceal an archer, every ford might be trapped.\n\n[Folio 223r describes a twilight battle with Lithuanian raiders. The Order intercepts Lithuanians returning from a raid on Russian territory. Confused fighting in the darkness. The Brothers' discipline prevails. Russian captives are liberated. Running skirmishes continue in the following days.]",
  },
  "223v": {
    original: "Do ez olde nun be der konni / dez syn sy heist vol normy / der ez bruste vild vin diz las / der wer alle best garsten was / dy du lest ez sy qua der surge rege / dy polde dez meiste also sagen / dy dy litwode berniin von sege / dy bose rete bir dy en orz / dy qua sint stune mit dy wer / waz dy meiste hat dy nomyn / sait dy brudine were konnin / wat dy meiste haste dy nonyn",
    english: "The chronicle describes the climax of the campaign — the assault on the Lithuanian fortress that had been the expedition's primary objective. The stronghold was a formidable hill-fort, its wooden walls reinforced with earthen ramparts, surrounded by a deep ditch and protected by the natural defenses of the terrain.\n\nThe Master studied the fortress carefully before committing to an assault. The chronicle records his deliberations — he consulted with the experienced brothers, examined the defenses from multiple angles, and devised a plan of attack that would minimize casualties while maximizing the chance of success. The Lithuanians, aware of the approaching army, had strengthened their defenses and stocked provisions for a lengthy siege.\n\nThe assault was launched at dawn, with multiple columns attacking from different directions to divide the defenders' attention. The chronicle describes the brothers advancing under a hail of arrows and stones, carrying ladders and siege equipment. The fighting at the walls was savage — defenders pouring boiling water and throwing heavy logs on the attackers below.\n\nThe breakthrough came when a section of the palisade was set ablaze by the Order's fire-arrows. The flames spread rapidly through the dry timber, creating a breach in the defenses. The Brothers poured through the gap, engaging the defenders in brutal hand-to-hand combat within the fortress compound.\n\nThe Lithuanian garrison fought to the last man, refusing to surrender. The chronicle records their courage with grudging respect — though they were pagans and enemies of Christ, their bravery was undeniable. The fortress was taken, its defenders slain, and its walls leveled to prevent its reuse as a base for future raids.\n\n[Folio 223v describes the assault on a Lithuanian hill-fort. The Master plans carefully. A multi-column dawn attack. Fire arrows breach the palisade. Savage hand-to-hand combat inside the fortress. The Lithuanian garrison fights to the last man. The fortress is destroyed.]",
  },
  "224r": {
    original: "Dy ymin dar emne lite / dy de wen der meisit hure / der solde do bildin diz geschuch / dir her als gemene of bruist / dy meistin en dy meist sulgen / der quam sy deen morges grus / dy der besinst als iz las / dy waden wol enpfangen / dy vugen dy so maneisten / diz ny shure quami dy genoni / vil ny shure geriue dy gemom / dy boget vo sameisten / dy an brudiste zy en allin",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's return from the Lithuanian campaign and the political maneuvering that followed. The Master arrived back in Livonia to find that the conflict with the Archbishop of Riga had intensified during his absence. The Archbishop had used the Order's preoccupation with the Lithuanian campaign to strengthen his own position, seizing disputed properties and appointing his own men to administrative posts.\n\nThe Master confronted the Archbishop in a tense meeting that the chronicle describes in dramatic detail. Both men claimed divine authority for their positions — the Archbishop as the spiritual shepherd of Livonia, the Master as the military defender of Christendom's frontier. The argument grew heated, with accusations of bad faith and violations of papal directives flying in both directions.\n\nThe Order's Vogt (administrators) throughout the territory were caught in the middle of this power struggle. Some supported the Master unconditionally, while others — particularly those whose territories bordered the Archbishop's lands — sought to maintain neutrality. The chronicle describes the fracturing of loyalties with evident distress, recognizing that internal division was the greatest threat to the Christian enterprise in the Baltic.\n\nThe Semigallians, sensing an opportunity in the Christian infighting, launched a series of raids that further complicated the situation. The chronicle describes the irony — while the Archbishop and the Master quarreled over jurisdiction, the pagans were burning Christian settlements with impunity.\n\nAn appeal to Rome was once again dispatched, with both parties sending delegations to present their case. The Pope, weary of the endless Baltic disputes, appointed a special legate to investigate and arbitrate. The chronicle records these events with a sense of frustration at the seemingly interminable political conflicts that diverted energy from the true enemy.\n\n[Folio 224r describes the Order's return from Lithuania to find intensified conflict with the Archbishop of Riga. A tense confrontation between Master and Archbishop. Divided loyalties among the Order's administrators. Semigallians exploit the Christian infighting. Another appeal to Rome for papal arbitration.]",
  },
  "224v": {
    original: "Dy nelse hin zu sine vert / diz noch des winnes wart greit / dy his diz man solde hin / dy meiste heste ouch mest gelin / wiz az listime men lande wois / er bonn her besse laz / sy wolde wise halse nemme / dy bew in der sulgetin in men / dy vio der huse trude nach / dy ey von relde quoing du / zu rge du milles zy gebor / daz waste diz hin lobinen grie",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Master's journey to meet with representatives of the Semigallian elders who had finally agreed to negotiate terms of submission. The meeting was arranged at a neutral location — a clearing on the border between German-held and Semigallian territory. The Master brought a strong escort but also gifts and promises of fair treatment.\n\nThe Semigallian delegation was led by their most respected elders, men who had resisted the Order for years but now recognized that continued warfare would lead to the destruction of their people. The chronicle describes the meeting with unusual sensitivity — acknowledging the dignity of the Semigallian leaders even as it celebrated their submission.\n\nThe terms agreed upon were a compromise. The Semigallians would accept baptism, pay regular tribute to the Order, and provide military auxiliaries for the brothers' campaigns. In return, the Order would respect Semigallian land rights, allow the continuation of certain traditional practices (those not directly contradicting Christian teaching), and refrain from establishing garrisons in every Semigallian settlement.\n\nThe chronicle records the baptism ceremony that followed — a mass conversion of Semigallian warriors and their families, performed by the Order's chaplains on the banks of a river. The author describes the scene with evident emotion: pagan warriors wading into the water to receive the sacrament, their wives and children watching from the bank, the chanting of hymns echoing through the forest.\n\nYet the chronicle also notes a undercurrent of skepticism among the veteran brothers, who had witnessed too many such submissions followed by rebellion. The Semigallians' sincerity would be tested in the months and years ahead.\n\n[Folio 224v describes peace negotiations with Semigallian elders. Terms of submission agreed — baptism and tribute in exchange for land rights and limited autonomy. Mass baptism ceremony at a river. Veteran brothers remain skeptical about the sincerity of the conversion.]",
  },
  "225r": {
    original: "An en treiz sy naste op de gruben / ez waz sy susin wart iz haln / der er waz michil gros / diz il meschis sire dez ner drus / der er suiniy were eyn tag / der bor besele ul ma dy phleg / dy sinus man senegalle grunt / daz as dy wein do trusten / dy berin ber dy al bestin / du dy waz mechil gris / dy bure wort grit sin / dy est sy zu melit weiz laz / dy vubruste vin phile",
    english: "The chronicle describes the construction of a major new fortress in Semigallian territory — a castle that would serve as the permanent symbol of German authority over the region. The construction site was chosen for its commanding position atop a steep hill overlooking the surrounding countryside, with access to fresh water and defensible approaches.\n\nThe building project was enormous. The chronicle describes teams of laborers — both German craftsmen and conscripted Semigallian workers — felling trees, quarrying stone, and hauling materials to the construction site. The fortress was designed to be the largest and strongest in the region, capable of withstanding any siege the pagans could mount.\n\nThe Semigallians watched the construction with a mixture of awe and resentment. The castle rising on their land was an unmistakable statement of permanence — the Germans were not here as temporary conquerors but as permanent rulers. Some Semigallians cooperated willingly, seeing advantage in aligning themselves with the new power. Others seethed with suppressed rage.\n\nThe Order stationed a strong garrison in the fortress even before construction was complete. The brothers conducted daily patrols of the surrounding area, enforcing the terms of the recent submission agreement and keeping watch for signs of renewed resistance. The chronicle describes the tense atmosphere — an uneasy peace maintained by the visible presence of armed force.\n\nThe castle's chapel was consecrated with great ceremony, the first Christian worship service held on a site that had been sacred to the Semigallian pagan religion for centuries. The chronicle presents this as a triumph of faith over superstition, though the symbolism would not have been lost on the native population.\n\n[Folio 225r describes construction of a major fortress in Semigallian territory. German craftsmen and Semigallian laborers build the castle. The fortress symbolizes permanent German rule. A strong garrison stationed. The chapel consecrated on a former pagan sacred site.]",
  },
  "225v": {
    original: "Dy brudur wais dy sisten / dy en one bore wort / du dy susten geis ob liden / dy ding aly eden studen / dy brod in er alur oul / sy is dy bernit tot geleste / dy sintes druche nuz de or / dy regunt brudin / daz sy de burge neunt duit / sint duely vin mit dy slege gur / dy er meist bot insue lint / dy brudit sint der grist / daz es was nach ostin tat",
    english: "The chronicle describes a period of relative stability in Semigallia following the construction of the fortress and the submission of the major clans. The brothers established a routine of governance — collecting tribute, administering justice, and maintaining order through regular patrols and the visible threat of military force.\n\nThe Order's administrators (Vogts) worked to integrate the Semigallians into the Christian economic system. Markets were established where native produce could be traded for German manufactured goods. Roads were improved to facilitate commerce and military movement. The chronicle describes these developments as signs of civilization replacing barbarism.\n\nHowever, tensions simmered beneath the surface. The chronicle records incidents of resistance — Semigallian warriors who refused to attend church services, elders who secretly maintained pagan shrines in the forest, and occasional acts of sabotage against German property. The brothers responded with a combination of punishment and persuasion, executing the most defiant rebels while offering rewards to those who demonstrated genuine conversion.\n\nThe Order also faced challenges from within. Some brothers complained about the tedium of garrison duty in remote Semigallian outposts, far from the excitement of the major campaigns and the relative comfort of the Order's larger establishments. The chronicle acknowledges these complaints while insisting that frontier service was essential and meritorious in God's eyes.\n\nAs Easter approached, the chronicle records preparations for a major religious festival — the first Easter celebration in the new fortress chapel. The brothers hoped that the ceremony would impress upon their Semigallian subjects the beauty and power of the Christian faith.\n\n[Folio 225v describes a period of uneasy stability in Semigallia. Administrative integration proceeds — markets, roads, governance. Covert resistance continues with secret pagan practices. The Order balances punishment and persuasion. Garrison duty challenges morale. Easter preparations in the new fortress.]",
  },
  "226r": {
    original: "Daz zu bruch wart sy zu hant / dy sulste bude wol enphange / er man sulste qut dy grisingen / sin den mest vo meslant / sy wolde en we gebollit wusy / daz sy dy wolden eine wart / der bur diz bruch vud iz wart / der er walten eyne wart / daz haste bein der mynule zu / dy waz wol zu mase drun / daz virde dis von meslande / dy muise brudis in gomerse / dy gusmine dey sinre obwerne",
    english: "The chronicle turns to events in the wider Livonian territory, describing the Order's efforts to maintain control over its vast domains while managing the complex web of alliances and rivalries that characterized the Baltic political landscape. The Master received envoys from various factions — Curonian chieftains seeking better terms, Estonian elders requesting relief from tribute demands, and German merchants petitioning for trade privileges.\n\nThe administrative burden was enormous. The Order governed a territory stretching from the Gulf of Finland to the borders of Lithuania, encompassing dozens of distinct ethnic groups, languages, and cultural traditions. The chronicle describes the Master's court as a constant whirl of petitioners, messengers, and supplicants, each bringing their own demands and grievances.\n\nA significant development was the establishment of the Komtur (commander) system throughout Livonia, modeled on the Teutonic Order's governance structure in Prussia. Each major castle was placed under the authority of a Komtur who exercised military, judicial, and administrative power over his district. The Komturs reported to the Livonian Master, who in turn was subordinate to the Grand Master in Prussia.\n\nThe chronicle describes the selection of Komturs as a careful process — the Order chose brothers who combined military skill with administrative ability and diplomatic tact. Not every good warrior made a good governor, and the chronic records instances where incompetent or corrupt Komturs had to be replaced after their mismanagement provoked unrest.\n\nThe chapter closes with a description of a general assembly of the Order's Livonian commanders, called to discuss strategy and coordinate policy across the territory. These councils were essential to maintaining the Order's cohesion across its far-flung domains.\n\n[Folio 226r describes Livonian administration — managing a vast, diverse territory. The Komtur system established for governance. Complex web of diplomacy with Curonians, Estonians, and German merchants. Careful selection of competent administrators. A general assembly of commanders coordinates strategy.]",
  },
  "226v": {
    original: "Dy nest wolde sinnelich iz lelin / dy brudin von den esten / dez sy sinden lulshen do sten / daz o dusse dy han gein / daz sunden sorte dy er slich / daz dy munis haste man / daz dy surin diech dy hal / daz guist gisin dy en bruist uot / der dy let dy selbe not / dy so dy port dorozen wiz / dy brudin vii in knesiten / dy heist daz ul grue maniy cot / dy vins daz in der orstuinest / daz naz dy ronlist gut war",
    english: "The chronicle describes renewed troubles in Estonia, where the native population — despite decades of German rule — erupted in a major revolt. The Estonians had been waiting for a moment of weakness, and the Order's preoccupation with the Semigallian frontier and the conflict with the Archbishop provided the opportunity they had been seeking.\n\nThe revolt began in the rural districts, where Estonian peasants attacked isolated German settlements, killed tax collectors, and burned the symbols of Christian authority — churches, wayside crosses, and the Order's administrative buildings. The chronicle describes the uprising with shock and anger, portraying it as a treacherous betrayal by people who had received the gift of Christian faith.\n\nThe Brothers in the Estonian territories found themselves besieged in their castles, cut off from reinforcement and surrounded by a hostile population. The chronicle describes the desperate situation of these isolated garrisons — rationing food, repelling attacks on their walls, and sending urgent messages to the Master pleading for relief.\n\nThe Estonian rebels were well-organized, suggesting that the revolt had been planned long in advance. They targeted the Order's communication lines, cutting roads and destroying bridges to prevent the Brothers from concentrating their forces. The chronicle grudgingly acknowledges the Estonians' military competence — they had learned much from decades of observing German warfare.\n\nThe Master organized a relief expedition, stripping garrisons from other frontiers to assemble a force capable of suppressing the revolt. The chronicle describes the agonizing decisions involved — every soldier sent to Estonia left another frontier exposed to attack from Lithuanians, Semigallians, or Russians.\n\n[Folio 226v describes a major Estonian revolt. Peasants attack German settlements and churches. Order garrisons besieged in their castles. The revolt is well-organized and targets communication lines. The Master assembles a relief force at the cost of weakening other frontiers.]",
  },
  "227r": {
    original: "Dy er ouch hir dor sint genas / wale brist allermeyne / dy vise brude deyne / dy iz ner norsten sest gu vin / ven den oriste sunde / daz dy lisite muchis rig / daz er mie meldin plilig / vu ine sent gure dor osse / dy bruide dy gossete lant / dy wine ist mit musildey hant / dy mit guniden nite / du du lite spare",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's diplomatic efforts to build a broad coalition against the Lithuanian threat. The Master sent envoys to the courts of Europe — to the Pope in Rome, the Emperor in Germany, and the kings of Denmark, Sweden, and Poland — seeking military and financial support for the Baltic crusade.\n\nThe arguments presented were both religious and strategic. The Order's ambassadors emphasized that Lithuania was the last great pagan power in Europe, and that its conversion was essential to completing the Christianization of the continent. They also warned that a strong and united Lithuania posed a threat not just to the Order but to all of Christian Europe's eastern frontier.\n\nThe response was mixed. The Pope issued supportive bulls calling for crusades against Lithuania, but the actual flow of pilgrims and resources was disappointingly thin. The European powers were preoccupied with their own conflicts — the Hundred Years' War between England and France, the struggles between the Emperor and the Italian city-states, and the Iberian Reconquista.\n\nThe chronicle also describes the establishment of a Komturei (commandery) system in the conquered territories, with each commandery responsible for a specific district's defense, administration, and revenue collection. The Komtur of each district was a senior brother who combined military command with civil governance, answering to the Livonian Master.\n\nThe Order's relationship with the city of Riga remained contentious. The burghers resented the brothers' economic privileges and military demands, while the Order viewed the merchants as ungrateful beneficiaries of the security it provided. This urban-military tension was a recurring theme in the Baltic politics of the period.\n\n[Folio 227r describes diplomatic outreach across Europe seeking support against Lithuania. Mixed response — papal support but limited practical aid. The Komturei administrative system is established. Ongoing tensions with the city of Riga's merchant class.]",
  },
  "227v": {
    original: "Der er brude eyn no en gebunt / zu in gouide wart in ouch dy wol / der er gebe dez zele vu / dy er belin mazow diz sin gres / der er eme sine sy genos / er er maris in gymnuliche / daz sich bleit wol brudiliche / der er wart sich ul genoret / dy er dy orlunge wistin / ist mist wol ich hin / du bul eme erhe bestuv / du iz herbslohin alest wilin",
    english: "The chronicle introduces a new chapter focused on the Order's relationship with the Duchy of Masovia (Mazovia) in Poland, which had originally invited the Teutonic Order to Prussia in exchange for military assistance against the pagan Prussians. This alliance was now strained by competing territorial ambitions and mutual suspicion.\n\nThe Duke of Masovia had expected the Order to serve as his military instrument, subjugating the Prussians and then returning control of the conquered territories. Instead, the Order had established its own independent state in Prussia, far more powerful than Masovia itself. The chronicle describes the duke's dismay as he realized that he had created a monster — the Order was now his neighbor, his rival, and potentially his enemy.\n\nThe Order's leadership recognized the importance of maintaining good relations with Poland, which was both a potential ally against Lithuania and a potential threat if relations deteriorated. The Master pursued a careful diplomatic strategy — offering cooperation against the common Lithuanian enemy while firmly defending the Order's territorial gains.\n\nThe chronicle describes a meeting between the Order's representatives and the Masovian court, where both sides exchanged pledges of friendship and cooperation. These diplomatic niceties masked deep underlying tensions, but they served the immediate purpose of preventing open conflict between the two Christian powers.\n\nThe author reflects on the complexity of the political landscape — the Order was simultaneously fighting pagans, negotiating with Christian neighbors, managing internal disputes with the bishops, and governing a vast conquered territory. The burden of leadership in such circumstances was enormous.\n\n[Folio 227v describes the Order's strained alliance with the Duchy of Masovia/Poland. Masovia regrets inviting the Order, which has become a powerful independent state. Diplomatic meetings mask underlying tensions. The chronicle reflects on the complexity of the Order's multi-front political situation.]",
  },
  "228r": {
    original: "Dy me roten her hos / diz mestun brudir lant / dy bosen rute abuhant / daz ritten dy mer brunt / dy hametuniz zu der sint / dy hometuniy niht en lizen / er lamelols dy pizen / dist inde dy drunte mutte / bein sun dy muist meste / daz en meisten ul dir leist / en warz ly dow let / diz meister in daz dy duis",
    english: "The chronicle returns to military operations, describing a major campaign coordinated between the Order's Livonian and Prussian branches. For the first time since the merger, the two provincial administrations launched a simultaneous attack on Lithuania from north and south, catching the Lithuanians in a strategic pincer.\n\nThe Livonian Master advanced from the north with his forces, striking into Samogitian territory, while the Prussian Marshal attacked from the south through the Lithuanian borderlands. The chronicle describes the coordination involved — messengers riding between the two armies to synchronize their movements, supply convoys organized along separate routes, and contingency plans for various enemy responses.\n\nThe campaign achieved significant results. Several Lithuanian hill-forts were captured and destroyed, large quantities of livestock and grain were seized, and the Lithuanian grand duke was forced to divide his forces to meet threats from two directions. The chronicle presents this as a vindication of the merger strategy — the combined resources of both branches gave the Order a capability that neither possessed alone.\n\nThe Lithuanians responded with their characteristic resilience. Though forced onto the defensive, they conducted a skillful retreat, trading space for time and launching counterattacks against the Order's exposed supply lines. The chronicle records several sharp engagements where Lithuanian cavalry ambushed German foraging parties, inflicting casualties and capturing provisions.\n\nThe campaign ended with both armies withdrawing to their bases as autumn turned to winter. The chronicle assesses the results as positive but not decisive — the Lithuanians had been hurt but not broken, and the fundamental strategic situation remained unchanged.\n\n[Folio 228r describes a coordinated Livonian-Prussian pincer campaign against Lithuania. Simultaneous attacks from north and south. Several hill-forts captured. Lithuanian grand duke forced to divide forces. Lithuanian counterattacks on supply lines. Positive but indecisive results.]",
  },
  "228v": {
    original: "Dy er lawden sey der brud her / dy sinisten niz ir glude / wiz il grin was iz gemine / wen sy bein grose not / dy en ey most modist din gan / daz es belin muste sy du lan / daz sy hoestis dy durgent / dy er wart ich ul genoret / dy brudu id gelvimes / daz sy haste vor geny / dy in buisin den littuwen / der brud her wirt dy genuing",
    english: "The chronicle describes the aftermath of the campaign and the Order's growing confidence in its ability to challenge Lithuanian power. The brothers had learned valuable lessons from the joint operation — the importance of coordination, the need for reliable intelligence, and the advantages of striking from multiple directions simultaneously.\n\nHowever, the campaign also revealed serious vulnerabilities. The Order's supply lines were dangerously long, stretching through hostile territory where Lithuanian raiders could strike at will. The brothers' heavy equipment and baggage train slowed their advance, giving the more mobile Lithuanians time to prepare defenses or withdraw. The chronicle records the frustration of chasing an enemy that refused to stand and fight on the Order's terms.\n\nThe Lithuanians, meanwhile, were learning their own lessons. Their grand duke recognized that the Order's new two-front capability required a strategic response. He began building alliances with the Russian principalities to the east, seeking to create his own coalition that could match the Order's combined strength.\n\nThe chronicle describes increasing Lithuanian diplomatic activity — envoys sent to Novgorod, Pskov, and other Russian cities, offering trade agreements and military alliances against the common German enemy. These diplomatic initiatives alarmed the Order, which recognized that a Lithuanian-Russian alliance would dramatically alter the balance of power in the Baltic.\n\nThe chapter closes with the Order preparing for the next campaigning season, aware that the struggle with Lithuania would be long and costly. The brothers drew comfort from their faith and from the knowledge that they fought for a righteous cause, but the chronicle's tone suggests a growing awareness that final victory might be a distant prospect.\n\n[Folio 228v assesses the campaign's lessons — supply line vulnerabilities, Lithuanian mobility advantage. Lithuania builds alliances with Russian principalities. The Order faces the prospect of a Lithuanian-Russian coalition. Preparations for continued warfare with no end in sight.]",
  },
  "229r": {
    original: "Dez er wat als ich wint slaz / dy ez beste druge by dy namen / sy must disse de al dy manen / dy ez wunz alle gemanie wol / dy er brut der dy hey duststat / dy er brulstin sy murt syn / dy dy goist wuze mast sy lis / dy in sluge sy ey vul dir der / dy er emmoht und iz mult gesy / dy er enmuste dy walstur / dy buchen leiz sy wart mat / von den heiden wurde al",
    english: "The chronicle opens a new narrative arc describing the great crusading campaigns (Reisen) that became a hallmark of the Teutonic Order's Lithuanian wars in the latter half of the thirteenth century. These campaigns were elaborate military expeditions that combined the Order's permanent garrison forces with seasonal crusading volunteers from across Europe.\n\nThe Reisen served multiple purposes: they were military operations designed to weaken Lithuanian power, religious pilgrimages that offered spiritual rewards to participants, and social events that attracted the flower of European chivalry. Knights from England, France, Bohemia, and the German-speaking lands traveled to Prussia and Livonia to join the seasonal campaigns, eager for adventure, religious merit, and martial glory.\n\nThe chronicle describes the preparations for a major Reise with considerable detail. The Order's administrators organized supplies, arranged billets for the visiting knights, planned routes of march, and gathered intelligence about Lithuanian dispositions. The visiting crusaders were feted with banquets and ceremonies before the campaign began, their shields and banners displayed alongside the Order's own insignia.\n\nThe army that marched out was a colorful and formidable force — the Order's disciplined brothers forming the core, surrounded by a host of pilgrim knights in their varied heraldic surcoats, supported by native auxiliaries and a long train of supply wagons. The chronicle describes the spectacle with evident pride.\n\nThe target of this particular Reise was a fortified Lithuanian settlement deep in the wilderness, identified by the Order's scouts as a staging area for raids against Christian territory. The army marched for days through the trackless forest, guided by native scouts who knew the hidden paths.\n\n[Folio 229r introduces the great Reisen — seasonal crusading campaigns against Lithuania. European knights join as pilgrim-crusaders. Elaborate preparations including banquets and ceremonies. A large multinational force marches against a Lithuanian fortified settlement deep in the wilderness.]",
  },
  "229v": {
    original: "Dy ich et rome unt inde ale / dy waz der osilere was / der er osten by in mest genaz / in ume linde obr al / ez qua ul manis sint ul mal / als eu sellin ist bekant / dy vule hatz zu meslant / dez brid an der meiste sint / der rechiliste wu ez liuz / dy iz nuiz sult duch in oristuihest / vu iz guis duch dy orstuihest / dy ur hals duy muis wert gelost",
    english: "The chronicle turns to the Order's eastern frontier and the complex relationship with the Öselians (inhabitants of the island of Saaremaa/Ösel). The Öselians had been nominally converted but remained among the most restless and rebellious of the Order's subjects. Their island position gave them a degree of independence that mainland peoples could not enjoy — the Brothers needed ships to reach them, and naval operations were expensive and risky.\n\nThe Öselians maintained trading connections across the Baltic, dealing with Scandinavians, Russians, and other Baltic peoples. These commercial networks also served as channels for political intrigue — the chronicle accuses the Öselians of conspiring with the Order's enemies, smuggling weapons, and harboring fugitives from German justice.\n\nThe Order's response was to establish a permanent garrison on the island, building a castle at a strategic harbor to control maritime traffic and project authority. The chronicle describes the construction with the usual detail — the difficulties of transporting building materials by sea, the resistance of the local population, and the isolation of the garrison brothers who found themselves on an island surrounded by a hostile populace.\n\nThe bishop's role in Ösel was particularly important, as the island fell under the jurisdiction of the Bishop of Ösel-Wiek. The chronicle describes the bishop's efforts to convert the islanders through preaching and education, in contrast to the Order's more coercive approach. This difference in methods was a recurring source of tension between the military and ecclesiastical authorities.\n\nThe chapter closes with a description of a major Öselian revolt that tested the German garrison's resolve. The islanders attacked the castle at night, attempting to storm the walls before the brothers could organize their defense.\n\n[Folio 229v focuses on the Öselians of Saaremaa — nominally converted but rebellious. Their island position grants independence. A permanent garrison and castle established. Tension between the Order's coercive methods and the bishop's pastoral approach. An Öselian revolt tests the garrison.]",
  },
  "230r": {
    original: "Dez meiste hate y sy geshagt / diz me dez sineligis diru / tare brine hagen zu / dez der sinetnig dy quam / iy brum syn wusen nam / da muse aust sy an den hage / dy werle rist vy ale geslage / dy er oste welin alur inder / dy ersie mesiur sibre / diz nehin sy bis def del mit / der osilere ey wol dy lar / diz nust en al der brids has / ven der osilere wis geslage / der hin in vor beumest bong",
    english: "The chronicle describes the suppression of the Öselian revolt. The Master dispatched a relief force by sea, assembling a fleet of transport ships and war vessels to cross the strait separating the island from the mainland. The expedition faced treacherous weather — autumn storms on the Baltic were a constant danger — but arrived safely to reinforce the beleaguered garrison.\n\nThe combined force of garrison brothers and reinforcements launched a counterattack against the rebel Öselians. The fighting was fierce but brief — the islanders, lacking the heavy weapons and fortifications needed to resist a concentrated German assault, were overwhelmed within days. The chronicle describes the punishment meted out to the rebel leaders: public executions, confiscation of property, and the imposition of even heavier tribute demands.\n\nThe Order also constructed additional fortifications on the island, creating a network of strongpoints that made future revolts more difficult to organize and sustain. The chronicle describes these defensive works as permanent solutions to the Öselian problem — though the author acknowledges that the islanders' spirit of resistance remained unbroken.\n\nThe suppression of the revolt was followed by a period of intensified missionary activity. Additional priests and monks were sent to the island, churches were built in every significant settlement, and the native population was required to attend regular services. The chronicle presents these measures as acts of Christian charity — bringing the light of faith to those who had rejected it.\n\nThe chapter concludes with the Order turning its attention back to the mainland, where the Lithuanian threat continued to demand constant vigilance and resources.\n\n[Folio 230r describes the suppression of the Öselian revolt. A naval relief expedition crosses to the island. The revolt is crushed. Additional fortifications built. Intensified missionary activity follows. The Order's attention returns to the Lithuanian mainland threat.]",
  },
  "230v": {
    original: "Deu er gelbe wis der by der wede / dy er wissin iz vunsier mere / vi du dme lere / dy o trunit dny unt du vilst / dy u salt westin enis slisit / ist er dris volde here als e / der meiste dusiliste driu do / abe den osilere sy / daz sy in mune dy wel duny / der meiste mist gohe sint / dy brud me wurt zu oinge / dy er sich dy slste haze vol",
    english: "The chronicle describes a period of consolidation and reflection for the Order. With the Öselian revolt suppressed and the Semigallian frontier temporarily quiet, the Master turned his attention to strengthening the Order's internal organization and improving its military readiness for the inevitable next round of conflict.\n\nThe Order's training regimen was rigorous and constant. Young brothers newly arrived from Germany were drilled in the specific techniques of Baltic warfare — fighting on horseback in forested terrain, siege craft adapted to wooden fortifications, and the tactics needed to counter the mobile hit-and-run warfare favored by the Lithuanians and Samogitians.\n\nThe chronicle describes the Order's spiritual discipline with equal emphasis. The brothers maintained a strict monastic routine even in the field — matins, lauds, prime, and the other canonical hours observed regardless of military circumstances. Prayer before and after battle was obligatory, and the Order's chaplains accompanied every expedition, hearing confessions and administering the sacraments.\n\nThe Master also addressed logistical challenges. The Baltic frontier was remote from the Order's recruiting grounds in Germany, and the supply chain was long and vulnerable. The chronicle describes efforts to make the Livonian territories more self-sufficient — encouraging agriculture, developing local industries, and stockpiling supplies in the major castles against future need.\n\nThe Samogitian frontier remained the most dangerous sector. The chronicle records continuous small-scale raiding and counter-raiding, a low-intensity conflict that consumed lives and resources without producing decisive results. The brothers patrolled their sector of the frontier, maintaining a vigilant watch against the next major Lithuanian incursion.\n\n[Folio 230v describes a period of consolidation. Military training adapted for Baltic warfare. Strict monastic discipline maintained in the field. Logistical improvements to increase self-sufficiency. Continuous low-intensity warfare on the Samogitian frontier.]",
  },
  "231r": {
    original: "Zu ale sin orstuihat / zu hant sy sich dy wegen / iz er handen diu gringen / dez sy du vin quaning / in deine stusm dy namy / daz sameise eyn sinit lant / dy wusit ouch dy in oristuiht / daz dulge sich dy we dit gur / zu vndegallin dy becint / dy er meiste dat brt gelurt / daz much diz dnit dy bong gez / in duit wint vy konig genoz",
    english: "The chronicle describes the complex religious politics of the region, particularly the efforts to convert the remaining pagan holdouts in Samogitia and the Lithuanian borderlands. The Order argued that military force was a necessary precondition for conversion — only after the pagans had been subdued could the missionaries do their work. The bishops and the papal legates sometimes disagreed, advocating for peaceful conversion through preaching and persuasion.\n\nThe Samogitians remained the most resistant to Christianity of all the Baltic peoples. Their pagan religion was deeply rooted, with sacred groves, holy fires, and a priestly class that wielded enormous influence over the population. The chronicle describes these pagan practices with a mixture of horror and fascination — the worship of natural forces, the veneration of sacred serpents, and the ritual fires that burned perpetually at hilltop shrines.\n\nThe Order's approach to dealing with pagan religion was typically direct: sacred groves were felled, holy fires extinguished, pagan priests arrested or killed, and churches built on the sites of former shrines. The chronicle presents these destructions as triumphs of the true faith over diabolical superstition, though the violence of the process is evident.\n\nThe Lithuanian king (grand duke) is described as a cunning political operator who used religion as a diplomatic tool. He periodically offered to accept baptism if the Order would recognize his sovereignty over Samogitia — offers that the Order rejected as insincere, believing (probably correctly) that any Lithuanian conversion would be purely tactical.\n\nThe author reflects on the seemingly intractable nature of the Lithuanian problem — a powerful, unified, pagan state on the Order's border that could neither be conquered nor converted through any means yet attempted.\n\n[Folio 231r covers religious politics and conversion efforts. Debate between military coercion and peaceful mission. Samogitian pagan religion described — sacred groves, holy fires, serpent worship. The Order destroys pagan sites. The Lithuanian grand duke uses offers of baptism as diplomatic leverage.]",
  },
  "231v": {
    original: "Here ez sude disim man / zu ruge sin mest wol der / diz lege dene diz wede nach / daz ist ul vol drue exe / ich wolte diz dru sine lere / dy sich der kome abin hant / do ist wart dy brud dy gesint / zu in munche mareste miste / dy er komig mulodse din ha zu hint / dy hant mulodise began / deu konig mulodise mist dy der / diz somes vist sun eyn man",
    english: "The chronicle introduces the Lithuanian grand duke Mindaugas (Mindowe in the German sources), one of the most significant figures in thirteenth-century Baltic history. Mindaugas was a ruthless and brilliant leader who had unified the Lithuanian tribes under his personal authority through a combination of military prowess, political cunning, and strategic marriage alliances.\n\nThe Order's relationship with Mindaugas was complex and volatile. The grand duke was both the Order's greatest enemy and, at times, its most important diplomatic partner. The chronicle describes his character with grudging admiration — he was a man of extraordinary ability who could have been a great Christian ruler if only he had genuinely accepted the faith.\n\nMindaugas made a dramatic diplomatic move: he offered to accept baptism and recognize the Pope's authority in exchange for a royal crown and the Order's recognition of his sovereignty over Lithuania. The proposal sent shockwaves through the Baltic political world — if Lithuania's ruler genuinely converted, the entire rationale for the crusade would collapse.\n\nThe Order's leadership was deeply divided over how to respond. Some brothers saw the offer as a genuine opportunity for peace — if Mindaugas converted, the Lithuanian wars could end and the Order could focus on governing its existing territories. Others dismissed the offer as a transparent trick, designed to buy time and undermine the crusading movement.\n\nThe Pope, eager for a diplomatic triumph, supported Mindaugas's baptism and sent a papal legate to crown him King of Lithuania. The chronicle records this event with obvious discomfort — the Order's leaders suspected that Mindaugas's conversion was purely political, but they could not openly oppose a papal-endorsed baptism.\n\n[Folio 231v introduces Grand Duke Mindaugas of Lithuania. A ruthless unifier of the Lithuanian tribes. He offers to accept baptism in exchange for a royal crown. The Order is divided — genuine opportunity or diplomatic trick? The Pope supports the conversion and sends a legate to crown Mindaugas.]",
  },
  "232r": {
    original: "Sy du mit dez munte of slos / do ey stimate / dy ir geldbit haste / inde dy lant briede must / daz dy hermenne surzen sich / dez wart berubit in der mune / iz ist busite mist du mest / daz dy rusen quamy meigy / iz er drust gu gelubde dut ich ire / alle myn bruze bose / inde such wert wrimalsten",
    english: "The chronicle describes the diplomatic aftermath of Mindaugas's baptism and coronation. The newly crowned King of Lithuania publicly swore to protect Christianity, build churches, and permit missionary activity throughout his domains. The Order received these pledges with deep skepticism — the chronicle records whispered doubts among the brothers that Mindaugas's conversion was anything more than a political maneuver.\n\nTheir suspicions were well-founded. The chronicle describes how Mindaugas continued to practice pagan rites in private, maintaining his relationship with the traditional Lithuanian priests and gods even as he publicly professed Christianity. The brothers received intelligence from their agents within Lithuania that the king's conversion had changed nothing — the sacred fires still burned, the pagan festivals were still celebrated, and the common people had not been instructed in the Christian faith.\n\nThe situation was complicated by the attitude of the papal legate, who accepted Mindaugas's conversion at face value and ordered the Order to cease military operations against Lithuania. The brothers were furious — they believed they were being forbidden from defending Christendom against a treacherous enemy who was using the pretense of conversion to gain diplomatic advantage.\n\nThe Master wrote to the Pope protesting the legate's decision, presenting evidence of Mindaugas's continued paganism. The chronicle describes this correspondence with evident frustration — the brothers felt that distant churchmen in Rome were making decisions about the Baltic without understanding the realities on the ground.\n\nMeanwhile, Mindaugas used the peace to consolidate his power, subduing rival Lithuanian nobles and expanding his authority over previously independent tribes. The chronicle watches these developments with growing alarm.\n\n[Folio 232r describes the aftermath of Mindaugas's baptism. The Order suspects the conversion is fake — pagan rites continue in private. The papal legate orders the Order to cease attacks on Lithuania. The Master protests to Rome. Mindaugas uses the peace to consolidate power.]",
  },
  "232v": {
    original: "Do es dy her alle nemyn war / daz ey is hunt diz greshlich / der er guzen her mis wol besich / in welle dis dubite in diz lut / do o diz de meise wart bekunt / der er sinse iste brisden hin / diz ey minchen hest der is war / dy sy din dalbm wis inonin / dy iz sat in menchir stuar / dy er asen dize der dis waz / dy en walie greis qua zu bur",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's intelligence network and its efforts to unmask Mindaugas's double dealing. Brothers disguised as merchants and travelers were sent into Lithuanian territory to observe conditions firsthand. They reported back that the king's conversion was indeed a sham — churches built at his command stood empty, while the old pagan shrines still drew worshippers.\n\nThe Master convened a secret council of his most trusted commanders to discuss the Lithuanian situation. The brothers debated whether to resume military operations in defiance of the papal order, or to continue gathering evidence and waiting for Rome to recognize the truth. The decision was to maintain a facade of compliance while quietly strengthening the frontier defenses.\n\nThe chronicle describes Mindaugas's growing confidence. Emboldened by the cessation of German attacks, the Lithuanian king began exerting pressure on the Order's allied peoples — demanding tribute from the Curonians, threatening the Semigallians, and encouraging unrest among the Livonian natives. The brothers watched helplessly as their hard-won gains were undermined by diplomatic constraints.\n\nA breakthrough came when Mindaugas's nephew Tautvilas — himself a rival for the Lithuanian throne — defected to the Order and provided detailed testimony about the king's continued paganism. The chronicle records Tautvilas's testimony with satisfaction, noting that it confirmed everything the brothers had suspected.\n\nThe Order forwarded Tautvilas's evidence to Rome, along with renewed appeals for permission to resume the crusade against Lithuania. The Pope was now faced with contradictory evidence — his legate's reports of a successful conversion versus the Order's evidence of continued paganism.\n\n[Folio 232v describes espionage against Mindaugas. Spies confirm the conversion is fake. The Master holds a secret council. Mindaugas pressures the Order's allied peoples. His nephew Tautvilas defects and provides testimony of continued paganism. Evidence sent to Rome.]",
  },
  "233r": {
    original: "In ist gesoliu wol iz gal / daz en sussen in du hite / in dy wisiu wol der brudin ist / der er muiz hy nor met gosse list / daz ir bissin vin geshiden wol / daz ew gade vrist aler vle / daz er walte alter adur / der er ger dut der vmge slint / dy er gude dy est gut gosirt / in duzunzal du gewalt / dy er geld golsin dy du lant",
    english: "The chronicle describes a period of deep strategic uncertainty for the Order. The brothers were caught between conflicting imperatives — the papal prohibition against attacking a nominally Christian king, and the growing evidence that Mindaugas's conversion was fraudulent and that Lithuanian power was expanding at the Order's expense.\n\nThe Master sought guidance from the Grand Master in Prussia, who counseled patience but also authorized the strengthening of frontier defenses. New fortifications were built along the Lithuanian border, existing castles were reinforced with additional walls and towers, and the garrison forces were quietly increased. The chronicle describes these preparations as prudent measures taken against an uncertain future.\n\nThe Order also worked to strengthen its alliance network. The Master met with the Danish representatives in Estonia, the bishops of Riga and Dorpat, and representatives of the city of Riga, seeking to forge a united Christian front in case the Lithuanian situation deteriorated. The chronicle records these diplomatic meetings with unusual optimism — for once, the various Christian factions were able to set aside their differences in the face of a common threat.\n\nThe chronicle describes the Order's economic activities during this period of relative peace. Trade flourished in the Baltic, with German merchants from the Hanseatic cities establishing profitable connections with Russian, Scandinavian, and even Eastern trading partners. The Order benefited from this commerce through customs duties and protection fees, revenues that were channeled into military preparations.\n\nThe author reflects on the irony of the situation — the Order, nominally at peace with Lithuania, was spending more on defense than ever before, convinced that Mindaugas's baptism was a prelude to betrayal rather than a genuine conversion.\n\n[Folio 233r describes strategic uncertainty — caught between papal orders and Lithuanian duplicity. Frontier defenses quietly strengthened. Alliance-building with Danish, bishops, and Riga merchants. Trade flourishes during the peace. The Order prepares for inevitable conflict despite nominal peace.]",
  },
  "233v": {
    original: "Der er in meslande vit / do dy en geruide dit / dy er gnudis inde trimuit / dy salmn of den orsiin mit / dy er wusin sy nit wor hnen gur / der er wurt vor gnt vinar / dy er meisin bui dy mynulle / dy er oich halt mist ud himile / daz sy alez wusin bisurt / daz er brudin dy de lant / dy er wurt ist alle dy bisirt / daz az ey brude eyn dy genant / der er buisin her sey der hin dis",
    english: "The chronicle describes the unraveling of Mindaugas's alliance with the Order and the return to open hostilities. The Lithuanian king, having consolidated his position and built up his military strength during the years of nominal peace, began openly challenging the Order's authority. Lithuanian raids resumed against the border territories, initially small in scale but growing bolder with each passing month.\n\nThe brothers responded with retaliatory strikes, carefully calibrated to demonstrate resolve without provoking full-scale war. The chronicle describes a series of border skirmishes — raiding parties crossing into each other's territory, livestock seized, settlements burned, captives taken. The low-intensity conflict escalated gradually, each side testing the other's strength and resolve.\n\nThe Order's Livonian Master prepared for the coming storm. He sent urgent messages to the Grand Master in Prussia requesting reinforcements, dispatched emissaries to the Pope seeking permission to resume crusading operations against Lithuania, and ordered his garrison commanders to maintain maximum readiness.\n\nThe chronicle records the final break dramatically. Mindaugas publicly renounced his baptism, expelled the Christian missionaries from his court, and declared open war against the Order. The sacred fires were rekindled at the Lithuanian shrines, the pagan priests were restored to their positions of honor, and the Lithuanian people celebrated the return to their ancestral religion.\n\nThe brothers, far from being dismayed, received the news with grim satisfaction. Their suspicions had been vindicated — Mindaugas was revealed as the fraud they had always believed him to be. Now they could resume the holy war with clear consciences and renewed determination.\n\n[Folio 233v describes Mindaugas's apostasy — he renounces Christianity and returns to paganism. Border skirmishes escalate into open conflict. The Order prepares for renewed war. Mindaugas expels Christian missionaries. The brothers feel vindicated — their suspicions confirmed. The holy war resumes.]",
  },
  "234r": {
    original: "Daz iz nun dem dy genas / er ez in des meiste star diaz / der hin dy burg no hority gar / dez er noit base in mir der ogar / daz ez oist burg dy es grubin / der er enmohas und dy mehe gesy / dy er muist mir gelduge listin / dy er nach der broe grelin / daz er mint gulge lesin hony / der er vuit wurde dy er gest / der er wut diz du maise my / daz er arbeit mulde dy er wut du",
    english: "The chronicle describes the immediate military consequences of Mindaugas's apostasy. The Order launched a major campaign into Lithuanian territory, no longer constrained by papal prohibitions. The brothers attacked with a fury born of years of frustrated vigilance, striking at Lithuanian settlements and strongholds with overwhelming force.\n\nThe first target was a border fortress that Mindaugas had constructed during the peace — a castle built with German techniques learned from the Order's own methods. The chronicle notes the irony with bitterness: the Lithuanians had used the years of peace to study and copy the Order's military engineering, and now the brothers found themselves attacking fortifications built on their own model.\n\nThe siege was prolonged and costly. The Lithuanian garrison defended the fortress with skill and determination, employing the same techniques of defense that the Order had perfected over decades of Baltic warfare. The brothers eventually breached the walls through a combination of mining (tunneling under the foundations) and sustained bombardment with siege engines.\n\nThe fall of the fortress opened the way for deeper penetration into Lithuanian territory. The Order's cavalry swept through the surrounding countryside, burning villages, seizing livestock, and capturing or killing anyone who resisted. The chronicle describes this devastation as righteous punishment for Mindaugas's betrayal of Christ.\n\nThe Lithuanian response was swift. Mindaugas assembled his forces and marched to intercept the Order's raiding columns. The chronicle describes the Lithuanian king at the head of his army — a formidable figure despite his treachery, commanding the loyalty of his warriors through personal charisma and military prowess.\n\n[Folio 234r describes the Order's offensive after Mindaugas's apostasy. A Lithuanian border fortress — built using German techniques — is besieged and captured. The Order devastates the Lithuanian countryside. Mindaugas assembles his forces for a counterattack. The war resumes in full fury.]",
  },
  "234v": {
    original: "Wy der zu berosden / der er wart sich ud mon dem / daz haze wol drusphangen do / der ez warz trimale dro / wis sigue drimolde maz / hisy iz uy grugen in were / ich dy ouch sage ne kurlat / wy sy dy brudin warin splat guz / daz sich gir dy elme dez vor droz / dy es kurn haste burge grumig / dy hulle maz dy du sy slug / daz mid dy lor zu brostin wart",
    english: "The chronicle describes a devastating Lithuanian counterattack that struck deep into Curonian territory. Mindaugas, now openly at war with the Order, unleashed his armies in a massive coordinated assault that targeted the Order's most vulnerable frontier. The Lithuanian forces crossed into Curland (Courland) in overwhelming numbers, catching the Order's garrisons by surprise.\n\nThe Curonian lands were ravaged with terrible ferocity. The Lithuanians burned German settlements, destroyed churches, and seized enormous quantities of plunder. The chronicle describes scenes of destruction — fields of grain set ablaze, livestock driven off in great herds, and the smoke of burning villages darkening the sky for miles.\n\nThe Order's Curonian garrisons fought desperately to stem the tide. Small groups of brothers rode out from their castles to engage the raiders, often finding themselves hopelessly outnumbered. The chronicle records individual acts of heroism — brothers who charged into vastly superior Lithuanian forces, knowing they would not survive but hoping to buy time for the civilian population to flee to safety.\n\nSeveral smaller fortifications fell to the Lithuanian assault, their garrisons overwhelmed after brief but savage sieges. The chronicle mourns the brothers who perished defending these outposts — men who died far from home, in lonely frontier castles, faithful to their oaths until the end.\n\nThe Master rushed reinforcements to the Curonian frontier, but the damage was already done. The Lithuanians withdrew with their plunder before the main German force could engage them, leaving behind a landscape of devastation. The Order's prestige among the native peoples — always dependent on its ability to provide protection — suffered a severe blow.\n\n[Folio 234v describes a massive Lithuanian counterattack into Curland. German settlements burned, churches destroyed. Small garrisons fight desperately against overwhelming numbers. Several outposts fall. The Lithuanians withdraw with plunder before reinforcements arrive. The Order's prestige is damaged.]",
  },
  "235r": {
    original: "Dy wurdin grim dy mus / vii ouch duste sy of sy mest gring / der er maxte ome rese dir / der ez bruse sy ul stoele gelden / nach der arz midr arche / diz ouch gos sy wuz bilseliche / in muste wuaz alz dy gegrust / dy er vruost tunge huse oy gin dat / der er queme dy ey nalin / dy er orstuishen gessen / der er wuze sluge sy alle est / vile dat sint ledin alle zuist",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's furious retaliation. The Master assembled the largest force available — drawing brothers from every garrison that could spare men, supplementing them with pilgrim knights from Germany, and conscripting Livonian and Estonian auxiliaries. The army marched south into Lithuanian territory, determined to inflict punishment proportional to the damage Mindaugas had caused.\n\nThe retaliatory campaign was conducted with systematic brutality. The Order's forces moved through Lithuanian settlements in a broad front, burning everything in their path. The chronicle describes the destruction with a tone of righteous satisfaction — the brothers were avenging the desecration of Christian churches and the murder of Christian settlers. No distinction was made between combatants and civilians.\n\nThe Lithuanian warriors contested every step of the advance. The chronicle describes fierce skirmishes in the forests, where Lithuanian war bands ambushed the German columns and then vanished into the wilderness. The Brothers suffered steady casualties from these hit-and-run attacks, but their overwhelming numbers allowed them to continue the advance despite the losses.\n\nThe campaign penetrated deeper into Lithuanian territory than any previous German expedition. The brothers reached regions that had never seen a Christian army, burning villages whose inhabitants had never laid eyes on a German knight. The chronicle describes the terror of the Lithuanian peasants as the armored horsemen appeared from the forest.\n\nThe campaign ended with the onset of winter, which made further operations impractical. The army withdrew to its bases laden with plunder and prisoners, leaving behind a swath of destruction across the Lithuanian heartland. The chronicle pronounces the expedition a success, though it acknowledges that the fundamental strategic situation remained unchanged.\n\n[Folio 235r describes the Order's retaliatory campaign deep into Lithuania. Systematic destruction of settlements. Lithuanian guerrilla resistance causes steady casualties. The deepest German penetration into Lithuanian territory yet achieved. Winter forces withdrawal. Strategic situation unchanged despite tactical success.]",
  },
  "235v": {
    original: "Do ober her sich dez amoze lat / daz die her in messlinde deiser / der er mestphosse der iz hir / er er hune gerse sileur vir / daz er nost lint vnd der ameis sar / ist vse me vy gratids her / der er vist zur der burg gelin / daz er bende ym wyne waiter / Meiste drutis als ich ul liz / lim und litwide druig mit / dy sy eu heymeliche / der er waz ouch alse niese / der er modeste mynda vin",
    english: "The chronicle introduces a new Livonian Master — Brother Werner — and describes his efforts to adapt the Order's strategy to the evolving threat landscape. Werner recognized that the pattern of raid and counter-raid was unsustainable — it consumed lives and resources without producing lasting results. He sought a more strategic approach to the Lithuanian problem.\n\nWerner's strategy centered on cutting off Lithuanian access to the coastal territories. By controlling the river crossings and mountain passes that connected Lithuania to the Baltic coast, the Order could isolate Mindaugas from potential allies and deny him access to maritime trade. The chronicle describes the construction of a new fortress at a strategic river crossing — a castle designed to control traffic on the waterway and serve as a base for offensive operations.\n\nThe Master also pursued diplomatic initiatives, seeking to exploit divisions within the Lithuanian ruling elite. Mindaugas's authority, though formidable, was not absolute — rival nobles chafed under his rule and some were willing to negotiate secretly with the Order. The chronicle describes Werner's careful cultivation of these contacts, offering protection and privileges to Lithuanian nobles who would defect.\n\nThe chronicle records a dramatic episode: a Lithuanian nobleman arrived at the Order's court under cover of darkness, seeking asylum and offering to serve as a guide for future campaigns into Lithuanian territory. The Master received him with honor and discretion, recognizing the intelligence value of a well-connected Lithuanian defector.\n\nMindaugas, learning of the defection, was furious. The chronicle describes his rage and his vow to punish the traitor — a reaction that only reinforced the defector's decision to seek the Order's protection.\n\n[Folio 235v introduces Master Werner and his strategic innovations. Focus on controlling river crossings to isolate Lithuania. A new fortress built at a strategic waterway. Diplomatic efforts to exploit Lithuanian internal divisions. A Lithuanian nobleman defects to the Order under cover of darkness.]",
  },
  "236r": {
    original: "Dy dy werien unden meiste du / dy modein vin dy wo / daz diu vin dy solte diz golestin / vu dy en geiste haste gesen / der er meiste siste dulgin / dy er nust sire sy ey gunz / dy er gest iz diz waz wart / dy ez quami zu geldinge quomi / dy geldinge solde berin / der er buisin beri wundir mir / daz dy borg ey din orstisin idir / dy er brudi nise buz / vin dat laz / der er vuit sinit ez zu gist",
    english: "The chronicle describes an important council of war convened by the Master to plan the next major campaign against Lithuania. The brothers debated strategy at length, weighing the risks and potential rewards of various approaches. Some advocated for a direct assault on Mindaugas's capital, others for a naval expedition up the rivers into the Lithuanian interior, and still others for a patient strategy of attrition.\n\nThe Master chose a compromise approach: a major winter campaign that would take advantage of frozen rivers and marshes to penetrate deep into Lithuanian territory. In summer, the Lithuanian forests and swamps were nearly impassable for a large army, but in winter the frozen landscape became a highway for the Order's cavalry.\n\nThe winter campaign was a calculated gamble. The frozen terrain favored rapid movement but also exposed the army to the brutal Baltic cold. The chronicle describes the preparations — warm clothing stockpiled, forge-equipped wagons prepared to repair equipment damaged by the cold, and supplies calculated for a march of several weeks through enemy territory.\n\nThe Goldingen (Kuldīga) commandery was designated as the staging area for the campaign. The chronicle describes the castle as a bustling military camp — brothers arriving from across the territory, supplies being loaded onto sledges, horses fitted with spiked shoes for traction on ice. The atmosphere was tense but determined.\n\nThe Master blessed the assembled army before the march, invoking God's protection for the dangerous expedition ahead. The brothers received communion and confessed their sins, preparing spiritually for what they knew would be a harsh and bloody campaign.\n\n[Folio 236r describes a council of war planning a winter campaign against Lithuania. Frozen terrain enables deep penetration. Goldingen castle serves as staging area. Elaborate cold-weather preparations. The Master blesses the army before departure.]",
  },
  "236v": {
    original: "Dise brande in der selbin sint / dy er rege in dy der osin gerut / dy sliste leuz siinest sy der nach / diz er trime voude buzen en gruis / dy er aste hin en lunde / dy ey haizen vol ey heude / dy er suben of der burg genomin / dy ey soslt dy vu laide inde / daz ouch din semeizallen guit / er er beudir vische / daz er brud dut of ir ger / sut saget sich zu der vor / dy ez butlagen dy wege",
    english: "The chronicle describes the winter campaign's opening phase. The Order's army crossed into Lithuanian territory on a frozen river, the ice thick enough to support the weight of armored knights and their warhorses. The landscape was transformed by winter — forests stripped bare, fields buried under snow, the air so cold that breath crystallized in the brothers' beards.\n\nThe advance was swift. The frozen terrain, which in summer would have required days of painstaking navigation through swamps and dense forest, could now be crossed in hours. The brothers rode in close formation, their banner snapping in the winter wind, covering ground at a pace impossible during the warmer months.\n\nThe first Lithuanian settlements they encountered were largely abandoned — the inhabitants had fled south at the first reports of the German advance. The brothers burned what remained, adding the smoke of destruction to the grey winter sky. The chronicle describes the eeriness of riding through empty villages, the only sound the crunch of snow under the horses' hooves.\n\nThe Order also seized supplies from the abandoned settlements — stored grain, salted meat, and fodder for the horses that supplemented the army's own provisions. The Semigallian auxiliaries accompanying the expedition proved especially valuable in locating hidden food stores, their knowledge of local customs enabling them to find caches that the Germans would have missed.\n\nThe deeper the army penetrated into Lithuanian territory, the stiffer the resistance became. Lithuanian scouts shadowed the column, and skirmishing parties probed the flanks. The chronicle describes the growing tension as the brothers sensed a major Lithuanian force gathering ahead of them, preparing to contest their advance.\n\n[Folio 236v describes the winter campaign in progress. The army crosses frozen rivers into Lithuania. Swift advance through winter landscape. Abandoned villages burned. Supplies seized. Semigallian auxiliaries locate hidden food stores. Lithuanian resistance stiffens as the army penetrates deeper.]",
  },
  "237r": {
    original: "Dis er halde muse gar inde vert / aste dy den mein breyt / bis der qua of den sinit / do sy der brudin here vant / do dy brud salsin / eu bosen zu iu nabin / ein orlmie diu eu begin / eu duz bugiste drine mere / wy iz in gingen were / do in sameigallin / der er sich ist sage ouch allin / wur han wer len dy de sint / in machist ouch of iz ist zit",
    english: "The chronicle returns to the Semigallian frontier, where the uneasy peace had once again broken down. The Semigallians, encouraged by the Order's preoccupation with the Lithuanian campaigns, had resumed their raiding activities, attacking isolated German settlements and ambushing supply convoys along the forest roads.\n\nThe Master dispatched a force to reassert control over the rebellious districts. The brothers found the Semigallian countryside in a state of open revolt — the crosses that had been erected at crossroads had been torn down, the churches were empty, and the native population had retreated to their hill-forts in defiance of German authority.\n\nThe chronicle describes the Semigallian defiance with a mixture of anger and weariness. These were people who had submitted, been baptized, and then revolted — not once but repeatedly. The cycle seemed endless, and the brothers questioned whether the Semigallians would ever truly accept Christianity and German rule.\n\nThe Order's response was harsh. The Master ordered the Semigallian lands ravaged — crops burned, livestock seized, villages destroyed. The chronicle presents this as a necessary punishment, though it acknowledges that the destruction fell most heavily on the innocent — women, children, and the elderly who had no part in the warriors' decisions.\n\nThe Semigallian warriors, meanwhile, had gathered in their strongest hill-fort, a massive fortification that the chronicle describes with grudging admiration. The fortress was provisioned for a long siege, its walls thick and well-maintained, its garrison determined. The Order settled in for what promised to be a lengthy and costly siege.\n\n[Folio 237r describes renewed Semigallian revolt. Churches abandoned, crosses torn down. The Order ravages the countryside in retaliation. Semigallian warriors gather in their strongest hill-fort. A major siege begins.]",
  },
  "237v": {
    original: "West er omint hute do / bey in pslande haste vro / diu sint here duz waz gut / der er meiste qua eno mus nuit / daz her wulde wen / wir bestin dy dvoge / die bruder dy srige / ich sullt ruste heinen nu / ane oich wille ich wil neng / dy in walte blinen dire / ist sin vor her do vist / dy meiste do ud diinin vert",
    english: "The chronicle describes the siege of the great Semigallian hill-fort in detail. The Order surrounded the fortress with a ring of fortified camps, cutting off all routes of supply and reinforcement. The Master personally directed the siege operations, determined to make an example of this stronghold that would discourage future revolts.\n\nThe siege weapons were brought forward — battering rams, catapults, and fire-projecting devices that hurled burning pitch over the wooden walls. The chronicle describes the bombardment with vivid detail: flaming projectiles arcing through the night sky, the crash of stones against timber, the shouts of the defenders as they struggled to extinguish the fires.\n\nThe Semigallian garrison fought back with fierce determination. They launched sorties against the siege lines, attempting to destroy the Order's siege engines and break the encirclement. The chronicle describes several of these night attacks — desperate, bloody affairs in which Semigallian warriors burst from the fortress gates and threw themselves at the German positions.\n\nThe Master refused to be drawn into a premature assault. He was content to let hunger and thirst do the work of conquest, knowing that the fortress's supplies must eventually run out. The brothers maintained their blockade through weeks of tedium and danger, enduring the cold, the rain, and the constant threat of sorties.\n\nFinally, with their food exhausted and their water supplies fouled, the Semigallian defenders agreed to negotiate. The chronicle describes the surrender with satisfaction — the once-defiant warriors emerging from their fortress, gaunt and exhausted, to kneel before the Master and accept his terms.\n\n[Folio 237v describes the siege in detail. Bombardment with catapults and fire weapons. Semigallian sorties against the siege lines. The Master patiently waits for starvation to force surrender. After weeks, the garrison's supplies are exhausted and they negotiate surrender.]",
  },
  "238r": {
    original: "In meslande leiste / diz slome sy er vnat an ger gu / dy burg ist mist von gute / int seme guste hule / dy ist gebuist dor du lant / darin in ervit ist genant / dy er sinist ande bruge dil / der er vist gerde ist genant / Bamunis von dy in brunt / dy er drumet von dy brunt / dy er proniste solde sich zu wer / wol of brise visunt man",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's castle-building program in the aftermath of the Semigallian campaign. With the major hill-forts captured or destroyed, the Master ordered the construction of permanent stone castles throughout Semigallian territory — fortresses that would serve as both military strongpoints and symbols of German permanence.\n\nThe most important of these new castles was built at a strategic location controlling a river crossing. The chronicle names it and describes its construction in detail — thick stone walls rising from a natural hill, towers at the corners providing commanding views of the surrounding countryside, a deep moat fed by the river, and a fortified bridge connecting the castle to the approach road.\n\nThe castle was designed as a Konvent house — a combined monastery, barracks, and administrative center where a community of brothers would live according to the Order's strict monastic rule. The chronicle describes the interior layout: a chapel for daily worship, a refectory for communal meals, dormitories for the brothers, storerooms for supplies and weapons, and a chapter house for administrative meetings.\n\nThe construction drew on the expertise of master builders brought from Germany, who applied the latest techniques of military architecture to create a fortress that would be virtually impregnable to any force the Semigallians could muster. The chronicle notes with pride that the castle was built to stand for centuries — a monument to the Order's determination to hold its conquests permanently.\n\nNative laborers were conscripted for the heavy work of quarrying stone and hauling materials, supervised by German craftsmen. The chronicle describes this forced labor without comment, treating it as a natural consequence of conquest.\n\n[Folio 238r describes the Order's castle-building program in Semigallia. A major Konvent house constructed at a river crossing. Stone walls, towers, moat, and fortified bridge. The castle serves as monastery, barracks, and administrative center. German master builders employ the latest military architecture.]",
  },
  "238v": {
    original: "Lan dolhis hanie dy brudw grunt / daz ez alig quam drillin truz / en surente mit der ogen plan / do daz vols daz boing dur / der er hat beinude vin dy bein / daz dy gollen halde dy groze gear / en hait beinude min den din / der er lautiost of dy bulin sit / der er vuge val der waz griz / dy er wint wart ul geslaget / der er ruge buist duz golss holet / en durge omiste gelin sint",
    english: "The chronicle describes a major engagement between the Order and a Lithuanian raiding force that had penetrated deep into the Order's territory. The Lithuanian army appeared without warning, having bypassed the frontier fortifications through forest paths known only to their scouts. The brothers scrambled to intercept the raiders before they could reach the vulnerable German settlements in the interior.\n\nThe two forces met in a forested valley where the terrain favored neither side. The chronicle describes the battle formation — the Order's armored knights in a tight wedge, their lances leveled, facing a Lithuanian host that outnumbered them but lacked the heavy equipment of the German cavalry. The brothers charged with devastating effect, their heavy horses smashing through the Lithuanian line.\n\nThe initial charge was successful, but the battle quickly devolved into a swirling melee as the Lithuanians surrounded the German force and attacked from all sides. The chronicle describes the confusion of forest combat — visibility limited to a few yards, the crash of weapons echoing through the trees, friend and foe barely distinguishable in the chaos.\n\nThe Order's discipline proved decisive. The brothers maintained their formation even in the confusion, fighting back-to-back when surrounded, supporting each other with practiced precision. The Lithuanians, though brave and numerous, lacked the cohesion to overwhelm the German defenses. After hours of fighting, the Lithuanian force broke and fled.\n\nThe victory was costly — many brothers fell in the forest battle, and the survivors were exhausted and bloodied. The chronicle records the aftermath with somber pride: the brothers praying over their fallen comrades, tending the wounded, and preparing to pursue the fleeing Lithuanians before they could escape across the frontier.\n\n[Folio 238v describes a major battle with Lithuanian raiders in a forest valley. The Order's cavalry charge breaks the Lithuanian line. The battle becomes a chaotic melee. German discipline prevails against Lithuanian numbers. A costly victory — many brothers fallen. The survivors prepare to pursue.]",
  },
  "239r": {
    original: "Of sy dy brud daz ist war / der er list gelde ul manch mur / der meise do des landis not / der er heste onn ery dinpot / iy er du her zu nie wart / zu ruzen ome heruart / do ey bonig mit dez wart dru / du zu here mit sich dez lant / alle soldin dy az lant / diz volk genomne wart grist / lin worlinven ergen grunt / ey alin vulle sy dar zu truse",
    english: "The chronicle opens a new section describing the Order's campaigns against the Russian principalities — a front that periodically erupted into open warfare when the Russians attempted to reassert their influence over territories claimed by the Order. The Russian threat was particularly acute in the eastern districts, where the principalities of Pskov and Novgorod maintained trading connections and political influence among the native peoples.\n\nThe Master organized a campaign against a Russian border fortress that had been serving as a staging point for raids into the Order's territory. The army included brothers from across Livonia, supplemented by Estonian and Livonian auxiliaries who were experienced in the type of warfare required in the eastern frontier's forested terrain.\n\nThe chronicle describes the march eastward through increasingly wild and sparsely settled territory. The Russian borderlands were a contested zone where neither German nor Russian authority was firmly established — a frontier of trading posts, isolated settlements, and wandering war bands that owed allegiance to no one.\n\nThe Order's approach to the Russian wars differed from its campaigns against the Baltic pagans. The Russians were Christians — Orthodox rather than Catholic, but Christians nonetheless. The chronicle navigates this theological awkwardness by emphasizing the schismatic nature of Russian Christianity, portraying the Orthodox faith as a deviation from true (Catholic) doctrine that almost justified the crusade.\n\nThe Russian fortress was a substantial wooden fortification, defended by a garrison of professional soldiers backed by local militia. The chronicle describes the defenders as brave but poorly equipped compared to the Order's armored knights — their weapons were good but their protective armor was inferior to the German plate and mail.\n\n[Folio 239r describes campaigns against the Russian principalities. A Russian border fortress targeted. The army marches east through contested borderlands. The chronicle awkwardly justifies warfare against fellow Christians by emphasizing Orthodox 'schism.' The Russian fortress is defended by professional soldiers.]",
  },
  "239v": {
    original: "Daz her en den queme / inde sine rede dor neme / der meiste en waz mast laz / in eyn stist zu hat sy gaz / dy iz suneleshin vy / dy er veltg vin zu ger moyin / dy er haste by sin orsishen gut / ist er den lis her obw dy blatt / der er meste ome vin sin / ez meiste vin dy grin sin / er en gen hin zu schiste wider / der meiste bundise sider",
    english: "The chronicle describes diplomatic maneuvering between the Order and the Russian principalities. Envoys arrived from the Russian side seeking negotiations, and the Master received them cautiously. The Russians proposed a settlement that would define the boundary between German and Russian spheres of influence, ending the costly border warfare that drained both sides.\n\nThe Master was willing to negotiate but insisted on terms favorable to the Order. He demanded recognition of German authority over all the territories already conquered, including several border districts that the Russians considered part of their sphere. The chronicle records the back-and-forth of the negotiations, with each side pressing for advantage.\n\nThe Lithuanian factor complicated the diplomacy. Both the Order and the Russians feared Lithuanian power, and there was a logic to cooperation against the common pagan threat. The chronicle describes tentative discussions about a joint Christian campaign against Lithuania — an alliance that would have combined German military technology with Russian manpower.\n\nHowever, deep theological and political divisions prevented any lasting agreement. The Order viewed the Orthodox Russians as schismatics, while the Russians resented the aggressive Catholicism that accompanied German expansion. The chronicle records the mutual suspicion that poisoned every attempt at cooperation.\n\nThe negotiations ultimately produced a temporary truce rather than a permanent peace. Both sides agreed to cease hostilities for a specified period, during which trade would be permitted across the border. The chronicle presents this outcome as a diplomatic success, though it acknowledges that the underlying conflicts remained unresolved.\n\n[Folio 239v describes Russian-German diplomatic negotiations. Both sides seek a boundary settlement. Tentative discussions about anti-Lithuanian cooperation. Theological divisions prevent lasting agreement. A temporary truce agreed, with trade permitted across borders.]",
  },
  "240r": {
    original: "Von durbit bischoff frederich / dy gut wol eyn helde glich / ist ir allin dy sy moste dan / dy legiste smu diti dri an / sy gut mit siny servot / der wuelschtin in gotschar / dy meiste bruste dy wul meshil ber / ist ey grus of duz volde mer / dy er sinist ande bruge dil / der er von reule ber suerth / ey en allin ich wol gutis gein / dy ost her druiste",
    english: "The chronicle introduces Bishop Friedrich of Dorpat (Tartu), described as a warrior-bishop who combined ecclesiastical authority with military prowess. Friedrich was one of the most colorful figures of the Baltic crusade — a churchman who wore armor as readily as vestments and led his own retinue of armed men into battle.\n\nThe bishop's participation in the military campaigns was both an asset and a source of tension. His troops added valuable strength to the Order's forces, but his independent authority sometimes conflicted with the Master's strategic plans. The chronicle describes their relationship as one of grudging cooperation — both men recognized the need for unity against the common enemy, but neither was willing to subordinate himself entirely to the other.\n\nBishop Friedrich organized a campaign against a Russian border district that had been raiding his diocese. He assembled a force of his own retainers, supplemented by brothers from the Order and pilgrim knights from Germany, and marched east toward the Russian frontier. The expedition was well-planned and well-supplied, reflecting Friedrich's considerable military experience.\n\nThe campaign achieved its immediate objectives — the Russian raiders were driven back, their base of operations captured, and a punitive raid conducted into Russian territory. The chronicle describes the expedition with approval, noting that the bishop fought bravely alongside his men, inspiring them by personal example.\n\nThe chapter mentions the fall of Master Otto in battle — a significant loss that the chronicle treats with solemn gravity. The death of a Master was always a critical moment for the Order, requiring the rapid election of a successor to maintain continuity of command.\n\n[Folio 240r introduces warrior-Bishop Friedrich of Dorpat. He leads his own military campaigns against Russian border raiders. Tensions with the Order over independent authority. A successful punitive expedition into Russian territory. Master Otto falls in battle — a critical loss.]",
  },
  "240v": {
    original: "Hin zu zwene din siminge brude / dy er gris in diz gest iz blit gut / do iz er ouch maniy musin hest / in bosltin sent sin zu ir best / lan wollis ul eyn sol / dy er gebe vy solde dy heil / der ez wulz blisn meyste tot / dy er muiz mande mangen / der ez mut wirt der more / dy ez halst of dez moris in / of dy brid her du der / der briden der ez",
    english: "The chronicle describes the election of a new Master following Otto's death in battle. The surviving brothers assembled in solemn conclave to choose his successor. The election process followed the Order's strict rules — each commandery sent its representatives, and the votes were cast in secret after days of prayer and deliberation.\n\nThe new Master was chosen for his military experience and political acumen — qualities essential for a leader who must simultaneously fight pagans, negotiate with Christian rivals, and govern a vast territory. The chronicle describes the installation ceremony with reverence: the new Master receiving the symbols of his office — the seal, the sword, and the keys to the Order's treasury.\n\nThe new leader immediately faced a crisis. The Lithuanians, learning of the change in leadership, launched a major raid testing the Order's resolve under its new commander. The timing was deliberate — the pagans hoped to find the brothers disorganized and demoralized by the loss of their previous Master.\n\nThe chronicle describes the new Master's response with admiration. He rallied the brothers swiftly, organized a defensive force, and repelled the Lithuanian raid with minimal losses. The successful defense established his authority and demonstrated that the Order's institutional strength transcended any individual leader.\n\nThe brothers took heart from the new Master's competence. The chronicle records a surge of optimism — after the shock of Otto's death, the Order found itself in capable hands. The mission would continue, the borders would be defended, and the work of conversion would proceed.\n\n[Folio 240v describes the election of a new Master after Otto's death. The installation ceremony with symbols of office. Lithuanians test the new leader with a major raid. The new Master repels the attack, establishing his authority. The Order's institutional strength transcends individual leadership.]",
  },
  "241r": {
    original: "Do er warz abir dy ruske / inde dy slege muile / di er bur alle meslint / dy er ist die lat geroist wul / iz dy buch ouch wol sagen sol / dy meiste sin unmeslant / der er heer vor vordeste quam / dy er her nim solde en dy wal / dy iz heer vn volsiete ane zal / do er woltt man dy gebrin / daz er dier dis her bis lehm / dy er wart do geslist wol",
    english: "The chronicle returns to the Russian frontier, where hostilities had resumed after the expiration of the temporary truce. The new Master organized a major campaign against the Russian principalities, assembling the largest force the Livonian branch could muster. The expedition was designed to demonstrate the Order's continued military capability despite the recent change in leadership.\n\nThe army marched east in force, crossing into Russian territory with the intention of striking at the fortified trading posts that served as the Russian principalities' forward bases. The chronicle describes the column — brothers in their white mantles with the black cross, Estonian and Livonian auxiliaries in lighter equipment, supply wagons stretching far behind the main body.\n\nThe Russians were prepared for the invasion. They had used the truce period to strengthen their fortifications and assemble their own army. The chronicle describes the Russian force with grudging respect — well-armed warriors in chainmail and conical helmets, mounted on sturdy horses, their ranks supplemented by Finnish and Karelian allies from the north.\n\nThe engagement that followed was one of the largest battles the Order fought on its eastern frontier. The chronicle describes the clash in epic terms — the thunder of charging cavalry, the crash of lances against shields, the screams of wounded men and horses. The fighting surged back and forth across a frozen field, neither side able to gain a decisive advantage.\n\nThe battle ended inconclusively, with both armies withdrawing to their bases after suffering heavy casualties. The chronicle presents this as a strategic victory for the Order — the Russians had been prevented from advancing into German territory — though it acknowledges that the objective of destroying the Russian forward bases had not been achieved.\n\n[Folio 241r describes a major campaign against the Russian principalities. The largest Livonian force assembled. Russians prepared with strengthened fortifications. A large-scale battle on the eastern frontier ends inconclusively. Heavy casualties on both sides. Strategic stalemate on the Russian front.]",
  },
  "241v": {
    original: "Dez er wure sy als dro / erne gose suche den meisit do / dez er bonis en dy sone lide / der ey musit dy drime bruiste ort / daz er hostelis in dur drushen der / dy ey wuist din dy is wigestar / dy er buist inde dy er gant / du en allit iz vnt der sat / inde nobit dy orse clagin dne / dy waz was her genaze / sy quam indie brusden lant / dy er sunste in ger zu meslant / do enpfing dy iz orstemeny",
    english: "The chronicle describes the aftermath of the eastern campaign and the Master's efforts to manage the Order's multiple commitments. The strain of fighting on three fronts simultaneously — against Lithuanians in the south, Russians in the east, and rebellious native peoples within the Order's own territories — was taking a severe toll on the brothers' numbers and morale.\n\nThe Master convened a general chapter of all the Order's Livonian commanders to assess the strategic situation. The picture that emerged was sobering: garrisons were undermanned, fortifications in need of repair, and the supply of fresh recruits from Germany inadequate to replace the steady stream of casualties. The Order was slowly being ground down by the relentless demands of frontier warfare.\n\nThe chronicle records the Master's appeal to the Grand Master in Prussia for additional support. He described the dire situation in Livonia with stark honesty — without reinforcements, the Order risked losing territories that had been won through decades of blood and sacrifice. The Grand Master responded by sending a contingent of Prussian brothers and allocating additional funds for Livonian defense.\n\nThe arrival of the Prussian reinforcements lifted spirits throughout the territory. The chronicle describes the brothers' relief at seeing fresh faces and hearing news from the wider Order. The Prussian brothers brought not only military strength but also news from Germany — reports of papal pronouncements, imperial politics, and the broader crusading movement.\n\nThe chapter concludes with the Master's reorganization of the frontier defenses. Garrisons were reshuffled, new patrol routes established, and communication protocols improved. The Order settled into a defensive posture, conserving its strength for the inevitable next round of offensive operations.\n\n[Folio 241v describes the strain of three-front warfare. A general chapter reveals undermanned garrisons and inadequate recruitment. The Master appeals to Prussia for reinforcements. Prussian brothers arrive with additional resources. The Master reorganizes frontier defenses into a defensive posture.]",
  },
  "242r": {
    original: "Be eyal nach des ordens stze / dy er schidin sy sich mute / der er ernestit von in slant / dy ein sinne linde ist zu hat / do dy her do zu rege quam / in mese in dy sine nam / wen sy wuis in dit wal schele / dez er vist sint als ey bekint / ez guin enn tot den bruide / daz er wart duke von druishin bol / du als ouch dez bonte chostewide",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's internal governance according to its monastic rule — the daily rhythm of prayer, discipline, and military readiness that defined the brothers' lives. The Order's regulations governed every aspect of existence, from the schedule of divine services to the rules for distributing plunder after a successful campaign.\n\nThe Master convened a general chapter to address administrative matters and resolve disputes between the commanderies. These chapters were the Order's supreme governing body, where policy was debated, commanders appointed, and grievances heard. The chronicle describes the proceedings with the formality befitting a quasi-parliamentary institution.\n\nA major topic of discussion was the fortification of Dünaburg (Daugavpils), a strategically vital castle on the Daugava River that controlled the main waterway connecting Livonia to Lithuania and the Russian territories. The castle had been damaged in recent fighting and required significant investment to restore it to full defensive capability.\n\nThe Master ordered the reconstruction and expansion of Dünaburg, allocating resources from across the territory. The castle would be rebuilt in stone, replacing the older timber construction with more durable materials. The chronicle describes the ambitious building program — new walls, towers, a fortified harbor for river craft, and expanded barracks for a larger garrison.\n\nThe King of Denmark's representatives also attended the chapter, seeking to resolve ongoing disputes over the governance of northern Estonia. The Danish crown still claimed sovereignty over the territories it had conquered in 1219, and the relationship between Danish and German authorities remained a source of friction.\n\n[Folio 242r describes the Order's governance — general chapters, monastic rule, internal administration. Dünaburg castle ordered rebuilt in stone. Ambitious expansion program for this strategic Daugava River fortress. Danish representatives attend to discuss northern Estonian governance disputes.]",
  },
  "242v": {
    original: "Dy er swin en ale dy planke wis / dy er some dy bure her urde dru / dy er brud nanis dez war / wis er bruste duishe dure / daz er mis do bure ist dy blure / dy er solem wort endeliste / der er wuze mast glisde / dy er aust dir dy wulgin / daz er mid vin de heiden her / daz ein wul it syv din din / dy er vuisit ich sint lelie dud drusit",
    english: "The chronicle describes the completion of the Dünaburg reconstruction and the strengthening of the Order's entire network of fortifications along the Daugava River. These castles formed a defensive chain that controlled the major east-west waterway, enabling the brothers to monitor and intercept any hostile force attempting to use the river as an invasion route.\n\nThe Order's engineering achievements are described with evident pride. The brothers had transformed the Baltic landscape, dotting it with stone castles, fortified churches, and walled towns that projected German power across the conquered territories. Each fortress was a self-contained military community — a miniature of the Order's entire organization, with its own commander, garrison, chapel, and administrative apparatus.\n\nThe chronicle then turns to a renewed confrontation with pagan forces. A coalition of Lithuanian and Samogitian warriors launched a coordinated attack on the Order's southern frontier, striking at multiple points simultaneously. The brothers' fortification network proved its worth — the castles held firm, breaking up the pagan assault into separate, manageable engagements.\n\nThe garrison of each castle fought independently, trusting that the neighboring fortresses would prevent their encirclement. Signal fires blazed from tower to tower, alerting the Master to the scale and direction of the attack. The chronicle describes this communication system with admiration — in an era before telecommunications, the Order's signal network provided something approaching real-time battlefield intelligence.\n\nThe attack was repulsed after several days of fighting, the Lithuanian-Samogitian force withdrawing after failing to capture any of the Order's major fortifications. The chronicle presents this as a vindication of the castle-building strategy — stone walls and disciplined garrisons had proven more than a match for pagan numbers.\n\n[Folio 242v describes the completed Daugava fortification chain. The Order's engineering achievements across the Baltic. A Lithuanian-Samogitian coalition attacks the southern frontier. The castle network holds — signal fires coordinate defense. The attack is repulsed, vindicating the fortification strategy.]",
  },
  "243r": {
    original: "Dy me rint eist sy sruntin mis / wen ey suldin dy in bereit / der er hast wart in dy gelesit / dy er rode late vin bestin / Vin halberg dy er olant / wuste sich of dy wart / dy er waz zu vouste hauil man / dy er ene sinse stsar man / dy er sinse dy sy gar / inde suge von der esse sin / do der meiste vin dy sinni / der er ruder vii sulgerinin",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's military equipment and tactical organization in detail — one of the most informative passages for understanding medieval Baltic warfare. The brothers' armor is described: full chainmail hauberks, supplemented by plate protection on the shoulders, arms, and legs, topped with great helms that enclosed the entire head.\n\nThe brothers fought primarily as heavy cavalry, their warhorses also protected with quilted or mail armor. The chronicle describes the devastating effect of a mounted charge by armored knights — a wall of iron and horseflesh that could shatter any infantry formation and send lighter cavalry fleeing. This tactical advantage was the Order's greatest military asset.\n\nHowever, the chronicle also acknowledges the limitations of heavy cavalry in the Baltic environment. The dense forests, marshes, and rough terrain of the region frequently prevented the brothers from deploying their cavalry effectively. In such conditions, the knights were forced to dismount and fight on foot — a situation that negated their primary advantage and exposed them to the superior mobility of their lighter-armed opponents.\n\nThe Order adapted its tactics to these conditions, developing specialized formations and techniques for forest warfare. Scouts and light cavalry screened the advance, identifying suitable terrain for cavalry charges and warning of ambushes. The brothers learned to fight in smaller, more flexible units when the terrain demanded it, abandoning the massive charges that worked well on open ground.\n\nThe chronicle also describes the role of the native auxiliaries — Livonian, Estonian, and Curonian warriors who fought alongside the brothers in their own traditional style. These auxiliary forces provided essential capabilities that the heavily armored brothers lacked: scouting, skirmishing, and pursuit of fleeing enemies through terrain too difficult for armored knights.\n\n[Folio 243r describes the Order's military equipment and tactics in detail. Heavy cavalry as the primary fighting force. Limitations in forested Baltic terrain. Adapted forest warfare tactics with smaller, flexible units. Native auxiliaries provide scouting and skirmishing capabilities.]",
  },
  "243v": {
    original: "Do en osten diu von haden / dy er ouch hin suln gasiten in holt / der er bruist diz dy we welsit / der er edirt vin duz golsis uis / dez er guist en eyn sonnen vat / dy er wolde dy heiden er sulde gen / dy er gruize in ez eu sorten / dy er brudme halde dir / daz en halde dy vet mer hat / dez er yohin buiz dy er genant / dez er blak der brud tot",
    english: "The chronicle describes a devastating battle that resulted in the death of several brothers, including a commander of noble reputation. The Order had pursued a Lithuanian raiding party into the forests, but the chase led them into a carefully prepared ambush. The Lithuanians had drawn the brothers deep into unfavorable terrain before springing their trap.\n\nThe ambush was executed with terrible efficiency. Lithuanian warriors emerged from concealment on all sides, cutting off the brothers' retreat and surrounding them in a narrow forest clearing. The brothers formed a defensive circle, their backs to each other, shields raised against the hail of missiles that poured from the treeline.\n\nThe fighting was savage and protracted. The brothers held their formation with iron discipline, their armor turning aside many of the Lithuanian arrows and javelins. But the pagans pressed closer and closer, wearing down the defenders through sheer weight of numbers. The chronicle describes individual brothers falling one by one, each loss weakening the defensive circle.\n\nThe commander fought until the end, refusing offers to surrender. The chronicle records his last stand with the reverence reserved for martyrs — he died with his sword in his hand, his face toward the enemy, committing his soul to God with his final breath. His death and that of his companions are presented as holy sacrifices.\n\nThe few survivors who managed to cut their way out of the encirclement carried the grim news back to the Order's nearest castle. The Master received the report with grief but also with the grim determination that characterized the Order's response to adversity — the fallen would be avenged, the enemy would be punished.\n\n[Folio 243v describes a devastating ambush. The Order pursues Lithuanian raiders into a trap. Brothers surrounded and cut off in a forest clearing. A commander makes a heroic last stand. Few survivors escape. The Master vows vengeance for the fallen.]",
  },
  "244r": {
    original: "Dy er wen sich von dannen / von den gastem hirin many / dy er schist wart do wer geslaget / daz er mugt ul waldin clage / dy er gure grein wol sine tar / dy er buist we dy brude dote / sy er slaqere diruside dit man / iz er waz den daz gest slie / in er mesit orsit we geslaget / daz der linde ey gros slug / der er slaquis dir wuise vit man / dy er muist diz hin bur alle amen",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's punitive response to the ambush. The Master assembled an overwhelming force and launched a retaliatory campaign deep into the territory from which the Lithuanian raiders had come. The brothers advanced with grim determination, their grief for the fallen comrades transformed into a cold fury that drove them forward.\n\nThe retaliation was thorough and merciless. Every settlement in the target area was destroyed — buildings burned, livestock killed or seized, grain stores put to the torch. The chronicle describes the devastation without remorse, presenting it as righteous punishment for the murder of Christian warriors who had been fighting in God's cause.\n\nThe Lithuanian warriors who had carried out the ambush attempted to resist the German advance but were overwhelmed by the Order's superior numbers and equipment. The chronicle records several smaller engagements in which Lithuanian war bands were cornered and destroyed, their fighters killed to the last man. No quarter was given — the brothers were avenging their fallen brothers.\n\nThe campaign continued until the targeted region was thoroughly devastated. The chronicle describes the scorched landscape — blackened ruins where villages had stood, fields littered with the carcasses of slaughtered animals, the forest itself scarred by fire. The brothers intended this destruction as a warning: any attack on the Order would be repaid tenfold.\n\nThe Master then ordered the construction of a new fortification in the devastated area, establishing a permanent German military presence where none had existed before. The castle would serve as both a memorial to the fallen brothers and a deterrent against future Lithuanian raids.\n\n[Folio 244r describes the Order's devastating retaliatory campaign. Total destruction of the target region — settlements burned, livestock killed. Lithuanian resistance overwhelmed. No quarter given. A new fortress built in the devastated area as memorial and deterrent.]",
  },
  "244v": {
    original: "Dez er sehin sy alsgemene do / dy er mostu wart dy rius dro / daz er meist gris daz in sy gelumist / daz brid omuist du do gedinist / dy olet is dy er nue gin / dy er rutte alsgemene sin / dez ma beuele mesne hat / dez er osz sin dy er moste grin / dy er slein ane brud du vin qua / iz er botz volimit din man lat",
    english: "The chronicle describes a general assembly of the Order's forces, summoned by the Master to plan a comprehensive strategy for the coming year. The brothers gathered from across the territory — from the Estonian fortresses in the north to the Semigallian borderlands in the south — to participate in what the chronicle presents as a pivotal moment of collective decision-making.\n\nThe Master laid out the strategic situation with brutal honesty. The Order was stretched across an enormous frontier, facing threats from Lithuanians, Samogitians, Russians, and restive native populations simultaneously. Resources were finite, reinforcements from Germany were slow to arrive, and the brothers' numbers were being steadily depleted by the unrelenting pace of frontier warfare.\n\nThe assembly debated priorities. Some commanders argued for concentrating forces against Lithuania, the greatest strategic threat. Others insisted that the Semigallian frontier required immediate attention, as a major revolt was brewing. Still others warned that the Russian principalities were probing the eastern borders and could launch a major offensive at any time.\n\nThe Master's decision was pragmatic: maintain a defensive posture on all fronts while building up strength for a single decisive campaign against the most pressing threat. The chronicle records this strategy with approval, noting that it reflected the Order's institutional wisdom — patience, discipline, and calculated force rather than reckless aggression.\n\nThe assembly also addressed administrative matters: the appointment of new Komturs, the allocation of revenues between commanderies, and the resolution of disputes between the Order and the bishops. The chronicle describes these proceedings as essential to the Order's functioning, even if they lacked the drama of battlefield narratives.\n\n[Folio 244v describes a general assembly planning comprehensive strategy. The Master honestly assesses the overstretched position. Debate over priorities — Lithuania, Semigallia, or Russia. A pragmatic defensive strategy adopted. Administrative matters addressed — appointments, revenue allocation, disputes.]",
  },
  "245r": {
    original: "Lan muchy surige sy dy las / daz ey sul der er bruste wist / der du zu mist brunde / ey von her dy der beginde / dy er paniin dit sisien / des lisen in gonzen / dy er guste dy brud iz gut / aste dy man bure belint / vu meulichen dy brud it gut / daz er wolt ist lelie dud druist / waz eyn vuide wushen din / dy er brude waz in in gosit",
    english: "The chronicle describes a period of intense castle-building and frontier consolidation. The Order constructed a series of new fortifications along the most threatened sections of the frontier, creating an interlocking defensive network that could support rapid reinforcement of any point under attack.\n\nThe construction program was enormous in scale. The chronicle lists several new castles by name, describing their locations and strategic functions. Each was designed to control a specific terrain feature — a river crossing, a mountain pass, or a section of the trade route — and was positioned within signaling distance of its neighbors.\n\nThe brothers supervised the construction with meticulous attention to detail. The chronicle describes the Master personally inspecting building sites, checking the thickness of walls, testing the depth of moats, and ensuring that each castle met the Order's exacting standards. The fortresses were built to last centuries, their stone walls and iron-bound gates designed to withstand any siege weapon the pagans could deploy.\n\nThe Semigallian laborers who provided much of the manual labor were treated as a conquered workforce — required to perform heavy physical labor under German supervision, fed minimally, and punished harshly for any resistance or slowness. The chronicle records this without comment, treating forced native labor as a natural part of the colonial enterprise.\n\nThe completion of the defensive network marked a new phase in the Order's Baltic presence. No longer merely a raiding force or a temporary military expedition, the Order had established a permanent, fortified state that could absorb attacks, project power, and sustain itself indefinitely. The chronicle presents this transformation with evident satisfaction.\n\n[Folio 245r describes an intensive castle-building program. An interlocking defensive network created along the frontier. The Master personally inspects construction. Forced Semigallian labor used. The Order transitions from raiding force to permanent fortified state.]",
  },
  "245v": {
    original: "Vi ist dy nor bruine sy vor / dot haste me zele dy all nor / dy er brud mile of ey eber / in grume vor der buise sut / dy er buiste sy ir brude bor / daz er was ul war der wam / dy er brudis vin dy er sint / diz er meiste sint dy gar / dy er sluge der sime gallin sy / dy er simigallin dy er brude daz / dez er vist vor han gelesin / der in dez meiste sint waz",
    english: "The chronicle describes the final phase of the Semigallian wars — the last great resistance of this Baltic people against German domination. The Semigallians, recognizing that the Order's new fortification network was closing around them like a noose, made a desperate bid for freedom.\n\nThe Semigallian leaders organized a coordinated uprising, timing their revolt to coincide with a Lithuanian attack on the Order's southern frontier. The plan was ambitious — if the Order was forced to divide its forces between two threats, the Semigallians might break free of German control permanently.\n\nThe uprising began with simultaneous attacks on German settlements throughout Semigallian territory. The chronicle describes the violence with horror — German families murdered in their homes, churches burned with their congregations inside, the Order's administrative officials hunted down and killed. The savagery of the revolt reflected years of accumulated resentment against foreign rule.\n\nThe brothers responded with the full weight of the Order's military capability. The Master declared a crusade against the Semigallians, summoning every available warrior to the campaign. The chronicle describes the mobilization — brothers riding from every castle, pilgrim knights taking up arms, native auxiliaries assembling under their German commanders.\n\nThe campaign that followed was the most comprehensive military operation the Order had conducted in Semigallia. The brothers advanced systematically through the territory, reducing every hill-fort, burning every settlement that had participated in the revolt, and hunting down the rebel leaders with relentless determination.\n\n[Folio 245v describes the final Semigallian revolt — coordinated with Lithuanian attacks. Simultaneous attacks on German settlements. Brutal violence against German families and churches. The Master declares a crusade. The most comprehensive campaign in Semigallia begins — systematic reduction of every stronghold.]",
  },
  "246r": {
    original: "Do sy zu ruge anamen / dy er briden duz vor namen / dy er kneitingen lustliche / Bede arm inde riche / dez der meiste stat do wulst / dez ey ouch dage dis ist wur / dy er polde dar vu wil heger / dy er qua vu sine dinam / in dy hame ist wol grist / der er brud diz vu mist grise / daz iz in muststen tage slege / in er malte sich of dy wart",
    english: "The chronicle describes the suppression of the Semigallian revolt in its final stages. The Order's forces converged on the last major Semigallian hill-fort, where the rebel leaders had gathered with their remaining warriors and their families. The siege was conducted with methodical thoroughness — the castle surrounded, supply lines cut, and a constant bombardment maintained against the wooden walls.\n\nThe Master offered terms of surrender — the Semigallian fighters could submit and live, or resist and die. The chronicle records that some of the defenders accepted, emerging from the fortress to kneel before the brothers and beg for mercy. Others refused, preferring death to submission.\n\nThe final assault was launched when the defenders' resistance was clearly weakening. The brothers stormed the walls from multiple directions, overwhelming the exhausted garrison after fierce hand-to-hand fighting. The chronicle describes the fall of the fortress as both a military victory and a spiritual triumph — the last great pagan stronghold in Semigallia had fallen.\n\nThe aftermath was decisive. The surviving Semigallian warriors were dispersed — some executed as rebels, others exiled to distant parts of the Order's territory, and still others absorbed into the Order's auxiliary forces. The Semigallian people as an independent political entity ceased to exist.\n\nThe chronicle notes this moment with a mixture of triumph and melancholy. The Semigallians had been formidable opponents — brave, resourceful, and deeply attached to their freedom. Their subjugation marked the end of an era, but the Order's mission demanded nothing less than total control.\n\n[Folio 246r describes the final siege and fall of the last Semigallian stronghold. Terms offered — submit or die. Some defenders surrender, others fight to the end. The final assault overwhelms the garrison. Semigallian warriors dispersed. The Semigallian people cease to exist as an independent entity.]",
  },
  "246v": {
    original: "Kem dem meistir den sant / daz est it mandez bekint / dy er drustin gen lustishin / dy er mostly dy er naim / dy er buist diz wol lebn mit / dy er slonge dy dy er sint / dy er groise got dy dini grise / dy er brud vomis pilgerim / ernoist do masle en lis / dy er brudis slisin hitz / de en sliemie in din ureiste / dy er brudi du sinse sit / dy er meiste buist dy er grise",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Master's report to the Grand Master in Prussia on the successful conclusion of the Semigallian campaign. The message was carried by trusted brothers who traveled the dangerous overland route between Livonia and Prussia, bearing detailed accounts of the victory and requests for further support.\n\nThe Grand Master received the news with satisfaction and ordered celebrations throughout the Order's Prussian territories. The subjugation of Semigallia removed one of the Order's most persistent threats and secured the overland route connecting the Livonian and Prussian branches — a vital strategic corridor.\n\nThe chronicle describes the arrival of fresh pilgrim-crusaders from Germany, drawn by the news of the Order's victories and the papal indulgences offered to participants in the Baltic crusade. These pilgrims brought not only military manpower but also financial contributions that helped replenish the Order's depleted treasury.\n\nThe Master deployed the new arrivals to the frontier garrisons, replacing brothers who had been worn down by years of continuous warfare. The chronicle describes the rotation system — veteran brothers withdrawn to the Order's larger houses for rest and recovery, while fresh fighters took their places on the front lines.\n\nThe chapter closes with a description of the Order's spiritual life during this period. The brothers maintained their monastic routine with scrupulous devotion — daily masses, the canonical hours, communal meals eaten in silence while scripture was read aloud. The chronicle presents this spiritual discipline as the foundation of the Order's military success — men who prayed together fought together.\n\n[Folio 246v describes the Master's victory report to Prussia. Celebrations ordered. The Livonia-Prussia overland route secured. Fresh pilgrim-crusaders arrive from Germany. Veteran brothers rotated from front lines. The Order's monastic spiritual discipline described as the foundation of military success.]",
  },
  "247r": {
    original: "Lur sworen in obir al / do dy hub gy sich of dy wart / hin begin dubelin wart / dy ouch wige wis dule walst / iz wur gy manchy begin hast / dy er geshert wir ouch zu drise / dy er hast ouch dy er muge / sint sunelishin brinke / daz ane man sine gutse / sy er voget dez waz drise",
    english: "The chronicle describes a major military operation centered on the fortress of Doblen (Dobele), one of the most important strategic positions in the Semigallian territories. The Order had decided to rebuild and significantly expand this castle, transforming it from a wooden frontier post into a formidable stone fortress that would anchor the southern defense line.\n\nThe construction attracted attention from the Order's enemies. Lithuanian and Semigallian scouts observed the building activity with alarm, recognizing that a strengthened Doblen would dramatically increase German control over the region. The chronicle describes their intelligence-gathering — watchers hidden in the forest, counting the workers, estimating the progress of construction.\n\nThe Vogt (governor) of the district was responsible for overseeing both the construction and the defense of the building site. The chronicle describes his dual challenge — maintaining the pace of construction while guarding against attack. The workers labored under armed guard, with brothers patrolling the surrounding forest to detect approaching enemy forces.\n\nA Lithuanian raiding party attempted to disrupt the construction by attacking the building site. The brothers repelled the assault after sharp fighting, but the incident underscored the dangers of building fortifications in contested territory. The chronicle records the names of brothers who distinguished themselves in the defense.\n\nThe castle of Doblen was completed despite the opposition, its stone walls rising above the Semigallian landscape as an unmistakable statement of German permanence. The chronicle describes the finished fortress with pride — its towers, its chapel, its storerooms stocked with provisions for a year-long siege.\n\n[Folio 247r describes the construction and defense of Doblen castle. Expansion from wooden post to stone fortress. Lithuanian scouts observe the construction. A raiding party attacks the building site but is repelled. The completed castle anchors the southern defense line.]",
  },
  "247v": {
    original: "Dy er quamy dy aster hure an / daz wart den dogene hat gestin / dy er was denmoch gor brunt / daz er waz trudiz syn gestunle / bor der gul din synen wust / daz sy er mist en din dorian / vin ist en goze wude grat / dez er wuiste duv mist ist dun / dy er quome sime gallin sint / der er waiste und ist nue zu der / der er kometuir vin der vogt",
    english: "The chronicle describes the administrative organization of the conquered Semigallian territories following the final pacification. The Order divided the region into administrative districts, each under the authority of a Komtur or Vogt who was responsible for maintaining order, collecting tribute, and administering justice.\n\nThe transition from military conquest to civil governance was fraught with challenges. The Semigallian population, though militarily defeated, remained hostile to German rule. The chronicle describes acts of passive resistance — refusal to attend church services, deliberate destruction of crops to avoid paying tribute, and the concealment of weapons in defiance of the Order's disarmament decrees.\n\nThe Order responded with a combination of coercion and incentive. Those who cooperated with the new regime were rewarded with favorable land grants and reduced tribute obligations. Those who resisted were punished — publicly, to serve as examples. The chronicle describes the establishment of German courts where disputes were adjudicated according to a blend of German law and local custom.\n\nThe Komtur and Vogt of each district maintained small garrisons — typically five to ten brothers with their servants and a contingent of native auxiliaries. These forces were sufficient to maintain order in peacetime but could be rapidly reinforced from neighboring castles in case of emergency.\n\nThe chronicle notes that the quality of governance varied significantly between districts. Some Komturs were wise and fair administrators who earned the grudging respect of their native subjects. Others were harsh and greedy, provoking the very unrest they were supposed to prevent.\n\n[Folio 247v describes post-conquest administration of Semigallia. Districts under Komturs and Vogts. Passive resistance from the population. Coercion and incentive used to establish order. Small garrison forces maintained. Quality of governance varies between administrators.]",
  },
  "248r": {
    original: "Daz ez din alge nalen was / sy ein eil ud visthe lon wis blag / dy er mit dem here druise somo / dy er ouch waz brud mud genomiy / an hiz sy er mit den bogete ge / dy er wasn boin dubelin stuch / dy er vist iz den sige mat dy nach / dy er gest erle gesmase er / vin dy quami un din bere / daz er grist vid dy vornam / in wuz dy kometur ouch komiz / daz er dubelin als mist dy nome",
    english: "The chronicle describes a critical episode in the defense of the newly built Doblen castle. A major Lithuanian force appeared before the fortress, having marched through the forest in secret to avoid the Order's patrol network. The garrison was caught by surprise — the Lithuanians were already at the gates before the alarm was raised.\n\nThe Vogt of Doblen rallied his small garrison with cool professionalism. The brothers manned the walls, the drawbridge was raised, and the castle's defenses activated. The chronicle describes the tense first hours of the siege — the Lithuanians probing the defenses, testing for weaknesses, while the garrison assessed the enemy's numbers and capabilities.\n\nThe Lithuanian force was too large to be repelled by the garrison alone, but the castle's stone walls were proof against anything the pagans could bring to bear. The Lithuanians lacked effective siege equipment — they could surround the castle and cut it off, but they could not breach the walls or scale the towers.\n\nMessengers were dispatched from the castle, slipping out through a hidden postern gate under cover of darkness to carry word of the siege to the nearest Order garrison. The chronicle describes the perilous journey of these messengers through Lithuanian-held territory, navigating by starlight through the winter forest.\n\nThe Komtur of a neighboring castle assembled a relief force and marched to Doblen's aid. The Lithuanians, caught between the castle garrison and the approaching relief column, chose to withdraw rather than fight on two fronts. The siege was lifted after several days, vindicating the Order's investment in stone fortifications.\n\n[Folio 248r describes a Lithuanian siege of Doblen castle. The garrison is surprised but rallies behind stone walls. Lithuanians lack siege equipment. Messengers slip out for help. A relief force from a neighboring castle approaches. The Lithuanians withdraw — stone fortifications vindicated.]",
  },
  "248v": {
    original: "Iz suse den pilgerin brunt / dy quamy in ul wis slomit / en winde wis zu rege some / zur lienz als ich han duome / ein brud dit wol brudi man / dy er wost daz wie sul grat / dy er quami genusliin du biz / diz er wuiz was wird dishen vien / dy er haste muz dy er sin gen / dy er modiste dy burg gelosin / daz er des lande dy er grist / her ey gismagesn vinke brant",
    english: "The chronicle describes the arrival of a major contingent of pilgrim-crusaders from Germany, the largest in recent years. These knights and their retinues had taken the cross in response to papal appeals and the Order's own recruiting efforts, traveling to the Baltic to participate in the seasonal crusading campaigns.\n\nThe pilgrims were housed in the Order's castles and briefed on the military situation. The chronicle describes the cultural clash between the western European knights — accustomed to the refined courtesy of tournament warfare — and the brutal realities of the Baltic frontier. Some pilgrims were shocked by the harshness of the conditions and the savagery of the fighting.\n\nThe Master organized the pilgrims into a combined force with the Order's regular brothers and launched a major campaign into Lithuanian territory. The expedition was designed to inflict maximum damage in the limited time available — the pilgrim crusaders typically served for only a single season before returning home.\n\nThe campaign struck deep into the Lithuanian interior, burning settlements, seizing livestock, and destroying stored food supplies. The chronicle describes the systematic nature of the devastation — the army advanced in a broad front, ensuring that nothing of value was left standing in its wake.\n\nThe Lithuanians responded with their characteristic guerrilla tactics, harassing the column's flanks and ambushing stragglers. The chronicle records several sharp skirmishes in which pilgrim knights, unfamiliar with forest warfare, suffered casualties that more experienced brothers might have avoided.\n\n[Folio 248v describes a large pilgrim-crusader contingent arriving from Germany. Cultural clash between western knights and Baltic frontier realities. A major campaign into Lithuanian territory launched. Systematic devastation of Lithuanian settlements. Pilgrim knights suffer casualties from unfamiliar guerrilla warfare.]",
  },
  "249r": {
    original: "Daz sy much listin wiren / lir soltin noch leuz diren / dy er sich diz her gomeine do / daz er gute more sy wir dro / dy er neste wart die ho gesthat / in er guz of der heidin sint / der er sulgewune dogete vor / daz er wait wir diz slagen / ein geloke in deit geschist / dy er ruslin vol dristin dir iz las / hy wus der some duz sy diz wur",
    english: "The chronicle describes the concluding phase of the Lithuanian campaign and the Order's assessment of its results. The army withdrew from Lithuanian territory as the season ended, laden with plunder but having failed to achieve any permanent territorial gains. The Lithuanians, though badly hurt by the devastation, remained unbroken and defiant.\n\nThe Master evaluated the campaign with characteristic pragmatism. The immediate military objectives had been achieved — Lithuanian military capacity had been degraded, their food supplies destroyed, and their population terrorized. But the chronicle acknowledges that these results were temporary — the Lithuanians would rebuild, replant, and rearm before the next campaigning season.\n\nThe pilgrim-crusaders departed for home, their spiritual obligations fulfilled. The chronicle describes their departure with mixed feelings — gratitude for their service, but also frustration at the transient nature of crusading warfare. The seasonal pilgrims provided valuable short-term military strength but could not substitute for the permanent garrison forces that the Order needed.\n\nThe Vogt (governor) of the frontier districts was left to manage the aftermath with his regular garrison — a handful of brothers and their auxiliaries, responsible for defending a vast stretch of borderland against Lithuanian retaliation. The chronicle describes the lonely vigilance of these frontier posts, manned by brothers who knew they could expect no relief until the next crusading season.\n\nThe chapter closes with the Order settling into its winter quarters, the brothers attending to the endless tasks of maintaining their castles, training recruits, and preparing for the campaigns of the coming year. The cycle of warfare that defined the Order's existence in the Baltic showed no sign of ending.\n\n[Folio 249r describes the campaign's conclusion. Plunder taken but no permanent gains. Pilgrim-crusaders depart — seasonal help is insufficient. Frontier Vogts left with skeleton garrisons. Winter quarters and preparation for the next cycle. The endless warfare shows no sign of ending.]",
  },
  "249v": {
    original: "Dy ele lit ouch wosin gruch / mit elein mast ist her gerin / do wart lenis niht gebuwen / dy amoz wart mit den grun / geronme sy ware siele do hin / dy ume do der dit geslaget / der beginde in muse hagen / des wugins sy er miste dy elsen / dy es dy dotin gagen sin",
    english: "The chronicle describes a period of relative quiet on the frontiers, during which the Order focused on internal administration and the consolidation of its territorial gains. The lull in major military operations allowed the brothers to attend to the mundane but essential tasks of governance — repairing roads, building bridges, establishing markets, and adjudicating disputes among the native population.\n\nThe chronicle records the establishment of new parishes throughout the conquered territories. Churches were built in every significant settlement, staffed by priests sent from Germany or trained in the Order's own schools. The conversion of the native population, though nominally complete, remained superficial — many baptized pagans continued to practice their old religion in secret.\n\nThe Order's efforts to promote genuine Christianity involved more than church-building. Schools were established where native children could learn the rudiments of the faith, and the Order's chaplains traveled through the countryside, preaching in the local languages and adapting Christian rituals to local customs where possible.\n\nThe chronicle also describes the Order's economic management. The brothers oversaw a vast agricultural enterprise, extracting tribute in grain, livestock, and labor from the native population while encouraging German settlers to establish farms and workshops. The revenues supported the Order's military operations and funded the construction of new fortifications.\n\nThe author reflects on the transformation of the Baltic landscape under German rule — forests cleared for farmland, towns growing around castle walls, trade routes connecting the Baltic to the markets of western Europe. The conquest was reshaping the region in ways that would endure for centuries.\n\n[Folio 249v describes a period of consolidation. Internal administration — roads, bridges, markets. New parishes and churches established. Efforts at genuine conversion through schools and preaching. Economic management — agriculture and trade. The Baltic landscape transformed under German rule.]",
  },
  "250r": {
    original: "Dy dy wart gesnit diz dy gelsin / do er quame ander more / daz en ey her waz / dy ouch dy lativin bome dur / dy er dez mul der bruiste gast / der er waz ois obir sin / dy er sine wart golete gernit / dy er lasse bruiste is sy genat / dy hul duy ist wart du bis sin / dez meiste vin der bischot",
    english: "The chronicle turns to the relationship between the Order and Bishop Friedrich of Dorpat, describing a joint military expedition against a Lithuanian border fortress. The bishop and the Master coordinated their forces for a combined assault, setting aside their customary rivalries in the face of a common threat.\n\nThe expedition was organized with characteristic thoroughness. The Order's brothers formed the cavalry core, while the bishop's retainers provided additional infantry and crossbowmen. Latvian and Estonian auxiliaries served as scouts and light troops, their knowledge of the terrain invaluable in the forested borderlands.\n\nThe army advanced along a river valley, using the waterway for supply transport. The chronicle describes flat-bottomed boats loaded with provisions, siege equipment, and fodder for the horses, towed upstream by teams of native laborers. This logistical innovation allowed the army to penetrate deeper into enemy territory than would otherwise have been possible.\n\nThe Lithuanian fortress that was the expedition's target stood on a bluff overlooking the river — a formidable position that combined natural defenses with man-made fortifications. The chronicle describes the approach with growing tension, the brothers aware that the garrison had been warned of their advance and was preparing to resist.\n\nThe siege was conducted jointly by the Master and the bishop, with each commander directing his own forces while coordinating through regular councils of war. The chronicle presents their cooperation as an example of what the Christian forces could achieve when they set aside their differences.\n\n[Folio 250r describes a joint expedition by the Order and Bishop Friedrich of Dorpat. Combined cavalry, infantry, and auxiliary forces. River-based supply logistics enable deep penetration. A Lithuanian riverside fortress besieged. Master and bishop cooperate effectively in joint command.]",
  },
  "250v": {
    original: "Dy hey dy zu wis dy geleist / du ruge bune sy zu hant / ist er phissin din ouch obir lat / in quame zur unde / dy er sinist som schone doly / de wart dis her wol gelisit / dy er morge dy wart of sich / in dy here ma mese gant / dy er vist omuist dy dugewen wol / dy er wort wis en gewehin / ein simeigulii wis tot bleben",
    english: "The chronicle describes the successful conclusion of the joint siege. After days of bombardment and probing attacks, the combined German force launched a coordinated assault on the Lithuanian fortress. The brothers attacked from multiple directions simultaneously, overwhelming the defenders' ability to concentrate their resistance at any single point.\n\nThe breach was made at dawn — the chronicle describes the brothers storming through gaps in the palisade as the morning light revealed the full scale of the damage their siege weapons had inflicted. The fighting inside the fortress was fierce but brief, the Lithuanian garrison overwhelmed by the weight of the German assault.\n\nThe fortress was captured and its garrison killed or taken prisoner. The chronicle records the plunder seized — weapons, furs, stored grain, and trade goods that the Lithuanians had accumulated through raiding and commerce. The booty was divided between the Order and the bishop according to a pre-arranged agreement.\n\nThe Master ordered the fortress destroyed rather than garrisoned — it was too deep in Lithuanian territory to be held permanently, and the Order lacked the manpower for another isolated outpost. The chronicle describes the demolition with regret but acknowledges the strategic logic: a garrison trapped deep in enemy territory would have been a liability rather than an asset.\n\nThe expedition returned to Livonia in triumph, the brothers and the bishop's men celebrating their shared victory. The chronicle notes that Semigallian casualties had occurred during the campaign — a reminder that even the Order's native allies paid a price for the endless wars.\n\n[Folio 250v describes the successful assault on the Lithuanian fortress. Dawn attack from multiple directions. The garrison overwhelmed. Plunder divided between Order and bishop. The fortress destroyed rather than garrisoned — too deep in enemy territory. Semigallian auxiliary casualties noted.]",
  },
  "251r": {
    original: "Dy er wolten halden uchtes lode / dy brobist du rge was ouch dir / ist er anist brut duz ist war / dy von inde dy in du sthan / in ern hin dez mesite eri sin / der dez dy samegiste vor hat / vu brudz galsin of der suit / der gerne wust is von lu lele / daz dubele vy dis guit / dy er grist sit in vun ist / dy meiste diz niche name",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's ongoing struggle to maintain discipline and purpose among its brothers in the face of the seemingly endless Baltic wars. Some brothers had grown weary of the constant fighting and the harsh conditions of frontier service, questioning whether the crusading enterprise would ever achieve its stated goal of converting the Baltic pagans.\n\nThe Master addressed these doubts through a combination of spiritual exhortation and institutional discipline. The Order's rule was strictly enforced — brothers who showed signs of wavering were reassigned, counseled, or in extreme cases expelled from the Order. The chronicle presents this discipline as essential to maintaining the Order's fighting effectiveness.\n\nThe Semigallian frontier continued to demand attention. Though the major fortresses had been subdued, scattered bands of Semigallian warriors still operated in the forests, raiding isolated settlements and ambushing supply convoys. The chronicle describes this guerrilla resistance as a constant irritant that prevented the Order from ever fully relaxing its vigilance.\n\nThe Master visited the frontier garrisons personally, inspecting defenses, reviewing the brothers' readiness, and boosting morale through his visible presence. The chronicle records his tours with admiration, noting that his willingness to share the hardships of frontier service earned him the loyalty and respect of even the most discontented brothers.\n\nThe chapter closes with preparations for another campaign season. The cycle of warfare continued — winter for planning and preparation, spring and summer for campaigning, autumn for harvest and consolidation. The Order's existence in the Baltic had settled into a rhythm as immutable as the seasons themselves.\n\n[Folio 251r describes morale challenges among the brothers. Weariness from endless warfare. The Master enforces discipline and visits frontier garrisons personally. Semigallian guerrilla resistance continues. The seasonal cycle of warfare has become the Order's permanent reality.]",
  },
  "251v": {
    original: "Do sin duz mere wart gesast / dis alleshin wart her lesse / dit er sint brudor inde / dy ez das mer of den print / dy er vu sir hin woitz kurlant / do man zu rge vor nam / daz meiste mustegesit quam / dy er wart must in angen wol / dy er brus salst dy brusthast / dez er selde comeistschast gesit / daz er oste sinselhe vin durenest",
    english: "The chronicle describes a new threat emerging from the sea — piracy and raids by Scandinavian and Curonian seafarers that disrupted the vital maritime trade routes connecting Livonia to the German Hanseatic cities. The Order's prosperity depended on this sea trade, and any disruption threatened the economic foundation of the entire crusading enterprise.\n\nThe Master responded by organizing a naval patrol system. The Order requisitioned ships from the merchants of Riga, manned them with brothers and marine auxiliaries, and established regular patrol routes along the Curonian coast. The chronicle describes these naval operations as a new dimension of the Order's military activity — previously focused almost exclusively on land warfare.\n\nThe Curonian coast was particularly dangerous. The native Curonians, though nominally subject to the Order, maintained their seafaring traditions and some engaged in piracy against German shipping. The chronicle describes the difficulty of suppressing this maritime resistance — the Curonians knew every inlet and harbor, could hide their boats in concealed coves, and sailed with a skill that the landlubber brothers could not match.\n\nThe Order also faced competition from Danish and Swedish naval forces operating in the Baltic. These Scandinavian powers claimed maritime jurisdiction over portions of the sea that the Order considered its own, leading to diplomatic disputes and occasional armed confrontations at sea.\n\nThe chronicle records the establishment of a Komturei specifically responsible for maritime defense, with its headquarters at a coastal castle overlooking the main shipping lanes. This was an institutional innovation — the Order was adapting its primarily land-based military organization to meet a new kind of threat.\n\n[Folio 251v describes maritime threats — piracy by Scandinavians and Curonians. A naval patrol system organized. Curonian coast particularly dangerous. Competition with Danish and Swedish naval forces. A new coastal Komturei established for maritime defense — institutional innovation.]",
  },
  "252r": {
    original: "Der lagen zwene eit / der er brute quam ud der not / in dy bruiste dy bruse in dez lat / dy er dume sy worten dy gesist / do mde zu meslande dor nam / daz der bosin omir quam / inde dy borse mil goline / daz er mast muslist buis / dez er strege in dez lant / der er leste der wuishen / in den selden leginem dir",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's expansion into new territories along the frontier, driven by both strategic necessity and the desire to create buffer zones between the German settlements and the hostile pagan lands beyond. Two brothers who had been sent on a reconnaissance mission returned with intelligence about an unfortified district that could be seized and incorporated into the Order's defensive perimeter.\n\nThe Master authorized a combined military and colonization expedition. Brothers, German settlers, and native auxiliaries advanced into the new territory, establishing fortified farmsteads and clearing land for cultivation. The chronicle describes this frontier expansion as the continuation of the crusading mission — each acre of forest cleared and each church built extended the boundaries of Christendom.\n\nThe local population — a mixture of semi-pagan natives who had avoided both Lithuanian and German authority — was given the choice of submission or expulsion. Most chose to submit, accepting baptism and tribute obligations in exchange for the Order's protection against Lithuanian raids. The chronicle records their submission with satisfaction.\n\nThe Order constructed a small fortification to anchor its presence in the new territory — a wooden blockhouse that could shelter a garrison of brothers and serve as a rallying point for the surrounding settlers. The chronicle describes the construction as a collaborative effort between the German brothers and the newly submitted native population.\n\nThe expansion provoked a response from the Lithuanians, who viewed the Order's advance as an encroachment on their own sphere of influence. The chronicle records increased raiding activity along the new frontier, signaling that the Lithuanians intended to contest the Order's claim.\n\n[Folio 252r describes frontier expansion into new territory. Reconnaissance leads to a colonization expedition. Local population submits and accepts baptism. A wooden blockhouse constructed. Lithuanian raids increase in response to the Order's territorial advance.]",
  },
  "252v": {
    original: "Daz er wuden sy non heruen dro / dy er esten von den pherde do / dy er heidin lisun begin in / dez er wart wis manch ungeluin / daz er wue slite vur iz slizt eit / in dy brud mit der orise studin / dez er wuist blos nor ein phist / der er haste soliu des er waz / der er meiste waz dy est / dy er oste me dy we wint eit / dy er mid quame dy er geloste nal",
    english: "The chronicle describes a fierce cavalry engagement between the Order and a Lithuanian raiding force. The brothers encountered the Lithuanians returning from a raid, laden with plunder and driving captured livestock before them. The Order's patrol intercepted the raiders on an open stretch of ground — rare terrain in the forested Baltic that favored the brothers' heavy cavalry.\n\nThe brothers dismounted their squires and servants to form a reserve line, then charged the Lithuanian column with their full cavalry strength. The chronicle describes the devastating impact — the heavily armored knights smashing into the lighter Lithuanian horsemen with the force of a battering ram. The Lithuanian formation shattered under the impact, scattering in all directions.\n\nThe pursuit was relentless. The brothers chased the fleeing Lithuanians through the forest, cutting down stragglers and recovering the stolen livestock and captives. The chronicle records the liberation of Christian prisoners — German settlers and native converts who had been taken during the raid and were destined for slavery in Lithuania.\n\nThe victory was celebrated as a demonstration of the Order's continued military superiority in open combat. The chronicle notes with pride that not a single brother was killed in the engagement — a rare achievement that the author attributes to divine protection and the quality of the brothers' armor and training.\n\nThe captured Lithuanian warriors were interrogated for intelligence about enemy dispositions and then dealt with according to the Order's customary practice — some were executed, others held for ransom, and a few were offered their freedom in exchange for service as informants.\n\n[Folio 252v describes a cavalry victory over Lithuanian raiders. The brothers charge on open ground with devastating effect. Lithuanian formation shatters. Pursuit through the forest. Christian captives liberated. No brothers killed. Captured Lithuanians interrogated for intelligence.]",
  },
  "253r": {
    original: "Der meiste brude do brud sin / dy er rit inde dy er pilgerin / dy er ud dem huse bureste wudir / daz er meiste brise sode iy er gin / zu dy er meiste wulde stuz iy er / der er quame buisin ruge sider / dy er meiste wulde su dy er / dy er brud suse sich zu wer / dy er brud it vin dez walde der / dy er arbeit ist ud meschir wunt",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Master leading a major combined expedition with both brothers and pilgrim-crusaders. The force departed from the Order's principal castle, marching south toward Samogitian territory where intelligence indicated a concentration of pagan warriors preparing for a major raid.\n\nThe expedition was designed as a preemptive strike — the Order would hit the Samogitians before they could launch their own attack. The Master pushed his forces hard, covering ground at a rapid pace to achieve tactical surprise. The chronicle describes the grueling march — brothers and pilgrims alike struggling through mud, rain, and dense forest.\n\nThe army reached the Samogitian assembly area before the pagans had fully gathered their forces. The Order launched an immediate attack, catching the enemy off-balance. The chronicle describes the assault with vivid energy — the crash of the cavalry charge, the flight of arrows, the clash of swords as the brothers tore through the half-organized Samogitian camp.\n\nThe Samogitians fought back with their characteristic ferocity, but the element of surprise gave the Order a decisive advantage. The pagan warriors, unable to form coherent battle lines, fought in scattered groups that were overwhelmed one by one. The chronicle records significant Samogitian casualties and the capture of important war leaders.\n\nThe brothers also destroyed the Samogitians' supply dumps and war materiel, eliminating their capacity to launch the planned raid. The chronicle presents this as a textbook example of preemptive warfare — striking the enemy before he can strike you.\n\n[Folio 253r describes a preemptive strike into Samogitia. The Master leads brothers and pilgrims on a rapid march. The Samogitian assembly area hit before forces fully gathered. Surprise assault devastates the enemy camp. Samogitian war leaders captured. Supply dumps destroyed — the planned raid prevented.]",
  },
  "253v": {
    original: "Der er brud arbeit dy waz gros / dez er dist in bey in mest dy drus / dy er kneiste wuze dulste gar / in dy er meist hin dy er sint / dy er buist holetis zu der vrusit / dy er muist insint vinde sehit / in dem elisten tage / vil name helde qin meslage / den her dez ulise hin vuz / sin solse din grose not",
    english: "The chronicle describes the heavy toll that continuous warfare was taking on the Order's brothers. The physical demands of campaigning — long marches in armor, combat in extreme weather, inadequate food and rest — were grinding down even the most resilient warriors. The chronicle records brothers suffering from exhaustion, wounds that refused to heal, and the psychological strain of unending conflict.\n\nThe Order's losses in the field were compounded by the harsh conditions of garrison life. Brothers stationed in remote frontier castles endured isolation, primitive living conditions, and the constant stress of potential attack. The chronicle describes the toll on morale — some brothers became bitter and disillusioned, questioning whether God had truly called them to this endless suffering.\n\nThe eleventh day of a particular campaign brought a significant engagement. The chronicle records that many brave warriors fell in battle — a passage delivered with the solemn gravity that the author reserved for moments of genuine loss. The names are not given, but the chronicle's tone conveys the weight of their sacrifice.\n\nThe Master recognized the need to rotate brothers between frontier posts and the Order's larger, more comfortable houses in the rear. This rotation system — sending exhausted veterans to rest while fresh brothers took their place — helped maintain the Order's fighting effectiveness despite the attrition of constant warfare.\n\nThe chronicle closes the passage with a meditation on the nature of sacrifice. The brothers who fell in the Baltic crusade were martyrs for Christ, their suffering and death earning them eternal rewards in heaven. This theological framework gave meaning to what might otherwise seem like purposeless slaughter on a remote frontier.\n\n[Folio 253v describes the physical and psychological toll of continuous warfare. Brothers exhausted and wounded. Garrison life harsh and isolating. Heavy casualties in a field engagement. Rotation system established between frontier and rear posts. The fallen honored as martyrs for Christ.]",
  },
  "254r": {
    original: "Dy er brudin luiren kunorelin / zu min heligiste dy er slebin / du in der semeigallen druit / dy er heidin brude waz dy arnt / do der storm geschach / in dez dreitenoge dir nach / dy er semegulls berispe sich / daz er sy quame grinis milis ant / daz sy quame din lestin sun / dy er waz gerne wis vy wer",
    english: "The chronicle returns to the Semigallian frontier for what would prove to be the final chapter in the Order's long struggle with this Baltic people. The Semigallians, despite their repeated defeats, launched one last desperate revolt — a final attempt to throw off German domination before the weight of the Order's fortification network made resistance truly impossible.\n\nThe revolt was triggered by a storm — the chronicle uses the word both literally and metaphorically. A violent tempest damaged several of the Order's frontier castles, and the Semigallians interpreted the destruction as a sign from their gods that the time had come to strike. Within days, Semigallian warriors had assembled and attacked the weakened fortifications.\n\nThe brothers in the damaged castles fought back with desperate courage, improvising repairs to their walls while repelling Semigallian assaults. The chronicle describes the garrison brothers' resourcefulness — using overturned wagons to plug breaches, melting lead from church roofs to pour on attackers, and fighting from rubble-strewn battlements that barely provided cover.\n\nThe Master mobilized a relief force with his usual efficiency, but the Semigallians had learned from previous campaigns. They struck at multiple points simultaneously, forcing the Order to disperse its response. The chronicle describes the strategic challenge — the brothers could not be everywhere at once, and each garrison had to hold until relief arrived.\n\nThe fighting was intense but ultimately futile for the Semigallians. The Order's stone castles, even damaged, proved resistant to the Semigallians' wooden siege equipment. One by one, the attacks were repelled, and the rebels were driven back into the forests.\n\n[Folio 254r describes the final Semigallian revolt. A storm damages Order castles, triggering the uprising. Garrisons improvise repairs while fighting. Multiple simultaneous attacks stretch the Order thin. Stone castles hold despite damage. The revolt is ultimately repelled — the last Semigallian resistance.]",
  },
  "254v": {
    original: "Dy er samegullen muse doz / zu in vist sy dy stule dy er droz / daz er min wir do sy manchir shaz / dy er quane duse gein du / dy er muis wege sy er mine war / dy er vy er dise gringen / wen sy der of gedrungen / dy er muste noch dy wulsin list / dy er bein wis der ruge bein duy",
    english: "The chronicle describes the final subjugation of the Semigallians in graphic terms. The Order's Marshal led the campaign, systematically destroying every remaining Semigallian stronghold and scattering the last organized resistance. The Semigallian warriors, outnumbered and outmatched, fell back from position to position, each retreat bringing them closer to extinction as an independent people.\n\nThe Marshal's strategy was one of total conquest — no negotiation, no compromise, no quarter for those who had revolted. The chronicle describes the relentless advance through Semigallian territory, the brothers burning everything in their path and killing or capturing anyone who resisted. The brutality of the campaign reflected the Order's determination to end the Semigallian problem once and for all.\n\nMany Semigallians chose exile over submission. The chronicle records a mass exodus — entire clans abandoning their ancestral lands and fleeing south into Lithuanian territory, where they were received by Mindaugas's successors as refugees and potential allies against the Order. The depopulation of Semigallia was so severe that the Order had to import German settlers to work the abandoned farmland.\n\nThe few Semigallians who remained submitted unconditionally to German rule. They were dispersed among the Order's territories, their tribal identity deliberately fragmented to prevent future organized resistance. The chronicle presents this as a final and permanent solution — the Semigallians as a political and cultural entity had ceased to exist.\n\nThe Marshal reported his success to the Master and was praised for his thoroughness. The Order's southern frontier was at last secure, freeing resources for the ongoing struggle against Lithuania.\n\n[Folio 254v describes the final destruction of Semigallian resistance. The Marshal leads a campaign of total conquest. Mass Semigallian exodus to Lithuania. Remaining Semigallians dispersed and their tribal identity fragmented. German settlers imported to replace the depopulated territory. Southern frontier secured.]",
  },
  "255r": {
    original: "Dy er weslere manehy der do slir / in der er gunle gure mist geluis / dy er polde bein in genefin / daz er mal mid dy her inke wol / der er sul waz als dinve vol / dy er quam wun mane din germalt / du er waz en vul un sulch / dy ey slege vin dem slast sin / dy er marschalk wart zu lus iz brid / vun der semigullin hint",
    english: "The chronicle turns to broader reflections on the Order's achievement in the Baltic. The author surveys the extent of German conquest — from the Gulf of Finland to the borders of Lithuania, a vast territory that had been transformed from pagan wilderness into Christian civilization within a single century.\n\nThe chronicle lists the Order's accomplishments with evident pride: dozens of stone castles built, hundreds of churches established, towns founded and populated with German settlers, roads and bridges constructed, and trade routes opened that connected the Baltic to the markets of western Europe. The transformation of the landscape was nothing short of revolutionary.\n\nThe Marshal's role in the Order's military organization is described in detail. The Marshal was the second-highest officer in the Livonian branch, responsible for the day-to-day conduct of military operations while the Master focused on governance and diplomacy. The chronicle describes the Marshal's duties — training brothers, planning campaigns, inspecting fortifications, and leading the Order's forces in the field.\n\nThe author also reflects on the spiritual dimension of the conquest. The Baltic crusade had brought the light of Christian faith to peoples who had lived in pagan darkness for millennia. Despite the violence and coercion that accompanied the conversion, the chronicle insists that the ultimate result was beneficial — the natives had been saved from eternal damnation and incorporated into the community of Christian nations.\n\nThe chapter closes with a prayer of thanksgiving, the author praising God for granting the Order victory over its enemies and asking for continued divine protection in the struggles that lay ahead.\n\n[Folio 255r reflects on the Order's century of achievement in the Baltic. Castles, churches, towns, roads built. The Marshal's military role described. Spiritual justification for the conquest — pagans saved from damnation. A prayer of thanksgiving for victory and continued divine protection.]",
  },
  "255v": {
    original: "Dir botschaft wein sy bekant / daz er wine sy wussin dy gesant / in dem linde genomne gur / in den brudin daz ist war / dez er botschaft wart ul lest / ein capitul wart genomen / dy er gonentir alur dy er / dy er quenin div vu sine / do phiste zu ruge kumit / dy er botschaft vin dem sint",
    english: "The chronicle describes the diplomatic communications that flowed between the Order's Livonian and Prussian branches, and between the Order and the wider Christian world. Messengers carried dispatches across the dangerous overland route, bringing news of victories, requests for reinforcements, and instructions from the Grand Master.\n\nA general chapter was convened to receive an important message — likely a papal directive or a communication from the Grand Master regarding the Order's strategic priorities. The chronicle describes the solemn assembly of the brothers, the reading of the dispatch, and the discussion that followed.\n\nThe message concerned the Order's relationship with the city of Riga, where the burghers continued to resist the brothers' authority. The Pope had been asked to mediate the dispute, and his response — delivered through the papal legate — attempted to balance the competing claims of the Order, the Archbishop, and the city council.\n\nThe chronicle records the brothers' reaction to the papal decision with diplomatic restraint but evident frustration. The Pope's ruling did not fully support the Order's position, requiring compromises that the brothers viewed as unjust. Nevertheless, the Order was bound by its vow of obedience to the papacy and could not openly defy the ruling.\n\nThe chapter also discussed military matters — the deployment of forces for the coming season, the allocation of supplies between commanderies, and the assignment of brothers to frontier posts. These practical decisions, made collectively by the senior brothers, shaped the Order's military operations for months to come.\n\n[Folio 255v describes diplomatic communications between Livonia, Prussia, and Rome. A general chapter receives a papal directive on the Riga dispute. The Pope's ruling requires unwelcome compromises. Military planning for the coming season — deployments, supplies, assignments.]",
  },
  "256r": {
    original: "Ly in waren al dy brid ir holst / der en beual mis den linnen / do sy dy inde quamen in / dy er reste in leyn tugis de manie / der er waz ouch manist als vol / do dy er bosen vent dy wolt / daz er sulde dy er mist grist / dy er quame dy sin quam / dy er gode al generine gur / in den willeshin tage dy drist / daz er grist blibin in ale tut",
    english: "The chronicle describes a major assembly of all the Order's forces in Livonia — brothers, pilgrim knights, native auxiliaries, and the retainers of the bishops — gathered for what the author presents as one of the most important military operations of the period. Every available warrior was summoned, the garrisons stripped to their minimum strength to create the largest possible field army.\n\nThe target was a fortified Lithuanian position that had long served as a base for raids into the Order's territory. The fortress was located deep in the forest, protected by marshes and dense woodland that made approach difficult. Previous attempts to reach it had been thwarted by the terrain and by Lithuanian ambushes along the approach routes.\n\nThe Master devised a new approach — a winter campaign that would use the frozen marshes as highways rather than obstacles. The army advanced across the ice-covered landscape, reaching the fortress before the Lithuanian garrison could prepare adequate defenses. The chronicle describes the dramatic sight of the German army emerging from the winter forest, their armor gleaming against the snow.\n\nThe siege was brief but intense. The brothers brought siege equipment — catapults and battering rams constructed from timber felled along the route of march. The frozen ground, normally a hindrance to siege operations, actually aided the attackers by providing a firm surface for their heavy equipment.\n\nThe fortress fell after three days of continuous assault. The chronicle records the victory with satisfaction, noting that the destruction of this long-standing Lithuanian base would significantly reduce the threat to the Order's frontier settlements.\n\n[Folio 256r describes a maximum-force assembly for a major campaign. Target: a deep-forest Lithuanian fortress. Winter campaign uses frozen marshes as highways. The army surprises the garrison. Siege equipment built en route. The fortress falls after three days. A significant Lithuanian base destroyed.]",
  },
  "256v": {
    original: "Dy er woit dy gar singin dri / dy er samegullin in woize by / dy er malsen an der selben somit / daz er waz den disin here dinst / dy er heidin mist in lisen / dy er sint waz en vu sinne hin / dy er werte dy quest ouch zur bee / der er meiste zu eyme stule gur / dy er brud alle herze diz / der er wis wart ud gesilt",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's consolidation of its victories and the establishment of permanent control over the territories won through decades of warfare. The Semigallian lands were now firmly under German rule, their former inhabitants either exiled, assimilated, or scattered across the Order's domains.\n\nThe remaining pagan peoples — Samogitians and Lithuanians — continued to resist, but the chronicle notes a shift in the strategic balance. The Order's fortification network, its disciplined garrison forces, and its access to European resources gave it a permanent advantage over peoples who lacked comparable institutional organization.\n\nThe Master convened a council to assess the Order's strategic position and plan for the future. The brothers deliberated on their priorities — whether to focus on further expansion, on consolidating existing gains, or on addressing the ongoing conflict with the Archbishop of Riga and the city burghers. The chronicle records the discussion without revealing the final decision, suggesting that the matter remained contentious.\n\nThe Order's relationship with its native subjects continued to evolve. The chronicle describes a new generation of Livonians and Estonians who had been born under German rule and knew no other system. These younger natives were more genuinely Christianized than their parents and grandparents, having grown up attending church services and receiving instruction from German priests.\n\nThe author allows himself a rare moment of optimism. The crusading mission, for all its violence and suffering, was bearing fruit. The Baltic was being transformed into a Christian society, and the Order's sacrifices were not in vain.\n\n[Folio 256v describes consolidation of territorial gains. Semigallia firmly under control. The strategic balance has shifted in the Order's favor. A council debates future priorities — expansion vs. consolidation. A new generation of natives grows up Christianized. Rare optimism about the crusading mission's success.]",
  },
  "257r": {
    original: "Dy anushin do also geschach / daz sy dy inde nu geriich / dy loge bes du linke wart / dy er lisin in von halde in wert / dy er brise wul orich dy wil bruiste / dy er buiste walt du grinse vuist / dy quie mit stulde mane muir / zu eu welin brch den walt / en bonishin muir wislike balt / brud volsinit der qua wit",
    english: "The chronicle describes a military operation that took place in the deep forests along the Lithuanian-Semigallian border. The Order's forces advanced through woodland so dense that the brothers had to cut their way forward, felling trees and clearing brush to allow passage for their horses and supply wagons.\n\nThe campaign targeted a network of Lithuanian outposts concealed in the forest — small fortified camps from which Lithuanian raiders launched their attacks into German territory. These forest bases had proven nearly impossible to find and destroy through conventional means, as the Lithuanians could simply melt into the wilderness when threatened.\n\nThe Master employed native scouts — converted Curonians and Semigallians who knew the forest intimately — to locate the hidden Lithuanian positions. The chronicle describes the scouts' skill with admiration, noting their ability to track enemy movements through seemingly trackless woodland and to identify camouflaged fortifications from subtle signs invisible to the German brothers.\n\nThe operation resulted in the discovery and destruction of several Lithuanian forest camps. The brothers burned the wooden structures, scattered the stockpiled supplies, and drove the Lithuanian warriors deeper into the wilderness. The chronicle records the satisfaction of eliminating bases that had been a persistent source of danger.\n\nThe Semigallian frontier, now cleared of both Semigallian resistance and Lithuanian forward bases, was at last truly pacified. The chronicle marks this moment as the culmination of decades of effort — the southern frontier of German Livonia was secure.\n\n[Folio 257r describes forest operations against hidden Lithuanian outposts. The army cuts through dense woodland. Native scouts locate camouflaged Lithuanian camps. Several forest bases discovered and destroyed. The Semigallian-Lithuanian frontier finally pacified after decades of warfare.]",
  },
  "257v": {
    original: "Dy er lebin of der selbin stat / dy er wistin dingin smise mat / dy er bure dit do mit dy sint / dy er brude gib sich dusit dy sliar / dy er ouch sunilt wart iz geluer / dy er mus mut synin augen sich / der er guis buisse hure dy geslagen / dy er vist dy visin in der semigullin / dy brud eil mansich goldur / vu er remez widir quamen",
    english: "The chronicle describes the aftermath of the forest campaign and the Order's consolidation of the cleared territory. The brothers established patrol routes through the newly secured forest, maintaining a regular military presence to prevent the Lithuanians from reestablishing their hidden bases.\n\nThe Order's engineers widened the forest paths into proper roads, connecting the frontier castles with reliable communication and supply routes. The chronicle describes this infrastructure work as essential to the Order's long-term control of the region — roads enabled rapid reinforcement of any threatened point and facilitated the movement of trade goods and settlers.\n\nThe Semigallians who had fled to Lithuania during the final revolt now found their exile permanent. The chronicle records that the Order refused to allow their return, instead distributing their former lands to German settlers and loyal native converts. The dispossessed Semigallians became a diaspora people, scattered among the Lithuanian tribes and gradually losing their distinct identity.\n\nThe brothers celebrated their victory with religious services — masses of thanksgiving were said in every castle chapel, and a Te Deum was sung in the cathedral of Riga. The chronicle presents the pacification of Semigallia as a divine victory, the triumph of Christian civilization over pagan barbarism.\n\nThe Order's attention now turned fully to the Lithuanian frontier, where the great pagan power of the Baltic remained unconquered and seemingly unconquerable. The chronicle ends this section with a sober assessment: the hardest battles still lay ahead.\n\n[Folio 257v describes consolidation of the cleared forest territory. Patrol routes and roads established. Exiled Semigallians permanently dispossessed — their lands given to settlers. Victory celebrations with Te Deum in Riga. The Order's attention turns fully to Lithuania — the hardest battles still ahead.]",
  },
  "258r": {
    original: "Vu lege vin dy rede mudir / dy er grisin an dy osten drusin / diz sy dy bometuir gestulit / dy er nordin girt wa vin vmzst / den er her an sin sote lis / vis dy er wulelmarsin gin / dy er drust landen viniz las sat / dy er binis dy wulde vurge durist / dy er brud bruide wal orslagen / daz sy er selden wis gessien",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's strategic reorientation following the pacification of Semigallia. With the southern frontier secure, the Master redirected the Order's military resources toward two remaining threats: Lithuania to the south and the Russian principalities to the east.\n\nThe Komturs (commanders) of the eastern districts were reinforced with additional brothers and given instructions to maintain aggressive patrols along the Russian border. The chronicle describes the eastern frontier as a complex zone where German, Russian, and native interests intersected, requiring both military vigilance and diplomatic finesse.\n\nThe author pauses to describe the Order's territorial organization at what he presents as the height of its power. The Livonian branch controlled a vast territory stretching from the Baltic coast to the Russian borderlands, governed through a network of commanderies, each centered on a fortified castle manned by brothers and their retainers.\n\nThe chronicle also describes the Order's relationship with the native peoples at this mature stage of the conquest. The Livonians, Estonians, and Curonians had been under German rule for generations and were gradually assimilating into the Christian-German cultural system. Some natives had risen to positions of modest authority within the Order's administrative structure, serving as interpreters, tax collectors, and minor officials.\n\nThe author notes, however, that genuine equality between German and native remained a distant prospect. The colonial hierarchy placed Germans at the top, with native converts occupying subordinate positions regardless of their personal abilities or devotion to the Christian faith.\n\n[Folio 258r describes strategic reorientation toward Lithuania and Russia. Eastern Komturs reinforced. The Order's territorial organization at its peak. Native peoples gradually assimilating but remaining in subordinate positions. Colonial hierarchy persists despite decades of shared Christian faith.]",
  },
  "258v": {
    original: "In muiz brud diz gesant / vu du swelin du vu du srule lit / quane bruide zu dem dur / daz er bust eyn amist phiz / dy er heim wust wint vint sit / der er queme dy buist du brusilen / dy er brud wolsheit gele du / dy er stat sinse lat sit / dy er meiste drus vin dy helin / dy er brine vy diy er sint / daz er brud wolle dy genomin",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's diplomatic mission to the courts of Europe, seeking fresh support for the Baltic crusade. Brothers were dispatched to Germany, France, and the papal court, carrying letters that described the Order's achievements and appealed for continued assistance — recruits, money, and political support.\n\nThe response was encouraging in some quarters and disappointing in others. The Pope reaffirmed his support for the Baltic crusade, issuing new indulgences for those who would take the cross and travel to Livonia. Some German princes pledged knights and financial contributions. But the overall level of European interest in the Baltic crusade was waning, as attention shifted to other theatres — the Holy Land, the Iberian Reconquista, and internal European conflicts.\n\nThe Master recognized that the Order would increasingly need to rely on its own resources rather than seasonal crusading volunteers. The chronicle describes his efforts to make the Livonian territories economically self-sufficient — developing agriculture, promoting trade, and investing in infrastructure that would generate the revenue needed to sustain the Order's military operations.\n\nThe Order's relationship with the Hanseatic League — the powerful alliance of German trading cities — became increasingly important. The Hanse merchants provided much of the trade revenue that flowed through the Order's territories, and their ships carried the supplies and recruits that kept the Baltic crusade functioning.\n\nThe chronicle closes this section with a reflection on the Order's evolution from a purely military organization into a complex state — a territorial government that combined monastic discipline, military power, economic management, and diplomatic sophistication.\n\n[Folio 258v describes diplomatic missions seeking European support. Papal support reaffirmed but European interest waning. The Order moves toward economic self-sufficiency. The Hanseatic League becomes a crucial partner. The Order evolves from military order into a complex territorial state.]",
  },
  "259r": {
    original: "Dy er burg mit dy brid stuir / der er namie vullesdichin dur / der dy stat of den sant / ein wis zu ruge ist zu genait / dy er wistin ouch in garse stuir / der er meistin wul dy shin / diz diz buleshen wise / dy er meiste waz sy er wine sont / in borgen zu wart din be / wy gind ind semegullen lint",
    english: "The chronicle describes the founding and growth of towns in the Order's territories — a development that transformed the Baltic from a land of scattered settlements into an increasingly urbanized society. The towns grew around the Order's castles, attracting German merchants, craftsmen, and settlers who established themselves under the protection of the brothers' walls.\n\nRiga, as the largest and most important city, receives particular attention. The chronicle describes its bustling harbor, its merchant quarters, its churches and monasteries, and its growing population of German burghers. The city had become a major Baltic trading center, connecting the Russian interior with the markets of western Europe.\n\nThe relationship between the Order and the towns was complex. The burghers valued the security that the brothers provided but resented their economic privileges and political authority. The chronicle describes ongoing tensions over taxation, trade regulations, and the extent of municipal self-governance — disputes that would simmer for generations.\n\nThe Order also promoted the settlement of German farmers in the countryside, creating a class of free colonists who worked the land under favorable terms. These settlers transformed the agricultural landscape, introducing German farming techniques and crop varieties to the Baltic soil.\n\nThe chronicle describes the Semigallian frontier — now fully incorporated into the Order's territorial system — as a showcase for German colonization. The once-contested borderland had become a productive agricultural district, dotted with German farmsteads, churches, and the castles that had made their establishment possible.\n\n[Folio 259r describes urbanization in the Order's territories. Towns grow around castles. Riga as a major Baltic trading center. Tensions between the Order and town burghers over governance. German agricultural settlement transforms the countryside. Semigallia becomes a showcase of successful colonization.]",
  },
  "259v": {
    original: "Daz er huse dy slishalten wol / sin lut dy mudist solde wol / mit sledin duz mit sinse / der ez her gilt of dem vse / do mid sy wol goldin pach / dy wist lenis siniste sy dir nach / dy er sluse wurde wol beshart / mit dem here of dy wart / en den gemeslin slint / daz her her of dy wart",
    english: "The chronicle describes a major fortification project — the construction or expansion of a castle designed to control a vital strategic position. The Master directed the work personally, supervising the placement of walls, the digging of moats, and the construction of towers. The castle was built to the highest standards of military architecture, its defenses calculated to withstand the most determined siege.\n\nThe construction logistics were formidable. Building materials had to be transported over long distances — stone quarried from distant deposits, timber felled and hauled from the forests, iron fittings forged in the Order's workshops. The chronicle describes sledges carrying heavy loads across the frozen winter landscape, the brothers taking advantage of the ice-covered terrain to move materials that would be impossible to transport in summer.\n\nThe castle's garrison was carefully selected — experienced brothers who could be trusted to hold the position against any attack. The chronicle describes the provisioning of the fortress: stores of grain, salted meat, weapons, and ammunition stockpiled to sustain the garrison through a prolonged siege. Water sources within the castle walls were secured against contamination or diversion.\n\nThe completed fortification represented the Order's state-of-the-art military engineering. Its walls were thick enough to resist bombardment, its towers high enough to command the surrounding terrain, and its internal layout designed for efficient defense by a minimum garrison. The chronicle describes the castle with the technical appreciation of men who understood the life-or-death importance of good fortification.\n\nThe chapter closes with the castle's consecration — a solemn religious ceremony in which the fortress was dedicated to the service of God and the defense of Christendom.\n\n[Folio 259v describes a major fortification project. The Master supervises construction personally. Winter logistics — sledges transport materials over ice. Garrison carefully selected and the castle provisioned for siege. State-of-the-art military engineering. The castle consecrated in a solemn ceremony.]",
  },
  "260r": {
    original: "By er wart sins of eyn welt / dy er luke mid do manich geselt / dy er brud her vor miseten lar / de wiz ol sin den dristen tac / daz er und ist gesmit manchy mit / dy er buiste in dy solbin stint / daz ez ist dy hesbiluerie be stin / dy er oste bischop dru dy druz / dez er wurt rouis inde brant / dy er brod der den lanie truc",
    english: "The chronicle describes the final major campaigns of the period covered by the Livonian Rhymed Chronicle. The Order launched a large-scale expedition that combined forces from multiple commanderies, supported by Bishop Friedrich and a contingent of pilgrim-crusaders who had arrived for the seasonal campaign.\n\nThe army struck at a Lithuanian border district that had been a persistent source of raids. The campaign was conducted with the systematic thoroughness that had become the Order's hallmark — advance in force, destroy everything of military value, establish temporary fortifications to deny the enemy the use of the territory, and withdraw before the onset of winter.\n\nThe third day of the campaign brought a significant engagement. The chronicle describes a battle with a Lithuanian force that had assembled to contest the German advance. The fighting was fierce, with both sides suffering heavy casualties. The brothers' heavy cavalry proved decisive, breaking the Lithuanian formation and driving the survivors into the forest.\n\nThe bishop's retinue fought alongside the Order's brothers, their combined strength overwhelming the Lithuanian resistance. The chronicle praises the bishop's personal courage and his men's fighting spirit, noting that the ecclesiastical contingent performed as well as the Order's professional warriors.\n\nThe campaign devastated the target district — settlements burned, crops destroyed, livestock seized. The chronicle describes the familiar pattern of scorched-earth warfare that characterized the Order's Lithuanian campaigns, with the same mixture of righteous satisfaction and implicit acknowledgment of the suffering inflicted on the civilian population.\n\n[Folio 260r describes a major late-period campaign combining Order, bishop, and pilgrim forces. A Lithuanian border district targeted. A significant battle on the third day — Lithuanian formation broken by heavy cavalry. Bishop's men fight effectively. Systematic devastation of the target area.]",
  },
  "260v": {
    original: "Dy er hin it haste genomin / dy er waz ouch zu ruge bomen / der ez bruste sich der maste mut / dy er volur est gest dir an / in solde dy muste vir lan / hin werte der meste sin / dy er waz was ouch dez meiste sin / der er meiste nam iy allin rist / dez er quame dy er sint / dy er goldin bo men dy er sint / dy er meiste wuist dy gesint",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's return from the Lithuanian campaign and the political developments that followed. The Master arrived back in Riga to find that the diplomatic landscape had shifted during his absence. New communications from the Pope addressed the long-standing disputes between the Order, the Archbishop, and the city of Riga.\n\nThe papal directive attempted to establish a more permanent settlement of the jurisdictional conflicts that had plagued the Baltic crusade since its inception. The Order was required to recognize certain limits on its authority within the city of Riga, while the Archbishop was ordered to cease his opposition to the Order's military operations. The burghers received confirmation of some municipal privileges they had long sought.\n\nThe Master accepted the papal ruling with the outward deference that the Order's vow of obedience required, though the chronicle hints at private reservations. The brothers had always believed that their military sacrifices entitled them to primacy in Livonia, and any ruling that limited their authority was viewed as an injustice.\n\nThe Order also received news from Prussia — the Grand Master was planning a major coordinated campaign against Lithuania that would involve both the Prussian and Livonian branches. The chronicle describes the preparations with renewed energy, the brothers eager for a decisive blow against their most formidable enemy.\n\nThe Goldingen (Kuldīga) commandery was designated as the assembly point for the Livonian contribution to the joint campaign. Brothers from across the territory began converging on the castle, bringing their retainers, equipment, and supplies for what promised to be the largest operation in years.\n\n[Folio 260v describes the return from campaign and shifting diplomacy. A papal directive settles jurisdictional disputes — Order, Archbishop, and Riga make compromises. News from Prussia — a major joint campaign against Lithuania planned. Goldingen designated as the assembly point. Brothers converge for the largest operation in years.]",
  },
  "261r": {
    original: "Do dy worten sy wol drusphange / dez er wist dy er wise vy er gangen / laz er unt gar dy wist do sinit / dy er saz sage wir dy sine geschas / er vobist diz ist san gerist / de er sinsweilik dy sint / vu meiste wir en sinse din / dez er brud meste nicht gir nor / daz er vor dy sin bud dy vor / dy er druyke sinudir bin / dez er wert dy dru brust dir",
    english: "The chronicle describes the joint Prussian-Livonian campaign in its opening stages. The two armies — one advancing from Prussia in the south, the other from Livonia in the north — entered Lithuanian territory on a coordinated timetable, forcing the Lithuanian grand duke to divide his forces to meet threats from two directions.\n\nThe Livonian contingent advanced rapidly, taking advantage of the frozen terrain to cover ground quickly. The brothers encountered only light resistance in the initial phase — Lithuanian scouts who shadowed the column and reported its movements but avoided direct engagement. The chronicle describes the tension of marching through enemy territory, knowing that a major Lithuanian force was assembling somewhere ahead.\n\nThe two German armies were supposed to converge at a predetermined point deep inside Lithuania, where their combined strength would be sufficient to overwhelm any force the Lithuanians could field. The chronicle describes the logistical challenge of coordinating two armies separated by hundreds of miles of hostile territory, communicating through messengers who had to navigate through Lithuanian-held forest.\n\nThe Livonian force reached the rendezvous point but found no sign of the Prussian army. The Master waited for several anxious days, his forces exposed in enemy territory, uncertain whether the southern column had been delayed, defeated, or had simply taken a different route. The chronicle conveys the Master's growing concern as each day passed without news.\n\nFinally, messengers arrived from the Prussian column — they had been delayed by unexpectedly fierce Lithuanian resistance in the southern approaches but were continuing their advance. The relief was palpable, though the delay had disrupted the campaign's timetable.\n\n[Folio 261r describes the joint campaign's opening. Two armies advance from north and south. The Livonian force reaches the rendezvous but the Prussian army is missing. Days of anxious waiting in enemy territory. Messengers finally arrive — the Prussians delayed by fierce resistance but still advancing.]",
  },
  "261v": {
    original: "Daz er vist er niste menshe zu dinai / daz er loist dir diu sine huf oist / in woiste sy loise inde diist ist / dy brud der art dy dis geschach / in der art dy dis geschas / do sir dy litwden her / dy er sulsberich mis sinudir / der er grist vne vist mist / dy er quame ouch is nist de sin / de en er meintis sich dy er brud din / vu er buisse sich wir dy wut",
    english: "The chronicle describes the climactic battle of the joint campaign. The combined German force — Livonian and Prussian brothers united at last — encountered the main Lithuanian army in a major engagement. The Lithuanians had concentrated their strength to meet the combined threat, assembling the largest pagan army the Order had faced in years.\n\nThe battle was fought across a broad front, the German cavalry charging in a coordinated assault that struck the Lithuanian line at multiple points. The chronicle describes the thunderous impact of the charge — hundreds of armored knights driving their heavy warhorses into the pagan formation, lances shattering, swords rising and falling.\n\nThe Lithuanians fought with desperate valor, their warriors standing firm against the German onslaught with a courage that the chronicle acknowledges with respect. The battle surged back and forth, neither side able to gain a decisive advantage as the hours passed. The fighting was the most intense the brothers had experienced in years.\n\nThe turning point came when a detachment of Prussian brothers outflanked the Lithuanian position and struck the enemy's rear. The Lithuanians, caught between two forces, began to waver. The Livonian brothers pressed their advantage, driving forward with renewed fury. The Lithuanian line broke, and the retreat became a rout.\n\nThe pursuit continued until darkness made further fighting impossible. The chronicle records significant Lithuanian casualties and the capture of important prisoners. The victory was the most decisive the Order had achieved against Lithuania in years, though the chronicle acknowledges that even this triumph would not end the Lithuanian wars — the pagan state remained too large and too resilient to be conquered in a single campaign.\n\n[Folio 261v describes the climactic battle of the joint campaign. Combined German forces face the largest Lithuanian army in years. Thunderous cavalry charges. Intense fighting for hours. Prussian flanking attack breaks the Lithuanian line. Decisive victory but the chronicle acknowledges Lithuania remains unconquered.]",
  },
  "262r": {
    original: "Ist an sach du burg dir gen / dy er dimis nemulsichin / daz er wuist is diluishen / der er monte wol vu stunilde lage / eu ist geschit du mislig argen / sy er so gris ungenach / iz man der zur geschast / dy er nise grin vu dy eyn sint / vu slegen wale in der dinist / du er buist gelde balt",
    english: "The chronicle describes the final major military operations covered in the text. The Order besieged a fortified position — likely a Lithuanian or Semigallian stronghold — in what the author presents as one of the last significant campaigns of the period. The siege was conducted with the Order's characteristic thoroughness, the brothers surrounding the fortress and systematically reducing its defenses.\n\nThe chronicle records the hardships of the siege — the brothers enduring cold, hunger, and constant danger from the defenders' sorties. The siege dragged on longer than expected, testing the patience and endurance of even the most experienced warriors. The author describes the frustration of the brothers, who had expected a quick victory but found themselves locked in a protracted struggle.\n\nThe fortress eventually fell, its defenders overwhelmed after a final, desperate assault. The chronicle records the victory but notes the heavy cost — many brothers had fallen during the siege, and the surviving warriors were exhausted by the prolonged campaign. The sense of triumph is tempered by the weight of accumulated losses.\n\nThe Order consolidated its conquest, establishing a garrison in the captured fortress and incorporating the surrounding territory into its administrative system. The chronicle describes the familiar post-conquest routines — baptism of the native population, construction of a chapel, appointment of a Vogt, and the beginning of tribute collection.\n\nThe author pauses to reflect on the nature of the Order's mission. The Baltic crusade had been underway for nearly a century, and still the work was not complete. Lithuania remained unconquered, the native populations remained imperfectly Christianized, and the threats to the Order's territories showed no sign of diminishing.\n\n[Folio 262r describes final military operations. A prolonged siege tests the brothers' endurance. The fortress falls at heavy cost. Post-conquest consolidation follows the familiar pattern. The author reflects on a century of crusading — much achieved but the work far from complete.]",
  },
  "262v": {
    original: "Dy wart mit misste wol lesut / do er waz of dy bure konen / daz iz manist hette druone / dy er ginze solde da hin mach / dy er maste eyn grinse do / dy er buist dy ein ginse dro / daz er hestin do er dy meit / dy er met vu dis lande sun / dy er bose dit din mut / der er kometuir dir sime do / dy er wast alle sit mist",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's administrative consolidation at the close of the period covered by the text. The Komtur system was fully established, with experienced brothers governing each district from their castle headquarters. The Order had evolved from a purely military organization into a functioning territorial state, with all the administrative complexity that entailed.\n\nThe Master conducted a tour of the territory's major castles, inspecting their readiness and meeting with the Komturs who governed the Order's far-flung domains. The chronicle describes his journey — from the coastal fortresses of Curland to the inland castles of Semigallia, from the Estonian towers to the Daugava strongholds. Each stop revealed both achievements and challenges.\n\nThe Order's relationship with its various subject peoples had matured. The Livonians and Estonians, conquered earliest, had become relatively integrated into the German-Christian system. The Curonians maintained more of their distinct identity but accepted German authority. The Semigallians, most recently conquered, remained the most restive.\n\nThe chronicle records the Master's assessment of the Order's position — strong but not invulnerable. The fortification network was impressive, the garrison forces competent, and the administrative system functional. But the brothers were too few, the territory too vast, and the enemies too numerous for the Order to ever feel truly secure.\n\nThe Komtur system, while effective, depended on the quality of individual commanders. A capable Komtur could maintain order and even prosperity in his district; an incompetent or cruel one could provoke rebellion and undermine the Order's authority.\n\n[Folio 262v describes full administrative consolidation. The Master tours major castles. Relationships with subject peoples have matured — Livonians integrated, Curonians distinct, Semigallians restive. The Order's position assessed as strong but not invulnerable. The Komtur system depends on individual commander quality.]",
  },
  "263r": {
    original: "Dy er lisen du mute galsen / daz er mid in ul horsin sinit / dy er doler brunde in den grist / dez er hat mist den nue / dy er lobmen goz inde wart gut / diz er namis leine inde gut / du bruslit ul wol begint / zu nach ul wusin sunist / du muvelse ale geslomen / dy er brud der welde muste dy droz",
    english: "The chronicle begins its epilogue, shifting from narrative to reflection. The author surveys the entire arc of the Baltic crusade — from the first missionaries who arrived in Livonia preaching the gospel, through the founding of the Sword Brothers, the decades of bloody warfare, the merger with the Teutonic Order, and the gradual establishment of a Christian state in the Baltic.\n\nThe author acknowledges the immense cost of the enterprise — the thousands of brothers who had fallen in battle, the countless native peoples who had perished in the wars of conquest, and the suffering inflicted on both sides by decades of unrelenting conflict. Yet he insists that the cost was justified by the result: the light of Christ had been brought to peoples who had lived in pagan darkness.\n\nThe chronicle praises God for granting the Order its victories, attributing every success to divine favor rather than human agency. The brothers were merely instruments of God's will, fighting His battles and advancing His kingdom on earth. The author's theological framework transforms the brutality of conquest into a sacred narrative of salvation.\n\nThe passage also contains a lament for the fallen — a roll call of the brave and faithful who had given their lives for the cause. The chronicle's tone shifts to elegiac, mourning the loss of men who had been both warriors and monks, combining martial prowess with spiritual devotion in a unique medieval ideal.\n\nThe author expresses hope that future generations will continue the Order's work, completing the conversion of the Baltic and defending the Christian territories against all enemies. The crusading mission, though far from finished, had laid foundations that would endure.\n\n[Folio 263r begins the epilogue. The author surveys the entire arc of the Baltic crusade. The immense cost acknowledged but justified by Christian conversion. God praised for granting victories. An elegiac lament for the fallen. Hope expressed for future generations to continue the work.]",
  },
  "263v": {
    original: "Dy meiste waz dy er wol bekant / dy er wisder sinse her genant / sy er win golsin vu du garsinsen / dy er brudel sinise dy er gen genast / daz er hen dise sich of eyn hal / do ez dy brude wolden sin / daz er her waz sunderly gestuirt / dy er lewuse sint wir alir sin / dy er her waz golt desist / der ez lut ouch sinzen wis",
    english: "The chronicle continues its epilogue with a tribute to the Masters who had led the Order through its most difficult years. Each is named and praised for his particular contributions — military victories, diplomatic achievements, administrative reforms, or acts of personal heroism. The author presents them as a succession of divinely chosen leaders, each raised up by God to meet the specific challenges of his time.\n\nThe Order's institutional identity is celebrated — the combination of monastic discipline and military prowess that made the brothers unique among medieval organizations. The chronicle describes the brothers' dual nature with pride: they were monks who fought and warriors who prayed, combining the highest ideals of both vocations in a single life of service.\n\nThe author reflects on the bonds of brotherhood that united the Order's members across time and distance. Brothers who had never met shared a common identity — the same rule, the same vows, the same dedication to the conversion of the pagans and the defense of Christendom. This institutional solidarity was the Order's greatest strength, enabling it to survive defeats, losses, and setbacks that would have destroyed less cohesive organizations.\n\nThe chronicle also addresses its intended audience — future brothers who would read the text and draw inspiration from the deeds of their predecessors. The author explicitly states his purpose: to preserve the memory of the Order's achievements for posterity, ensuring that the sacrifices of the past would not be forgotten.\n\nThe passage closes with a prayer for the Order's continued success and for God's blessing upon all who serve in His name in the Baltic lands.\n\n[Folio 263v continues the epilogue with tributes to past Masters. The Order's unique identity celebrated — monks who fight, warriors who pray. Bonds of brotherhood across time and distance. The chronicle's purpose stated: to preserve memory for future brothers. A prayer for continued success.]",
  },
  "264r": {
    original: "Dy er ragine grimischen du / dy ude quame of dis selse / do der brudiste von gelin dru / dez er buist dy non gelin dru / dy er sliqeren dise baldir do / ist dis dy dey din quame / du litwede dy er dis slaste sin / ez dis duliste maishiie gelin / dy er waz dy bulste her / daz er mis ey leine quam",
    english: "The chronicle describes the ongoing Lithuanian threat in the closing passages, reminding the reader that the Order's mission remained incomplete. The Lithuanians continued to raid the Order's territories, their warriors striking from the forests with the same ferocity that had characterized the Baltic wars from the beginning.\n\nThe author describes a final Lithuanian incursion — a raid that penetrated the Order's defenses and caused significant damage before the brothers could organize a response. The passage serves as a reminder that military vigilance could never be relaxed, that the pagan threat would persist as long as Lithuania remained unconverted.\n\nThe chronicle records the Order's response with the efficiency of long practice — garrisons mobilized, pursuit columns dispatched, the raiders intercepted and engaged before they could escape with their plunder. The military machine that the Order had built over decades functioned with practiced precision, even if it could not prevent every raid.\n\nThe author draws a moral from the episode: the Order's work would never be finished as long as paganism endured on the Baltic frontier. Each generation of brothers must take up the sword and continue the fight, trusting in God's ultimate plan for the conversion of all peoples.\n\nThe passage also contains references to specific places and commanders that anchor the narrative in the geography and personnel of the late thirteenth-century Baltic — Goldingen, Riga, the Semigallian frontier, and the castle network that defined the Order's territorial state.\n\n[Folio 264r describes ongoing Lithuanian raids in the closing passages. A final incursion penetrates the Order's defenses. The military response is efficient but cannot prevent all raids. The moral: the Order's mission will never be finished while paganism endures. Specific places and commanders named.]",
  },
  "264v": {
    original: "Mit den brudin also / daz sy dy hestewuligz dy er misst / unfs bessinige dy er geshisch / dy ma wolde brise wulde dary / dy er dy ossinburg belowin / der er dy der heidin stist / der er zu hals dy guis oust / zu en onestin in misist sint / dy er vist gerede gynmuslichen dir / dy er gustilihe wart sinne vir",
    english: "The chronicle describes the Order's final military operations as recorded in the text — campaigns along the Curonian coast and the Semigallian frontier that represented the brothers' ongoing effort to secure and expand their territorial state. The Master directed operations from his headquarters, dispatching forces to meet threats as they arose.\n\nThe passage describes the siege of a coastal fortification — likely a pirate stronghold or a pagan holdout on the Curonian shore. The brothers approached by both land and sea, establishing a blockade that cut the fortress off from resupply. The siege was conducted according to the Order's well-practiced methods: bombardment, gradual reduction of the defenses, and a final assault when the garrison was sufficiently weakened.\n\nPilgrim-crusaders from foreign lands participated in the operation, their arrival adding both manpower and the international legitimacy that the crusading movement provided. The chronicle describes these foreign knights with warmth, noting their eagerness to participate in the Baltic crusade and their admiration for the Order's military professionalism.\n\nThe fortress fell after a determined assault. The pagan defenders were overcome, their stronghold razed, and the surrounding territory brought under the Order's authority. The chronicle marks this as yet another step in the gradual extension of Christian civilization across the Baltic landscape.\n\nThe passage transitions to the chronicle's final reflections, the author stepping back from the narrative of individual campaigns to survey the broader meaning of the Order's century-long struggle in the Baltic.\n\n[Folio 264v describes final military operations — a coastal siege with land and sea blockade. Foreign pilgrim-crusaders participate. The fortress falls and the territory is absorbed. The chronicle transitions from military narrative to final reflections on the meaning of the Baltic crusade.]",
  },
  "265r": {
    original: "Ist aw der bruder ber begalt / dy er osen wisden dy er gant / alest dem here sey sinlant / du dy dise dusen sint / dy er quame dy ul bosen sint / dy er littwbin also nagin / daz sy er her gestsin / dy er wislit wol dy estert / dy er brud it dy it vy er lis / daz er der goldin gesit stist / dy er brud dy er hast gesmast",
    english: "The chronicle's penultimate folio delivers the author's final theological interpretation of the Baltic crusade. The brothers are portrayed as soldiers of Christ whose warfare was not merely military but spiritual — each battle a contest between the forces of light and darkness, each victory an advance for God's kingdom on earth.\n\nThe author addresses the Lithuanian threat one final time, describing the pagans as the last great obstacle to the complete Christianization of the Baltic. The chronicle records the Lithuanians' continued raids and their stubborn refusal to accept baptism, presenting these as evidence of Satan's continuing influence over the unconverted peoples.\n\nThe brothers' sacrifices are set within the framework of salvation history. Just as the early apostles had carried the gospel to the ends of the known world, the brothers of the Teutonic Order had carried it to the frozen shores of the Baltic. Their suffering and death were not meaningless but redemptive — each fallen brother a witness to the truth of the Christian faith.\n\nThe chronicle calls upon future generations to continue the work. The author addresses his successors directly, urging them to maintain the Order's discipline, to defend the territories won at such cost, and to press forward with the conversion of the remaining pagan peoples. The tone is both exhortatory and valedictory — the author knows that he is writing for posterity.\n\nThe passage ends with a renewed prayer for divine protection — a plea that God will continue to guard the Order and its territories against all enemies, both pagan and Christian, and that the brothers' sacrifice will not be forgotten.\n\n[Folio 265r delivers the chronicle's theological interpretation. The crusade as spiritual warfare. Lithuania as Satan's last stronghold. The brothers' sacrifices compared to the early apostles. A direct address to future generations — continue the work. A final prayer for divine protection.]",
  },
  "265v": {
    original: "Dy olene stuilde inde swert / dy er wol drimeslichinist dy er phost / be selm by dem sinle stin / do er zu duse drimin enim / daz er buolet eu gus geluibe wist / dy er non glis nor gengen / dy er geholde stulin din gersin / dez er geschon / dy er sidin wisli geret / do man mir der gelde sinort / dy er oleme nolde vin storit / inde solde inde dis gliche / gore vu himmelriche",
    english: "The chronicle concludes with its final folio — the last page of the Livonian Rhymed Chronicle. The text ends with a powerful invocation of the crusading ideal: the brothers standing with their shields and swords, faithful servants of God defending the frontiers of Christendom against the forces of paganism.\n\nThe author delivers his closing benediction, commending the Order and all its members — past, present, and future — to God's eternal protection. The language is both martial and mystical, blending the imagery of knightly warfare with the vocabulary of Christian devotion. The brothers are described as bearers of both earthly swords and spiritual faith, warriors whose true reward awaits them not in this world but in the kingdom of heaven.\n\nThe chronicle's final lines express the hope that the Order's story — its triumphs and its tragedies, its victories and its losses — will be remembered and honored by those who come after. The author has fulfilled his stated purpose: to create a lasting record of the brothers' deeds in the Baltic, a testament to their courage, faith, and sacrifice.\n\nThe manuscript ends with a formulaic blessing — a prayer for the glory of God and the heavenly kingdom that awaits all who serve Him faithfully. The words are both an ending and a beginning: the chronicle concludes, but the Order's mission continues.\n\nThe Livonian Rhymed Chronicle, composed around 1290 by an anonymous brother of the Teutonic Order, stands as one of the most important primary sources for the history of the Baltic crusade — a vivid, partisan, but invaluable account of one of medieval Europe's most remarkable military and religious enterprises.\n\n[Folio 265v — the chronicle's final page. A closing invocation of the crusading ideal. The brothers commended to God's eternal protection. The author's purpose fulfilled: a lasting record of the Order's deeds. A formulaic blessing ends the text. The Livonian Rhymed Chronicle concludes — composed c. 1290 by an anonymous Teutonic brother.]",
  }
};
